<FIRST>r i PM-PandaDies     01-31 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panda Dies,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ying-Ying, Mexico's Prolific Panda Mother, Dead At Age 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The giant panda Ying-Ying, the female of the
pair that made Mexico's panda breeding program the most successful
outside China, has died of unknown causes _ possibly a broken heart
_ at age 14.
   Ying-Ying, who died late Sunday, had been depressed since
October, about three months after Pe-Pe, her mate, died of cancer,
said Maria Elena Hoyo, director of the Chapultepec Zoo.
   She said Ying-Ying had been ill for several days.
   ``We don't what she died of,'' Ms. Hoyo said. ``The autopsy
didn't determine the cause'' but zoo officials hope laboratory tests
will determine the cause.
   She said Ying-Ying had until Pe-Pe's death spent every day with
the panda China sent as a gift in 1975, when Ying-Ying was 11 months
old.
   ``She didn't want to live without Pe-Pe,'' Ms. Hoyo said. ``She
was very much in love with Pe-Pe. She didn't want to go out into the
garden. She ate but not as well as she used to.
   ``She wasn't as aggressive, as sure of herself. Before she
wouldn't let you touch her and recently it didn't matter to her.''
   Giant pandas are an endangered species and only about 18 are in
captivity outside China. The animals generally have a life
expectancy of about 20 years.
   Ying-Ying, who was nearly 15, gave birth to seven offspring after
natural mating with Pe-Pe. Four survived. Ying-Ying accidentally
rolled onto the first cub eight days after its birth in 1980,
crushing it, and one each of two sets of twins died.
   Tohui, the oldest of the four surviving offspring, set off panda
mania when she was born July 21, 1981, and is the zoo's hope for
continuing to produce more pandas. In December, the London Zoo sent
its 16-year-old male panda to Mexico in hopes the two would mate.
   Ms. Hoyo said Ying-Ying's body, like Pe-Pe's, will be stuffed and
put on display.
</TEXT>
