<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg-Hedda     01-31 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg-Hedda,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nussbaum Could Become Women's Advocate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Steinberg, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum has become a powerful symbol of
family violence and could become a powerful advocate for other
battered women, says the psychiatrist who is nurturing her recovery.
   Tragedy put Ms. Nussbaum into her role, portrayed by prosecutors
as a brainwashed victim of brutality and by Joel Steinberg's defense
as a fraud who killed the little girl they illegally adopted and
raised until her death at age 6.
   The once-pretty woman bared her scarred face and psyche to
television viewers during testimony that unraveled an all-too-common
story of domestic violence. A state jury Monday convicted Steinberg
of manslaughter.
   When Ms. Nussbaum, a 46-year-old former children's book editor
for Random House, was arrested with Steinberg after little Lisa
Steinberg's death, she had a black eye, broken nose, nine fractured
ribs, split lip, cauliflower ear, and a leg so severely ulcerated
that doctors called the injury life-threatening.
   Charges against her were dropped when prosecutors determined she
was too physically and mentally incapacitated to be responsible for
the girl's death. Ms. Nussbaum agreed to become the key prosecution
witness.
   Steinberg, 47, was charged with beating Lisa on the night of Nov.
1, 1987. The death, three days later, of a child from an affluent,
well-educated household, shocked many and became a nationwide symbol
of family violence as a problem that cuts across social strata.
   Ms. Nussbaum's testimony described a 12-year relationship in
which she was beaten, brainwashed and subjected to other bizarre
punishments for transgressions imagined by Steinberg.
   Slowly, deliberately, Ms. Nussbaum told how she came to see
Steinberg as a ``godlike figure'' _ asking his permission to eat,
obeying his orders to sleep on the floor or sit in a tub of cold
water.
   Jurors saw handwritten pages in which Ms. Nussbaum vowed to care
about Steinberg's hair, clothes, work, problems, diet, future, teeth
and other concerns. In another paper, she wrote 10 times that
``anger is destructive'' and that ``self-defense is regressive.''
   Her psychiatrist, Samuel Klagsbrun, has said Ms. Nussbaum won't
be ready to leave the Four Winds hospital in Katonah, north of New
York, for at least two months. But while she hasn't made definite
plans, Klagsbrun said he wouldn't be surprised to see Ms. Nussbaum
become an advocate for other battered women.
   ``She feels an obligation at this point to be helpful to others _
in helping people stand up and fight for themselves and regain a
level of self-respect,'' said Klagsbrun. ``She's very conscious of
the responsibility she now has to take a horrible part of her life
and make it useful for other women as well as for herself, her own
healing.''
   ``She's articulate and intelligent. She has the capacity to
relate and be available to other people'' _ and already has helped
other patients during her hospitalization, said Klagsbrun.
   ``Her impact on other people who have experienced battering has
been enormous,'' he said. ``She has allowed some people to reveal
more than they were prepared to do ... to feel they can assert
themselves in society and stand up to evil. People have said things
along those lines to her.''
   During seven days of testimony in December, Ms. Nussbaum said
that Steinberg told her in bed, after they had free-based cocaine
and while Lisa lay comatose on their bathroom floor, that he had
``knocked Lisa down and she didn't want to get up.''
   The defense charged that Ms. Nussbaum was jealous of Steinberg's
attention toward Lisa and inflicted the fatal injuries.
   Prosecutors said Ms. Nussbaum, who lost her job when she
frequently missed work because of injuries, suffered from the
battered spouse syndrome and was herself too much a victim herself
to have hurt, or helped, the child.
</TEXT>
