<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Romania     01-31 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Romania,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Protests ``Manhandling'' of Its Ambassador To Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian police ``manhandled'' Britain's ambassador
to that country as they prevented him from visiting a government
critic who was under house arrest, the Foreign Office said.
   The Foreign Office on Monday summoned Romania's ambassador, Stan
Soare, to demand an apology for the incident in Cluj on Friday, when
Ambassador Hugh Arbuthnott tried to deliver a letter to historian
Doina Cornea.
   The ambassador, accompanied by his wife Vanessa, was physically
stopped by police at the garden gate of Mrs. Cornea's home and the
letter was snatched from his grasp, the Foreign Office said.
   ``The ambassador was prevented from meeting, and was manhandled
by the militiamen,'' a Foreign Office spokesman said. He spoke on
condition of not being identified.
   Mrs. Cornea has been under house arrest since last fall, when she
wrote a letter to the Western press protesting that Communist
Romania, under a policy of President Nicolae Ceausescu, was
deliberately destroying villages and farming communities.
   Later Friday, British diplomat Alan Clark was summoned to the
Foreign Ministry in Bucharest, which protested that Arbuthnott
``tried to go down a one-way street,'' and had ``mistreated and
insulted'' the police.
   Clark rejected the Romanian version and ``a somewhat heated
exchange ensued,'' the Foreign Office said.
</TEXT>
