<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     01-31 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rain Man' Continues Dominance at Nation's Theaters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Rain Man'' was moviegoers' favorite for the
fifth-straight weekend, but another brotherly tale, ``Twins,''
dropped to fourth after being runnerup for four-consecutive weeks.
   ``Rain Man,'' starring Dustin Hoffman as an autistic savant on
the road with his manipulative brother Tom Cruise, grossed $6.8
million at the nation's box offices last weekend, Exhibitor
Relations Co. said Monday.
   It was the second dose of good news this weekend for ``Rain
Man,'' which collected two top Golden Globes: for best dramatic
movie and best dramatic actor for Hoffman.
   ``Rain Man'' was followed by ``Three Fugitives,'' a new comedy
starring Nick Nolte and Martin Short as outlaws trying a raise a
young girl. The movie brought in $6.4 million.
   In third was ``Beaches,'' a poignant drama featuring Bette Midler
and Barbara Hershey as best friends, with $4.9 million.
   ``Twins,'' with Danny DeVito and Arnold Schwarzenegger playing
brothers separated at birth, was next with $4.8 million. The movie
had been finished second for the past four weeks and first the
previous two weeks.
   Next was by the civil rights chronicle ``Mississippi Burning,''
which grossed $3.5 million.
   In sixth place was ``Working Girl,'' the Wall Street
rags-to-riches tale, with sales of $3 million. ``Working Girl,''
starring Melanie Griffith, received four trophies at the Golden
Globes, including best comic motion picture and best comic actress
for Griffith.
   The detective spoof ``The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police
Squad!'' finished in seventh with $2.9 million.
   ``The Accidental Tourist,'' a film adaptation of the celebrated
Anne Tyler novel, claimed eighth place with $2.6 million. In ninth
was the new Burt Reynolds drama ``Physical Evidence,'' with receipts
of $1.8 million. The comedy ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels'' finished
10th with $1.6 million.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Rain Man,'' United Artists, $6.8 million, 1,563 screens,
$4,370 per screen, $88.8 million, seven weeks.
   2. ``Three Fugitives,'' Disney, $6.4 million, 1,153 screens,
$5,581 per screen, $6.4 million, one week.
   3. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $4.9 million, 1,097 screens, $4,503 per
screen, $20.1 million, six weeks.
   4. ``Twins,'' Universal, $4.8 million, 1,659 screens, $2,895 per
screen, $86.5 million, eight weeks.
   5. ``Mississippi Burning,'' Orion, $3.5 million, 1,058 screens,
$3,350 per screen, $14.7 million, eight weeks.
   6. ``Working Girl,'' 20th Century Fox, $3 million, 1,149 screens,
$2,615 per screen, $38.2 million, six weeks.
   7. ``The Naked Gun,'' Paramount, $2.9 million, 1,501 screens,
$1,910 per screen, $68.4 million, nine weeks.
   8. ``The Accidental Tourist,'' Warner Bros., $2.6 million, 926
screens, $2,766 per screen, $21.8 million, six weeks.
   9. ``Physical Evidence,'' Columbia, $1.8 million, 691 screens,
$2,572 per screen, $1.8 million, one week.
   10. ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels,'' Orion, $1.6 million, 1,313
screens, $1,247 per screen, $36.4 million, seven weeks.
</TEXT>
