<FIRST>r a PM-People-Barenboim     01-31 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Barenboim,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Paris Orchestra Named Chicago Symphony Music Director</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Georg Solti is passing the baton as Chicago
Symphony music director to Daniel Barenboim, who an orchestra member
characterized as a first-string quarterback who ``can lead us to the
Super Bowl.''
   The 46-year-old Argentine-born Israeli conductor and pianist was
named Monday to succeed Solti, who is retiring at the end of next
season after two decades as the orchestra's conductor.
   Barenboim, fired recently from the newly formed Opera-Bastille in
a power struggle, will continue as director of the Paris Orchestra,
a position he has held for 15 years, said Chicago Symphony
spokeswoman Susan Dewey.
   He and Solti will work together until Solti's retirement.
   ``Now we have two first-string quarterbacks, and either one can
lead us to the Super Bowl,'' said timpanist Donald Koss, chairman of
the Orchestra Members' Committee. ``We've played for maestro
Barenboim many times and know he is truly a world-class conductor,
absolutely first-rate.''
   ``In choosing Daniel Barenboim, I'm completely confident that we
have made the best possible choice for our orchestra,'' Orchestral
Association Chairman Richard L. Thomas said.
   ``With his infectious enthusiasm, his commitment to excellence
and his exceptional credentials, I have no doubt that he will build
on his previous accomplishments as well as those of the orchestra.''
   The 76-year-old Hungarian-born Solti, who has won a record-high
26 Grammys and has been Chicago music director since 1969, said he
had the ``health and energy'' to continue here, but felt it was
important to hand the baton over to someone younger.
   ``It is with the greatest pleasure that I welcome the appointment
of Daniel Barenboim as my successor,'' said Solti, who also was
Barenboim's predecessor at the Paris Orchestra. ``I have known him
and have been closely involved in his development as a conductor for
many years and he is my first choice.''
   Barenboim will be the ninth music director of the Chicago
Symphony, which was founded in 1891. He will begin his tenure Sept.
1, 1991.
   ``The past 20 years of music making with the orchestra as a guest
conductor have taught me to admire not only its unique qualities but
also its members' devotion to music,'' Barenboim said from Paris.
   Terms of the three-year contract call for Barenboim to conduct at
least 12 weeks of concerts in Chicago each season. He also will lead
all major tours for three to four weeks each year, Thomas said. The
salary was not announced.
</TEXT>
