<FIRST>r i PM-BusDrivers-Manners     01-31 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Drivers-Manners,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Urban Bus Company Sends Drivers To Charm School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ATHENS, Greece _ In a bid to control hot Mediterranean tempers
and teach them a smattering of English for the benefit of tourists,
Athens bus drivers are being sent to charm school.
   The $4.3 million program is aimed at improving the image of the
capital's public transportation system, which faces stiff
competition from taxis whose cost is among the cheapest in the world.
   Classes such as ``Driver and Communication with the Public'' and
``English for Drivers'' are part of the 15-day courses for the staff
of the semi-private Urban Transportation Company.
   ``The classes will help the driver control his Mediterranean
temperament ... but passengers must also understand that it's not
the driver's fault when the bus is late,'' said Andreas Kolas, a
spokesman for the Union of Bus Drivers.
   Quarrels often break out between bus drivers and passengers irked
by waiting for buses or when riders insist on getting off where
there is no bus stop.
   Because of the chaotic state of public transportation _ bus
routes and timetables are rarely available _ tourists often take
taxis, which cost about $2 for a three-mile ride. The bus fare is 20
cents.
   Kolas said drivers' manners aren't helped by the aggravation of
navigating the capital's notoriously congested streets.
   According to the transit company's chairman, Vassilis Xeomeritis,
about 3,500 of the 5,000 bus drivers are very experienced but
``older people with almost no education.
   ``Our drivers could use some retraining ... they must understand
that passengers are our customers and that it's the driver's duty to
serve the public,'' Xenomeritis said.
   The corporation's 1,200 buses cover the whole of Athens _ a
120-square-mile area. With only one subway line crossing the city,
more than 70 percent of Athenians commute by bus daily.
   A bus driver who wouldn't let his name be used said the public
should also ``learn how to behave'' and use the transportation
system properly.
   ``Passengers sometimes ask us unbelievable things,'' he said.
``We try to explain something to them and they are already so upset
that they turn around and swear at us.''
   About 1,500 drivers are scheduled for the course in 1989. The
rest will take it in the next couple of years, said Christos
Halazias, a transportation company spokesman.
   The corporation received almost half its financial backing for
the training program from the European Economic Community, he said.
</TEXT>
