<FIRST>r a AM-HaitianRefugees     01-31 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitian Refugees,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearly 150 Haitians Interdicted Off Miami Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 Haitian refugees crammed aboard a sailboat
were detained Monday after they were intercepted eight miles off the
entrance to the Port of Miami, the first such boatload this year,
authorities said.
   The group reportedly included two pregnant women and a child,
said U.S. Coast Guard spokesman Gary Starks.
   A tugboat spotted the wood-hulled vessel around 2:30 p.m. and the
Coast Guard immediately dispatched a patrol boat to the scene, just
east of Government Cut on the southern end of Miami Beach.
   The 40-foot sailboat apparently was not in jeopardy of capsizing,
the Coast Guard said, and two Haitian males suffering from severe
dehydration were airlifted late Monday to Jackson Memorial Hospital
for treatment.
   Late Monday, 149 Haitian refugees and one from the Dominican
Republic wer transferred to two Coast Guard cutters and were being
interviewed by immigration officials.
   The interviews to determine whether they would be brought ashore
or returned to their homeland would be made once all the interviews
were completed, the Coast Guard said.
</TEXT>
