<HEAD>Irish Group Urges Woman Grand Marshal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman will be grand marshal of this year's St.
Patrick's Day parade for the first time in its 226-year history.
   Broadcaster Dorothy Hayden Cudahy and Mary Holt Moore, an
activist for the independence of Northern Ireland, were selected
Monday night as the only nominees by the parade committee, said
Martin Galvin, spokesman for the Irish Northern Aid Committee.
   Representatives of Irish-American groups running the March 17
parade were to elect the grand marshal today. Both nominees have run
before.
   ``It's long overdue to have a woman grand marshal,'' Galvin said.
``Each of these candidates have done great service to the Irish
community. They would do great honor to the parade and the Irish
community.''
