<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmingHeresy Bjt   01-31 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farming Heresy, Bjt,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Plow That Broke the Plain Is Under Lock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Dakota farmer Luther Berntson stood
before an audience at the Department of Agriculture and spoke what
he admitted sounded like heresy: Lock the plow in the barn, he
advised, and farm without tilling.
   ``My neighbors say it is sacrilege, unpatriotic and everything
else,'' he said. ``It was the plow that opened the prairie. Thomas
Jefferson made improvements to the plow. Why, the plow is mentioned
in the Bible.''
   Yet what Berntson advocated wasn't heresy here. He was a
participant in a Agriculture Department conference Monday on a new
breeze in farming _ low-input agriculture.
   That's maximum farming with minimal disturbance to nature,
farming with seed, soil and manure and as little chemistry as
possible.
   The movement is similar in some respects to ``organic'' farming,
although many low-input practitioners find they can't stay in
business without using herbicides and other chemicals scorned by
their more dogmatic counterparts.
   With drought blowing the topsoil away, the cost of petrochemicals
skyrocketing and farmers coming under the scrutiny of the
Environmental Protection Agency for polluting groundwater, the
Agriculture Department decided to take a fresh look at low-impact
farming.
   Keynoter Will Erwin, an Indiana farmer, said public impatience
has given urgency to the cause.
   He summed up the public's attitude toward farmers this way: ``We
paid you not to produce so much and you used chemicals and
fertilizers to produce more, and spoiled the environment to boot.''
   With his topsoil only six inches deep and more blowing away every
time he plowed, Berntson, a third generation wheat farmer in
northeastern North Dakota, started no-tillage farming 10 years ago,
raising wheat and barley from acres that normally get a mere 18
inches of rain a year.
   Does it pay off?
   The jury is out, he said. Farming his way is costly and still
requires a lot of herbicides to control weeds, doing what his
locked-up plow once did.
   He puts so much stuff on the weeds, he said, that ``we say we are
plowing with a can and a jug.''
   As for his neighbors, ``They are not quite ready to go to
no-till, and maybe they're smarter than I am.''
   The Agriculture Department spends just $3.9 million of its $25
billion annual budget on ``alternative agriculture.'' Tom Brown, a
west-central Nebraska farmer, pleaded with it to do more.
   Brown, who raises corn and soybeans with three sons on 3,300
acres, said he, too, has parked his plow, ``and if this makes me a
good guy, I guess I qualify.''
   He's a member of the Sierra Club, but he can hardly be called a
low-input farmer, he said.
   To get corn yields of 150 to 200 bushels per acre, this is what
he pours onto each acre: $24 in seeds, $51 in fertilizer, $18 in
herbicides, $12 in insecticides and $50 to $60 worth of electricity
to run the irrigation system.
   ``We know this is wrong,'' said Brown, ``but we don't know what
else to do about it because we still have to make a living. I belong
to a lot of organizations that recognize the problem. But I have to
make a living.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Democrats-Jones     01-31 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Democrats-Jones,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown's Last Opponent for Dem Party Chief Drops Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Jim Jones' withdrawal from the race
for chairman of the Democratic National Committee clears the field
for former Jesse Jackson aide Ronald Brown to assume the top party
job next month.
   Jones became the last opponent of Brown to drop out of the race
Monday, when he conceded Brown had enough votes on the 404-member
committee to assure his election next week.
   ``I don't see prolonging a campaign that is outvoted,'' Jones
said.
   Brown's election to the top Democratic Party job was assured last
week when three other rivals for the post dropped out and endorsed
him. Although Jones briefly continued his challenge, Brown claimed
he had enough votes to win and there was near-unanimous agreement
within the party that he did.
   The Democratic National Committee meets in Washington on Feb. 10
to select a new chairman to replace Paul Kirk, who is giving up the
job.
   Jones, a former congessman from Oklahoma, said he spoke with
Brown on Sunday and congratulated him for winning.
   Brown was Democratic National Convention manager for presidential
hopeful Jackson last year. Some of Brown's opponents had cited his
ties to Jackson, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and New York Gov.
Mario Cuomo as evidence he would give ammunition to Republicans
trying to paint the Democrats as too liberal.
   Brown met over the weekend with Jewish leaders in Denver in an
attempt to put to rest concerns about his views on Israel, which
were raised because of his association with Jackson.
   Jones, in announcing his withdrawal, said he would still address
the DNC members during their two-day meeting in Washington and would
continue efforts ``to move the party to a more centrist position.''
   He said Brown ``has to take some steps that will show true
independence'' and display a commitment to winning back Southern and
Western voters to the Democratic Party.
   He warned that the party is perceived by many as too liberal,
that voting trends are moving against Democrats and that they could
lose control of Congress and find themselves a true minority party
in coming years.
   ``The Democratic Party could go the way of the British Labor
Party unless we make some fundamental changes in our message and
image,'' he said.
   ``If the Democrats keep sweeping under the rug the fact that we
are losing moderate voters, that we're losing adult white male
voters, that we're losing white and ethnic minority young voters, if
we keep sweeping those statistics under the rug and failing to face
up to them, we are really buying our own doom,'' Jones said.
</TEXT>
