<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-31 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oh, the perks of the presidency. When George
Bush sets up his horseshoe pit at the White House, he won't have to
use plain old horseshoes.
   No, Bush will get shoes befitting a president, not a horse.
Cousins Morrie and Don Wheeler, who own the 80-year-old Wheeler
Brothers Brass Foundry, have made Bush some solid brass, engraved
horseshoes.
   The shoes were forged, ground and polished to 2 pounds, 10
ounces, regulation weight for the National Horseshoe Pitchers
Association.
   ``They really turned out to be quite an impressive casting,''
said Bob St. Germain of Averill Park, a woodworker who made the
patterns for the shoes out of mahogany. ``They look like they're
solid gold.''
   Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-New York, is planning to deliver the
horseshoes to Bush.
   ``I think he'll appreciate these,'' said St. Germain. ``He
probably gets all kinds of gifts, but these have a lot of real
people in them. ... It's something we've worked on together.''
   Morrie Wheeler said he expects the horseshoes will make an
impression on the president.
   ``It's something nobody would buy for just themselves,'' he said.
``And they'll last forever.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No need to hold your nose. A new organization
of skunk lovers says the animals make wonderful pets once their
ability to create a stink is removed.
   ``These are the most misunderstood animals in the world,'' said
Jane Bone, a national authority on skunks. ``In the state of
Georgia, there has never been a documented case of rabies in
domesticated skunks.''
   So maybe rabies isn't what some people had in mind. But the new
members of Skunks as Pets Inc. say they've taken steps to ensure
that their pets are, uh, socially acceptable.
   Pet skunks are de-scented at an early age and are incapable of
any olfactory assaultism, they say.
   About 30 people met Sunday to organize an Augusta-area chapter of
the skunk organization. As they talked, their pets _ Stinky, Daisy,
Barney, Pudgy and friends _ made themselves at home, ambling around
and checking things out.
   Ms. Bone said pet skunks are not wild animals. In fact, Skunks As
Pets, which is beginning to register skunks much like the American
Kennel Club does dogs, will not recognize a black and white skunk
unless it can be proven the animal is domestic.
   Consequently, the skunks at the meeting were either albinos,
which have been bred domestically for more than 100 years, or
``chocolates,'' which have been bred for 40 to 50 years.
   Ms. Bone was quick to point out that the animals aren't for
everyone _ particularly children under age 12 _ and that they
require conscientious care.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opera lovers aren't going to like this, but
talent agent John Shea won tickets to a Broadway play by singing the
aria to ``Gilligan's Island.''
   Yes, that's right. Asked to sing at least 16 bars from any opera,
Shea broke into the renowned ``Gilligan's Island'' theme _ and won
his tickets. ``I don't know any opera,'' he explained.
   Neither did a lot of other people who showed up Monday morning at
the Royale Theater to win tickets to the first preview of ``Lend Me
a Tenor,'' a new comedy revolving around a performance of Verdi's
``Otello.''
   The theater offered tickets to the first 100 people who could
sing a bit of opera. Among the borderline offerings: ``Summertime''
from ``Porgy &amp; Bess'' and Frederick's song from ``The Pirates of
Penzance.''
   Others, like ``Gilligan's Island,'' were clearly beyond the pale.
Among them were ``I Dreamed a Dream'' from ``Les Miserables'' and
``I Don't Know How to Love Him'' from ``Jesus Christ Superstar.''
(``It's an opera,'' insisted Nancy Nisselbaum, who sang the latter.
``A rock opera.'')
   Finally, there were actual, real, bona fide opera selections.
Jeanette Murawski drew a round of applause for ``Vissi d'arte'' from
Puccini's ``Tosca.'' Other selections came from ``Carmen,''
``Rigoletto,'' ``Faust,'' ``La Boheme,'' ``Madama Butterfly'' and,
yes, ``Otello.''
