<FIRST>r w PM-SolicitorGeneral     01-31 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solicitor General,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Appeals Judge Starr Apparent Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives applauded and liberals took a
wait-and-see attitude toward the Justice Department's recommendation
of federal appeals court judge Kenneth W. Starr as the new U.S.
solicitor general.
   Justice Department sources confirmed Monday that Starr, 42, had
been recommended to President Bush to becme the government's chief
appeals lawyer, arguing cases before the Supreme Court and deciding
whether to appeal lower court decisions against federal agencies.
   White House spokesmen said Monday they did not know when Bush
might nominate Starr, but a Justice Department source, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said: ``I understand it's a done deal. Bush
hasn't done anything on it, but we wouldn't have recommended it
formally if we didn't think it suited his personnel people.''
   The nomination would be subject to Senate confirmation.
   Starr, born in Vernon, Texas, has been on the U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals for the District of Columbia since Oct. 11, 1983. Before
that, he had been a clerk for former Chief Justice Warren E. Burger,
a partner with the Los Angeles law firm of Gibson, Dunn &amp; Crutcher,
and counselor to former Attorney General William French Smith.
   He had previously been mentioned as a possible Supreme Court
nominee after the 1987 retirement of Justice Lewis Powell.
   Starr was unavailable for interviews Monday, his secretary said.
   Kenneth Cribb, a top aide in Reagan's White House and in former
Attorney General Edwin Meese III's Justice Department, said Monday
that Starr ``would make an excellent solicitor general.''
   ``I found him to be quite compatible with the conservative
judicial philosophy of the Reagan administration in all matters,''
said Cribb, a senior fellow at the conservative Heritage Foundation.
   Bruce Fein, a conservative columnist and attorney who was
associate deputy attorney general during President Reagan's first
term, said in a November 1988 column that Starr ``epitomizes the
Reagan judicial legacy.''
   Fein said Monday that virtually all of Starr's written opinions
``have been earmarked by conservative instinct, yet open-mindedness.
There's no ideological fervor.''
   But liberals expressed some wariness.
   ``We're looking at the nomination very cautiously,'' said Susan
Liss, legal director for People for the American Way.
   ``I think the most interesting thing about Starr's selection is
that it gives the administration another seat in the D.C. Circuit to
fill,'' she said. ``Starr has been a less reliable conservative than
the Reagan administration may have hoped when it selected Starr to
sit on the court.''
   One seat on the appeals court, Robert Bork's, already is open.
Bork resigned after the Senate rejected Reagan's nomination to place
him in the Supreme Court.
   To Colleen O'Connor of the American Civil Liberties Union,
``Starr is a question mark.''
   However, she added, ``All the signals that have come out of the
Bush administration's Justice Department do not seem all that
different from what we've seen in the past.''
   In some recent cases, Starr has joined with other judges to
uphold First Amendment rights.
   In other cases, he helped overturn court-imposed limits on the
District of Columbia's prison population and helped throw out the
D.C. Fire Department's affirmative action hiring plan.
   Starr received his bachelor's degree from George Washington
University in 1968, got a master's from Brown University in 1969 and
graduated from Duke University Law School in 1973.
   If approved, Starr would succeed Charles Fried, who has left the
solicitor office to return to Harvard University Law School.
</TEXT>
