<DOCNO> AP890131-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Grandfathers     01-31 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Grandfathers,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Loophole in Election Law Moves Toward Closing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress are moving to close a
custom-made loophole in federal election laws allowing some of them
to keep unspent campaign funds, a potential personal bonus of up to
$1 million each.
   The loophole, which was written to help ensure passage of the
1980 election law, has since lost some of its popularity in
Congress. Repealing the provision is now part of a package of
legislation related to a pending 50 percent pay raise.
   ``It's an embarrassment to them,'' Norman Ornstein, a political
analyst with the American Enterprise Institute, said Monday. ``It's
the sort of question not too many members who were there before 1980
want to have asked of them.
   ``I think it's a foregone conclusion that they'll do away with
it.''
   More than $61 million in surplus campaign funds is sitting in the
accounts of 191 House members and 71 senators who were in Congress
when the law was passed. A ``grandfather clause'' in the law allows
them to convert the money for personal use, an action forbidden for
those who came to Congress later.
   On the average, House members who were grandfathered in hold
about $224,000 in their campaign accounts, while senators, whose
campaigns usually are considerably more costly, have an average of
$341,000, according to FEC records.
   ``I didn't go out and spend all the money because that's not the
way I operate my own home,'' said Rep. Larry J. Hopkins, R-Ky. ``I
spend what I think is appropriate to win.''
   Hopkins, who cruised to re-election on a 3-to-1 margin last year,
had $604,824 left over in his campaign account, according to records
at the Federal Election Commission.
   That puts him in 10th place among members of the House.
   The top spot in the House belongs to Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y.,
with more than $1.1 million. Solarz is co-sponsor of a bill that
would abolish the grandfather clause.
   The House Ways and Means Committee chairman, Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., has more than $1 million _ up from $596,000
since January 1987 _ and has not expressed an opinion on the issue
of abolishing the loophole, according to an aide.
   In the Senate, the list is topped by Sens. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.,
with nearly $2.1 million and Phil Gramm, R-Texas, with $1.9 million.
However, those amounts are not unusually big war chests since both
those senators face re-election campaigns next year.
   The legislation now before each house would eliminate the
possibility of letting the grandfathered members convert leftover
funds to their own uses but would continue permitting conversion for
the other uses allowed under the law.
   Candidates for Congress can use leftover campaign money to
support political organizations or other candidates. In addition,
members of Congress can use the money to ``defray any ordinary and
necessary expenses'' arising because of their position.
   And, unlike the House, the Senate has a rule forbidding its
members from converting their campaign money for personal use,
although it does not have the force of law and its effect on former
senators or their survivors is unclear.
   Proposals to abolish the exemption in both the House and Senate
have come up as members of Congress are about to pick up 50 percent
pay raises, boosting salaries from $89,500 to $135,000 annually for
rank-and-file lawmakers.
   Hopkins said Monday that he kept his campaign treasury stocked
with cash because he represents a largely Democratic district and he
doesn't want to borrow.
   ``You will never see Larry Hopkins holding one of these dumb fish
frys at $25 a head to retire a campaign debt,'' he said.
   He offered to give back money over the next month to ``anybody
who donated to my campaign last time and is not satisfied. Please
contact me, and I will send the money back.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
