<FIRST>r a PM-Burning-Challenge     01-31 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burning-Challenge,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Sheriff Threatens Suit Against ``Mississippi Burning'' Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence Rainey, the sheriff when three
civil rights workers were slain in rural Neshoba County in 1964, is
demanding a retraction from the producers of ``Mississippi Burning.''
   ``They didn't use my name but nobody in Mississippi or any other
state has any doubt they intended that sheriff to be me,'' said
Rainey, 65, now employed as a security officer in Meridian.
   ``We will be mailing a demand letter for a retraction on Tuesday
and that's a prerequisite for a lawsuit under Mississippi law,''
said his attorney, James McIntyre.
   Rainey was acquitted on charges of violating the civil rights of
the three workers in a federal trial at which he was represented by
McIntyre.
   McIntyre said the film ``mixes fact with fiction and depicts
Rainey as terrorizing citizens of Neshoba County. It depicts him as
being a person bent on violence and it is not an accurate, fair
account of what did happen in Neshoba County in 1964.''
   On June 21, 1964, James Earl Chaney, 21, who was black, and
whites Andrew Goodman, 20 and Michael Schwerner, 24, disappeared
after they were released from the county jail in Philadelphia. They
had been stopped for speeding after investigating a church burning
by the Ku Klux Klan.
   Their bodies were found 44 days later in a soggy earthen dam in
rural Neshoba County. All three had been shot to death.
   Alan Parker's ``Mississippi Burning,'' an Orion Pictures release,
is loosely based on the murders. The film, which stars Gene Hackman
and Willem Dafoe, has drawn both praise from movie critics and
criticism from blacks who contend it gives the FBI too much credit
in the civil rights struggle.
   Rainey maintains his innocence and said the movie had subjected
him to ridicule.
   ``The character in the movie was a big man like me and he chewed
tobacco like I chewed tobacco all the time,'' said Rainey, who works
for a black-owned security firm.
   ``Everybody knows it was made off the happenings in Neshoba
County,'' he said Monday. ``The actor had twice as big a crew of
tobacco as I ever had but they might have well as called him
Lawrence Rainey.''
   Rainey, who served as Neshoba County sheriff from 1964 to 1968,
said he had lost a security job in 1975 following a movie based on
the civil rights violence in Mississippi.
   ``I've got a good relationship with blacks,'' he said. ``I'm
working for a black man and a black company but he is getting a lot
of feedback for working me.''
   The former sheriff said he wanted McIntyre to proceed with a
damage suit immediately because ``of the way it has hurt me and is
going to hurt me.''
   ``If they say `We are sorry for what has happened and it isn't
true,''' McIntyre said, ``that still does not negate a cause of
action, it only mitigates the damages.''
   McIntyre noted that of the 18 individuals brought to trial on
charges of conspiring to violate the victim's civil rights, only
Rainey and a few others were found innocent. Seven were convicted
and given sentences ranging from three to 10 years.
   Calls to Orion Pictures were not answered late Monday afternoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
