<FIRST>r w PM-Quayle     01-31 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Echoes Early Reagan in Criticism of Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle told religious
broadcasters that ``the gospel'' of Vladimir Lenin still pervades
the Soviet Union and the United States must be realistic in dealing
with that communist nation.
   Speaking Monday to the National Religious Broadcasters, Quayle
said the Soviet Communist Party had over the years gained an
``appalling confidence in its own wisdom, indeed, its own
omniscience.''
   ``I think the root of the matter all comes back to a hatred of
God, to a rejection of the entire concept of a religious system,''
he said.
   Comparing the American revolution with the communist revolution
in Russia, Quayle said, ``Look how much good has come into the world
as a result of the first revolution and how much evil has entered
the world because of the second.''
   Bush is addressing the group Wednesday.
   Quayle's comments, somewhat reminiscent of Ronald Reagan's
rhetoric in the early days of his presidency when he called the
Soviet Union an ``evil empire,'' differed in tone from recent Bush
remarks concerning the Soviets.
   Bush has used less harsh wording, but has urged a cautious
approach to U.S.-Soviet relations, which were improving as Reagan's
term came to an end.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Quayle's
comments were not inconsistent with administration policy.
   Quayle quoted Lenin, the leader of the 1917 Communist Revolution,
as saying the idea of God is ``unutterable vileness ... of the most
dangerous kind.''
   ``That was Lenin and unfortunately his gospel is still actively
pursued in the Soviet Union,'' Quayle said.
   On the other hand, Quayle said the U.S. founding fathers had a
``belief in the existence of a Creator whose laws have placed
irrevocable limits on the power of the state.''
   He also said that if Moscow's planned 1991 international human
rights conference occurs, the United States must ensure that it ``is
not just a public relations extravaganza for the Soviet leadership.''
   President Bush has said he would follow through on Reagan's plan
for U.S. participation in the conference, but also has said U.S.
officials will be watching Soviet human rights performance in the
interim.
   Talking about his trip this week to Venezuela and El Salvador,
Quayle said, ``My message will be democracy, democracy and more
democracy,'' he said.
   Quayle is not expected to make any policy initiatives during the
trip but plans to meet with a number of heads of state who will
attend Thursday's inauguration of Venezuela's new president, Carlos
Andres Perez.
</TEXT>
