<FIRST>r w PM-NursingHomes     01-31 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Homes,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Regulations Aim at Protecting Patients' Rights, Improving Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 15,000 nursing homes will have to
meet higher standards of care and give patients more say in their
treatment, under new regulations for Medicaid and Medicare
reimbursement.
   The final regulations, announced Monday, cap several years of
efforts by the Health Care Financing Administration to meet the
terms of a law passed by Congress in 1987 to improve the quality of
nursing home care.
   ``These regulations change our focus in regulating nursing homes,
away from looking to see merely if a facility has the capacity to
deliver care, to looking at the quality of care that is actually
being delivered,'' said Dr. William L. Roper, HCFA administrator.
   Among other things, the regulations will:
   _Give patients the right to refuse treatment, manage their own
money, receive visitors, manage their own privacy, express
grievances, be free of physical restraints and not be transferred or
discharged against their will.
   _Offer patients services needed to treat specific conditions and
guard against such things as inappropriate weight gain and loss and
bed sores.
   _Require nursing homes to have 24-hour nursing capability,
including a registered nurse for eight hours of every day.
   _Require facilities to train nurses' aides, provide dental,
vision and hearing care, and offer an activities program by a
qualified professional.
   The final regulations will apply to nearly 15,000 long-term care
facilities. The rules are open to a 90-day comment period and most
will go into effect 90 days after that. The rest will go into effect
Oct. 1, 1990.
   The American Health Care Association, which represents licensed
nursing homes and long-term health care facilities, generally
endorsed the regulations, but expressed concern about the length of
time it is taking to put them in place.
   The group also is concerned that ``if there is not adequate
funding for them, they won't have the impact they were intended to
have,'' said Linda Keegan, a spokeswoman for the association.
   The American Nursing Association said it was ``extremely
concerned at the disregard for the quality of care'' in the
regulations.
   Lucille Joel, president of the nursing association, criticized
the rules for permitting HFCA to waive a requirement that a
registered nurse be on duty for eight hours a day, seven days a week.
   The Health and Human Services agency has proposed no criteria on
which to grant waivers ``and has implied that the waivers may be
used as a way to cut the budget for Medicare and Medicaid nursing
home programs,'' she said.
   Tom Hoyer, director of provider service coverage policy at HFCA,
said the law allows waivers only when a nursing home can't find
nurses to hire and would be granted only if quality of care were not
affected. The agency will be issuing proposed rules for waiver
requirements in the next couple of months, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
