<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     01-31 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review Sought of Bridge-Inspection Rule Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Highway Administration is being
asked to rethink its decision to require bridges to be inspected
every four years instead of every two years, as previously required.
   An auto safety advocacy group and relatives of people killed in a
1987 New York bridge collapse said in a petition filed Monday,
``FHwA failed to obtain crucial information relevant to the decision
and consequently could not make a knowledgeable analysis of the
effects of less frequent bridge inspections.''
   The new rule was passed in August and affects about 122,000
bridges nationwide.
   The federal agency ``has issued the final rule despite the
documented inadequacies of state bridge inspection programs covering
576,000 bridges,'' Clarence M. Ditlow III, executive director of the
Center for Auto Safety, said in a letter accompanying the petition
that asks the agency to review the rule change.
   Also filing the petition were relatives of three people who were
among 10 killed when the Schoharie Creek bridge on the New York
State Thruway fell into the Schoharie Creek on April 5, 1987, after
days of rain and flooding.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Study Says Electric Power Shortages Possible in 1990s</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. power companies must build more generating
capacity than currently planned or the nation may face an
electricity shortage in the 1990s, a trade group says.
   Based on conservative projections of growth in electricity
demand, the nation will need an additional 50,000 megawatts of
generating capacity by 1997 in order to avoid a shortage, a newly
published American Gas Association study said Monday.
   That amount would be needed in addition to the 32,500 megawatts
of capacity currently under construction, the study said.
   Using an assumption of faster electricity demand growth over the
next decade, which the gas group said it considered to be more
realistic, an additional 105,000 megawatts of plant capacity would
be needed to avoid shortages.
   The study said 71 percent of capacity additions planned in the
1979-88 period were canceled.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>District Council Proposes Liability for Handgun Manufacturers and</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sellers
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Handgun manufacturers and sellers would be
liable for injuries and deaths caused by the weapons, under a new
proposal by the District of Columbia City Council.
   The proposal ``is designed to force gun manufacturers to consider
carefully the purposes for which handguns are manufactured,'' said
Council Chairman David Clarke, the bill's sponsor.
   Sponsors of the legislation said it will be the first of its kind
in the nation.
   The plan would hold handgun manufacturers, importers and dealers
liable for damage caused by handguns, in the same manner that some
states hold tavern owners or party hosts liable for injuries caused
by drunken drivers.
   The bill is supported by 12 of the 13 council members in a city
whose officials are worried about a rising murder rate.
   January is already the bloodiest month in city history, with 49
killings through Monday. The highest yearly total was set in 1988
when 372 people were killed in the nation's capital.
