<FIRST>r w PM-Commodities 1stLd-Writethru a0453 01-31 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raw Materials Prices Reached Top Levels in 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``It calculated...'' to drop extra
word `dollars'; INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``In addition...''
to add oil prices; picks up 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``Penelope Hartland-Thunberg...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for raw materials all over the world
reached their highest level for the 1980s last year, according to
figures collected by the World Bank.
   It calculated that the drought in this country pushed the average
price of wheat to $168.90 a metric ton, or $4.69 a bushel, last
month, compared with an average of $112.10 a metric ton, or $3.11 a
bushel, in 1987.
   Big demand by the industrial countries of east Asia helped raise
the price of copper to a record $3,498.90 a metric ton, nearly $1.20
a pound, the World Bank said Monday.
   The average rise for a long list of commodities was 10.2 percent
for the year. That brought the overall level to just a little _ 2.8
percent _ above the average for the years 1979 to 1981.
   Problems of Third World countries have been aggravated in recent
years by low prices they have been getting for the products of
fields and mines, their chief source of foreign income. For some,
things are now improving.
   Aluminum, nickel, rice, sugar, bananas, fats and oils were all up
for the year. Timber, cotton and oranges were down.
   In addition to the Arab countries of the Middle East, oil is a
major export for Nigeria, Mexico, Venezuela, Ecuador, Indonesia and
others. Chile benefits doubly: from the rise in the copper price and
the drop in the oil price, because oil is a big import.
   The average oil price in 1988 was $13.60 a barrel compared with
$17.20 a barrel in 1987, and the price dropped as low as $11.60 a
barrel in the fourth quarter of 1988. However, oil prices increased
steadily in December, reflecting growing market confidence in the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' November decision to
set a production ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day, according to
the report.
   Penelope Hartland-Thunberg, trade expert at the independent
Center for Strategic and International Studies, said that commodity
prices go in short-term cycles, now up and now down. But the long
term trend is now toward a decline as new inventions come into use
and fewer raw materials are used for each dollar of goods produced.
   Ron Duncan, chief of the World Bank's Commodities Division,
pointed out that there is sometimes a wide spread even within
individual commodities. High quality arabica coffees from the
highlands of Brazil, Colombia and Jamaica are being bought more and
more in western Europe, he said.
   The report credited the reintroduction of export quotas under the
International Coffee Agreement as helping raise the price of
arabicas by 20 percent in 1988.
   That meant a shift away from the lower grade robusta coffees
grown nearer the sea in West Africa and Indonesia. Their prices were
down by 8 percent.
   Duncan also emphasized the uneven effects of price movements.
   ``The newly industrialized countries in Asia are importing feed
for pigs and poultry,'' he said. ``That pushes up the price of grain
up for the low income countries of Africa, which have to buy more
because they're producing less themselves and there's less foreign
aid available.''
   West Africa countries, especially the Ivory Coast, are suffering
from low prices for both their coffee and cocoa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
