<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     01-31 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Lower Against Yen, Stock Shares Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed lower against the Japanese yen
Tuesday while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange reversed
morning declines to close slightly higher.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which had lost
64.05 points at the end of the morning session, closed 13.80 points,
or 0.04 percent, higher at 31,581.30. The index lost 111.57 points
Monday.
   The dollar ended trading at 129.13 yen, down 0.60 yen from
Monday's close of 129.73 yen. The currency opened at 129.59 yen and
moved between 129.05 yen and 129.63 yen.
   The dollar's lower opening in Tokyo followed a decline in New
York Monday when traders who had bought dollars Friday sold for
profit taking, dealers said. The dollar closed at 129.30 yen in New
York Monday, down from last Friday's finish of 129.43 yen.
   ``In Tokyo, market players were not making any major moves except
for some position adjustments, and many of them remained on the
sidelines trying to determine the future of the dollar-yen rate,''
said Minori Takeuchi of the Chemical Bank.
   However, she said, the currency's slight loss Tuesday morning did
not signal a reversal in the trend toward a stronger dollar. Trading
was also thin because of the lack of market-affecting news, Ms.
Takeuchi said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei index, the market's main
barometer, opened lower despite gains in the Dow Jones industrial
average in New York.
   Traders said institutional investors were cautious due to
fluctuations in the dollar-yen rate on foreign exchange markets.
   Trading was directionless in the absence of major
market-affecting incentives, said one trader with a major securities
firm in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
