<FIRST>r a PM-ChemicalWeapons     01-31 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Weapons,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities: Two Arrested in Chemical Weapons Shipments To Iran And
Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American businessman and a Dutch national
have been arrested for diverting shipments of an industrial
lubricant to Jordan for use as a chemical weapon by Iraq,
authorities said.
   Besides announcing the arrests, U.S. authorities said Monday that
a Baltimore-based company agreed to plead guilty to one count of
violating export laws in connection with the export of thiodiglycol.
   The lubricant, used in inks and textiles and sold under the brand
name Kromfax, produces lethal mustard gas when combined with
hydrochloric acid.
   Nicholas J. Defino, 64, of New Jersey and Dutch citizen Frans Van
Amraat, who was apprehended in Milan, Italy, on Jan. 26, were
charged with conspiracy, listing phony destinations on export
documents and violating U.S. export laws.
   Defino surrendered to Customs Service agents in Baltimore on
Monday and was released on bond after appearing before a magistrate.
Van Amraat is awaiting extradition.
   The chemicals, manufactured by Alcolac International Inc. of
Baltimore, were illegally shipped to Iran and Iraq by separate
agents during 1987 and 1988, said U.S. Attorney Breckinridge L.
Willcox.
   The two men were accused of shipping the chemical to Belgium then
to Jordan. From there, the chemical was transported to Iraq, said
Willcox.
   Four shipments, each weighing more than 100 tons, were sent to
Western Europe in 1987 and 1988, but at least three wound up in
Iraq, according to the federal complaint.
   Last year, a West German pleaded guilty to purchasing a component
of mustard gas from Alcolac and shipping it via Greece and Singapore
to Iran.
   DeFino conducted business with Alcolac through Nu Kraft
Mercantile Corp. of New York City, purchasing the more than 400 tons
of the chemical, authorities said. Van Amraat was the European agent
for Nu Kraft, authorities said.
   Willcox said Defino is vice president of United Steel and Strip
Corp. of New York.
   Alcolac officials said the chemicals were sent to the Middle East
without their knowledge.
   ``That was not my understanding,'' said Willcox, who refused to
elaborate.
   Alcolac Vice President Jack Rubin said the company was unaware
the chemicals were going to the destinations other than the European
points listed on shipping documents. He said the company has
cooperated fully with federal investigators.
   One former employee filled out the shipping documents in a way
that ran afoul of the complex provisions of the Export
Administration Act, Rubin said. The employee did not know the
eventual destinations, he said. Willcox declined to say whether the
worker would be charged.
   ``No one within this company had any indication that these
materials were going to be diverted to the Iran-Iraq war zone,''
Rubin said. ``We feel just awful that one of our products was
misused for that end use.''
   The federal investigation previously led to the arrest in July of
Peter Walaschek, a West German employee of Chemco G.m.b.h., who
purchased three shipments of the chemical during 1987 and 1988 for
shipment to Greece and Singapore and then re-exported them to Iran,
Willcox said.
   Walaschek pleaded guilty to violating American export law for
arranging the shipments. After initially agreeing to cooperate with
prosecutors as an informant, Walaschek fled the country, forfeiting
a $350,000 bond, authorities said.
   Willcox said talks were continuing with West German officials
about extraditing Walaschek.
   Chemco had purchased thiodiglycol at the direction of Sexed
Kharim Ali Sobhani, an Iranian diplomat stationed in West Germany,
The New York Times reported Sunday.
   Under American law, exporting the chemical requires a license.
Shipments to Iran, Iraq and Syria are barred.
   Chemco purchased three shipments of thiodiglycol from Alcolac and
90 tons were delivered to Iran in 1987 and 1988, Willcox said. A
later shipment of 120 tons was intercepted by Customs investigators,
who substituted water for the chemical and then traced their travels
to Iran, authorities said.
   One ton of thiodiglycol produces about a ton of mustard gas. One
hundred tons would cover about 50 square miles.
</TEXT>
