<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0510EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru a0436 01-31 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solarz Reports Pakistani Offer to Verify No-Weapons Pledge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Solarz said...'' to add Beg's first
name; SUBS 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``The network...'' to correct location of
plant; picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``Pakistan is...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistani officials are willing for the first
time to agree to verification that they are not building nuclear
weapons if they are permitted to buy U.S.-made reactors for power
production, says a senior member of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., who brought the proposal back from a
recent trip to Pakistan, said Monday it deserves serious
consideration and he will hold hearings on the idea in his Asia
subcommittee.
   Solarz said ``key'' Pakistani officials had endorsed the
reactors-for-safeguards swap but declined to say which ones. During
his stay in Islamabad he met with new Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto,
President Ghulam Ishaq Khan and army Chief of Staff Gen. Aslam Beg,
among others.
   Under the proposal, Pakistan would agree to some form of
negotiated verification process to ensure that its nuclear program
is put only to peaceful uses, and is not devoted to weapons
development.
   Pakistan's nuclear intentions have been a source of friction in
past relations with the United States, although U.S. policy-makers
sought to put those concerns aside in recent years because of
Pakistan's cooperation in funneling weapons to the anti-Soviet
rebels in neighboring Afghanistan.
   Now that Soviet troops are being withdrawn, however, the nuclear
issue has come back to the forefront of relations between the two
countries. Administration officials have said U.S. aid to Pakistan
may be cut off after Sept. 30 because President Bush will not be
unable to certify that the Pakistanis have not developed a nuclear
weapon.
   Further details of the Pakistani weapons program were reported
Monday by CBS, which said nuclear materials made in the United
States found their way to Pakistan through by way of West Germany.
   The network said heavy water from the U.S. Savannah River weapons
reactor complex near Aiken, S.C., was sold to a West German company
and was processed 15 to 20 years later into the tritium gas used to
build nuclear warheads. Then, after being sold and resold, it
reached another West Germany firm, NTG, which shipped the gas to
Pakistan, CBS said.
   Pakistan is receiving $230 million in military aid and $215
million in economic aid from the United States this year, making it
the third largest beneficiary of U.S. aid after Israel and Egypt.
   Solarz said an agreement that would provide safeguards against
Pakistani weapons development could not only head off a prickly
showdown over U.S. aid, but it also could facilitate a budding
reconciliation between Pakistan and neighboring India.
   ``If the United States is willing to sell nuclear reactors for
peaceful nuclear energy, Pakistan would agree to establish
full-scope safeguards on all their nuclear facilities, including
existing ones,'' Solarz said in describing the proposal made by
Pakistani officials.
   ``If we can cap the Pakistani nuclear program at its present
level, that would represent a very significant and constructive
development.''
   Pakistan in the past has refused to cooperate in international
inspection procedures under a non-proliferation treaty. Bhutto said
recently that her country will not sign the international treaty
unless India does too.
   Solarz noted that Pakistan's relatively high level of U.S. aid
was based on its key role in supporting the Afghan rebels, and that
the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan would lessen the
need for military aid. But he said there might be a greater need for
economic aid than in the past.
   The Reagan administration, in its 1991 budget proposal, asked
that military aid levels to Pakistan be increased to $240 million
and economic aid be increased to $250 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
