<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia-Drugs     01-31 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Drugs,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Eight Labs, 2,310 Pounds of Cocaine, Destroy 44 Runways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a new offensive against drug
traffickers, Colombia's narcotics police destroyed eight cocaine
laboratories, 2,310 pounds of cocaine and 44 runways in remote
areas, the national police chief said.
   The raids, all in jungle areas, occurred last weekend as part of
Operation Springtime, Gen. Miguel Antonio Gomez said in a news
release on Monday.
   Gomez took over the national police last month in one of the
frequent changes of command in government security forces. New
police commanders frequently come on strong with a series of raids.
   Eight people, who had all made just a few dollars a day as
laborers at the cocaine processing labs, were arrested in the
weekend raids, Gomez said.
   Not one of Colombia's dozen major cocaine bosses has ever been
arrested on drug trafficking charges and convicted in Colombia.
   An average of two dozen cocaine processing labs are destroyed in
Colombia each year, and scores of clandestine runways are bombed by
the air force.
   New labs and new runways appear within weeks. A police colonel
told The Associated Press last year that there probably were more
than 500 clandestine runways in use by drug traffickers in Colombia
at any given time.
   The U.S. government gives about $15 million worth of aid to
Colombia each year in the form of equipment and training to fight
drug trafficking.
   Colombian narcotics officials have suggested privately that $15
million dollars does not go far toward stopping the
multibillion-dollar illegal cocaine trafficking in Colombia.
   Scores of helicopters and thousands of police would be needed to
deal effectively with the problem, the officials have said privately.
</TEXT>
