<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg-Foreman     01-31 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg-Foreman,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Steinberg, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jeremiah Cole, a 46-year-old former health
maintenance organization senior manager, was the foreman of the jury
that convicted Joel Steinberg of first-degree manslaughter following
a 12-week trial. These are his comments as told to Associated Press
writer Samuel Maull, who covered the three-month trial.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By JEREMIAH COLE</NOTE>
<NOTE>For The Associated Press</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   We arrived at a verdict in the Joel Steinberg
murder trial in our eighth day of deliberations because for a short
period on Monday I abdicated my position as chairman of the group.
   That action enabled the last holdout (against a guilty verdict
for first-degree manslaughter) to participate more fully in the
deliberations. That person and I had had some friction, some
conflict and another person's assumption of the chair enabled the
holdout to participate without dealing with me.
   The timing for this action was right. It could not have been done
any sooner.
   I knew before the testimony was half over that there was enormous
potential for a hung jury. I could sense it in the people.
   I thought there would be a hung jury. This was because of the
complexity of the case and the circumstantial nature of the evidence.
   It was clear from the beginning that the only possibility of
arriving at a verdict was to keep everyone talking, avoid for a time
the areas of greatest conflict, and try to find things we could
agree on.
   We did not take a vote right away when we began deliberations. An
immediate vote would have made the jurors feel locked into a
position. I felt that we should start with as many facts that seemed
to have significance that we could agree on.
   There were unmistakable indications at the beginning of our
deliberations that we were almost hopelessly divided.
   There were three who indicated that it was more probable that
Hedda (Nussbaum, Steinberg's live-in lover) had done it (fatally
injured Lisa) than that Joel had done it.
   But they were not putting forth their case. They never made any
effort to convince anyone of their point of view. They thought it
was enough that they had this point of view. Essentially, their
position was, ``I don't think Joel did it and that's it.'' They
didn't understand how a jury works and comes to a consensus.
   There were two other groups who were generally willing to argue
their positions. There were four in the Joel-is-guilty group. And
about five were in what basically is a middle group that was
undecided. They always felt they should try to convince the other
people of the positions they were holding.
   The defense strategy changed several times during the trial and
that internal inconsistency weakened their case.
   Only two people could have killed Lisa. If Joel knows Hedda did
it, then what's all this stuff about Reye's syndrome (which the
defense at one point contended was the cause of death). I could have
easily entertained a defense of insanity. And there was another
juror who was in the Joel-is-guilty camp who said she would have
been open to an insanity defense. He left the child on the bathroom
floor when he went out to dinner. Then he comes home and uses
cocaine. There was some casual speculation by us about why they
didn't put on an insanity defense.
   The people who believed Hedda had done it used Marilyn Walton's
testimony (who said she saw Ms. Nussbaum slap Lisa) in their own
arguments. They were taking it into account in support of their case.
   Eventually, we voted unanimously a ``not guilty'' verdict on the
murder count. This was a very difficult vote for several jurors who
may have done so in order to avoid a hung jury.
   There were hundreds of times when tension was relieved by joking.
There were only about four times when people almost came to blows.
   I think that if I look deeply into my heart, I would say there
were people (jurors) I did not trust and some I did not hold in
great respect. Over time, I came to change my opinion about some of
the people.
   In the final analysis, everything we accomplished was as a result
of the two things we had in common, a sense of humor and a great
willingness to work together. One of the court officers said that we
were the loudest and funniest jury he had ever observed. The noise,
the running jokes, and the laughter were our way of letting off
steam during and after our many long tense emotional deliberations.
   There was an enormous amount of affection in that jury room _ I
would say a form of love.
   This jury was an extraordinarily diverse group of people. I think
it's fair to say that despite all of our differences of background
and of opinion, we became a family _ so much so that we are planning
a reunion in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg-Charges     01-31 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg-Charges,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Explanation of the Charges In the Steinberg Child Abuse Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Steinberg, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg, who faced four homicide counts in
the death of his 6-year-old illegally adopted daughter, Lisa, was
acquitted of the most serious charge and convicted of the
second-most serious.
   Steinberg was charged with second-degree murder, which would have
required a finding by the state Supreme Court jury that he had
recklessly struck the girl and then showed depraved indifference to
her life by failing to get medical help.
   The jury acquitted him of that charge, which carries a sentence
of 25 years to life in prison.
   The charge on which Steinberg was convicted _ first-degree
manslaughter _ required the jury to find that he intended to cause
serious physical harm to the girl, and that the injury caused her
death. The charge carries a maximum penalty of 8 1@3 to 25 years in
prison.
   The judge had instructed the jury it could infer that Steinberg
intended to cause the injury ``by the results produced by his act.''
But if they found his use of cocaine had so dulled his awareness
that he could not form intent, they were to find him innocent of
first-degree manslaughter.
   The jury did not need to consider the two lesser charges:
second-degree manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide.
   The former requires action that is reckless but not with depraved
indifference. It carries a five-to-15-year prison sentence.
   The latter covers situations in which a death is caused by
someone who fails to perceive the risk of his actions. It carries a
term of 1 1@3 to four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Anti-US     01-31 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Anti-US,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Attack U.S. Cultural Center _ Yet Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shouting ``Yankee go home,'' dozens of
radical students hurled firebombs today at the U.S. cultural center
in Kwangju, U.S. officials said. It was the second such attack this
month.
   About 30 firebombs were thrown, but none landed inside the
compound, said an official at the U.S. Embassy in Seoul. The
official, who requesting anonymity, said there were no injuries or
damage.
   About 50 students shouted anti-U.S. slogans as they dashed out of
alleys and hurled dozens of firebombs and rocks toward the center,
the Yonhap news agency reported. Most of the bombs landed on the
street, it said.
   ``Drive out Yankees who manipulated the Kwangju massacre,''
Yonhap quoted students as shouting.
   They also chanted ``Shut down the Kwangju center'' and ``Punish
(former President) Chun Doo-hwan and (President) Roh Tae-woo,'' the
agency said.
   Roh was elected in December 1987 and replaced Chun, who stepped
down after seven years of authoritarian rule and played a leading
role in the brutal military suppression of the 1980 Kwangju uprising.
   About 100 riot police guarding the center charged at the
attackers, firing tear gas, and chased them away in a few minutes,
Yonhap said. The agency did not say whether any students were
arrested.
   On Jan. 18, about 50 students attacked the center with
sledgehammers, rocks and firebombs and broke windows. No one was
hurt.
   U.S. officials in Seoul, who say the center has been attacked
eight times in the past last year by radical students, today denied
reports that they have decided to close it.
   But they said the facility could close if the attacks continue.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington that
the United States has been seeking promises from South Korean
authorities that they will provide adequate protection for the
Kwangju center and its staff.
   U.S. cultural centers in Seoul and Pusan have also been attacked,
but not as frequently as the Kwangju center. The centers have
libraries and occassionaly offer speaker programs.
   Anti-U.S. sentiment is relatively high in Kwangju, an opposition
stronghold 180 miles southwest of Seoul, because of the suppression
of the 1980 pro-democracy civil uprising in the southern city.
   By official count, about 200 people were killed and more than
1,000 injured or wounded as government troops put down the nine-day
armed revolt.
   Many opposition and dissident figures claim the United States was
involved in the Kwangju incident by supporting a South Korean
government plan to quell the uprising ruthlessly.
   The United States has denied any involvement in the incident and
agreed to submit written testimony from U.S. officials to South
Korean lawmakers who are conducting parliamentary investigations
into misdeeds committed under Chun.
   The United States has 42,000 troops stationed in South Korea
under a mutual defense treaty and many radical students want the
U.S. soldiers to leave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev     01-31 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev to Visit West Germany, Cuba, Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
will visit West Germany for the first time in June and plans
wide-ranging economic and political talks with the Bonn leadership,
a government spokesman said.
   Gorbachev also will visit Britain and Cuba in April, the British
government and Soviet media said Monday. Gorbachev had planned
visits to those two nations in December but canceled them because of
the earthquake in Armenia.
   In Bonn, chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost said in a
statement Monday that Gorbachev would visit from June 12-15, meeting
several times with Chancellor Helmut Kohl as well as other
high-ranking officials.
   Ost said that after the talks, both countries would issue a joint
communique about ``the future of cooperation'' between West Germany
and the Soviet Union. He did not elaborate.
   When Kohl visited Moscow in October, several economic and
cultural agreements were signed.Similar agreements are expected
during the Gorbachev visit, Ost said.
   West Germany is the Soviet Union's largest Western trading
partner and West German banks have been heavily involved in issuing
new credits to help modernize the communist nation's beleaguered
consumer services industry.
   In London, a spokesman for Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
office said Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, would visit Britain from
April 5-7.
   The Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda reported Monday that
Gorbachev will go to Cuba in early April, but did not give specific
dates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
