<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     01-31 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in calm early European
trading today. Gold prices rose.
   Currency dealers in Frankfurt, West Germany, said the dollar is
in a retrenchment phase after failing to pass key psychological
resistance barriers of 1.870 marks and 130 yen on Monday.
   ``The market was ripe for a downward correction because too many
people were bullish,'' said one dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow
range ahead of the Group of Seven industrialized nations meeting in
Washington on Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.60 yen to a closing 129.13. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 129.40 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8634 West German marks, down from 1.8660
   _1.5845 Swiss francs, down from 1.5884
   _6.3365 French francs, down from 6.3500
   _2.1019 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1085
   _1,362.50 Italian lire, down from 1,365.50
   _1.1815 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1820
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7620, slightly cheaper for
buyers than $1.7650 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $394.65 a troy ounce, up
from $394.50 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $394.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $394.90, up from $394.00 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 59 cents to close at a bid
$396.55.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.84 a troy ounce,
little changed from Monday's $5.83, but its lowest level since March
1987.
</TEXT>
