<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     01-31 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane-Force Winds Blast Through Montana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane-force winds that toppled railroad cars howled through
Montana today as the cold air that caused Alaska's historic cold
snap headed for the lower 48 states after high-temperature records
were set or tied in 16 places.
   The winds, accompanied by snow in some places, gusted more than
100 mph along the east slopes of the Montana Rockies, overturning a
freight train and blowing over grain elevators. No injuries were
reported. Choteau reported a gust of 124 mph. The winds were
expected to spread to Wyoming and Colorado today.
   Moving behind the cold front generating the wind and snow was the
massive dome of cold air that caused the two-week Alaskan cold
spell. Temperatures were expected to drop well below zero by
Wednesday in Montana and North Dakota.
   The high-pressure zone over Alaska set a North American record
Monday for the highest pressure ever recorded: 31.58 inches at
Bettles and Big Delta, Alaska. The old record of 31.53 inches was
set Jan. 1, 1974, over the Yukon Territory, Canada.
   Elsewhere today, rain fell along the northern Pacific Coast and
snow fell on the Cascade mountains of Washington state.
   In Marquette, Mich., the temperature hit 37 degrees early today,
breaking the high-temperature record for the date of 36 degrees set
in 1964. It was the fifth day in a row records were broken or tied
in that city.
   High-temperature records were set Monday in 13 Western and
Midwestern cities, including Rapid City, S.D., where the balmy
72-degree reading surpassed by 3 degrees the mark for the date set
in 1892. It was 67 degrees in Scottsbluff, Neb., breaking the
66-degree record set in 1911 and 62 degrees in Great Falls, Mont.,
breaking the 1962 record of 61. Records were tied in three other
places.
   Today's forecast called for rain in the Pacific Northwest, with
snow in the mountains; snow from the northern Rockies to North
Dakota, northern Minnesota and upper Michigan; scattered rain
showers in the lower Great Lakes and northern New England, with snow
in northern Maine; and continuing strong, gusty winds in the
northern and central Rockies.
   High temperatures were forecast in the teens and 20s from
northern Montana to northern Minnesota; the 30s and 40s from the
Pacific Northwest to the northern and central Rockies, much of the
northern Plains, much of the upper Mississippi Valley, the upper
Great Lakes, New York state and New England; the 70s in Southern
California, southern Arizona, the southern Plains, southern and
western Kansas, the lower Mississippi Valley, the Gulf Coast and
much of Florida; and in the 50s and 60s in much of the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 2
degrees at Havre, Mont., to 70 at the Key West, Fla., Naval Air
Station.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 41 fair; Boston 39 fair; Buffalo 36 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 51 fair; Cincinnati 35 fair; Cleveland 36 fair;
Detroit 36 foggy; Miami 64 fair; New York 42 fair; Philadelphia 41
fair; Pittsburgh 37 cloudy; Portland, Maine 36 fair; Washington 42
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 39 cloudy; Chicago 42 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
43 fair; Denver 45 fair; Des Moines 44 fair; Indianapolis 35 partly
cloudy; Kansas City 48 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 42 partly cloudy;
Nashville 38 fair; New Orleans 51 foggy; St. Louis 45 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 28 fair; Anchorage 0 fair; Las Vegas 42 fair;
Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 51 fair; Salt Lake City 19 foggy; San
Diego 50 fair; San Francisco 47 fair; Seattle 38 windy.
   _Canada: Montreal 28 fair; Toronto 34 hazy.
</TEXT>
