<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Sniper     01-31 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sniper,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlady Unaware She Rented Room to Self-Styled Commando</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Nelson had been afraid to go out
at night because of sniper attacks near her home. Then she learned
that her tenant had confessed to the crimes.
   ``And here he is living in my house,'' Mrs. Nelson exclaimed
Monday after authorities said self-styled commando Yusef Abdullah
Rahman had confessed to one killing and sniper attacks that wounded
three people on eastern Long Island.
   ``I've been sitting here all morning shaking my head back and
forth,'' Mrs. Nelson said. ``I can't believe it.''
   Rahman also has admitted to three killings in Kansas City, Mo.,
authorities said.
   ``There is some indication that he wanted to kill all the drug
dealers in Kansas City,'' Kansas City police Sgt. Pete Edlund said.
   Suffolk County police reported getting telephone calls following
the Long Island attacks in which the caller said his victims were
``drug dealers and crooked cops,'' but police said there was no
evidence that the shootings were drug related.
   Police arrested Rahman on Saturday, six days after weapons found
in a car in Southampton were linked to him and the sniper attacks.
   Police said Rahman told them that he began to play army combat
games when he was 6 years old, bought his first real gun when he was
14 and killed someone four years later.
   ``It appears that he enjoyed killing,'' said Timothy Mazzei,
deputy chief of the district attorney's homicide bureau. ``He got
his kicks out of playing army and shooting people.''
   In written and videotaped confessions after his arrest, Rahman
said he frequently went into the woods to practice combat training
maneuvers.
   On Dec. 5, the day of the first Long Island shooting, Rahman said
he was ``running and crawling'' in the woods when he encountered a
dog, which he shot. He said he then saw the dog's owner, Bernard
Timothy Heaney.
   ``I opened up on him,'' Rahman said in the police confession.
   Police said Heaney was shot to death with a .22-caliber rifle.
   In three other attacks in which people were wounded, Rahman
apparently chose his victims at random, firing into their home
windows before riding away on his bicycle.
   In his final attack, Rahman shot the emergency lights out of a
police patrol car but no one was injured.
   Friends in the lower income neighborhood in Riverhead where
Rahman has rented a room since August described him as an extremely
quiet, devout Muslim.
   ``They seem to be talking about a different person than who lived
here,'' Mrs. Nelson said of police. ``He was very mannerly and
respectful.''
   Mazzei said Rahman told police he knew his actions were wrong and
expressed remorse for his actions.
   ``There is no question there is a sickness involved but we don't
believe he was legally insane,'' he said.
   The case is to be presented to a grand jury later this week.
   Rahman was placed on a suicide watch at the Suffolk County jail,
where he is being held without bail, Warden Salvatore Romano said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
