<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     01-31 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Publishes Birthday Message to Higgins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife and daughter of kidnapped U.S.
Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins sent him birthday greetings in a
message published today by the Beirut newspaper An-Nahar.
   Higgins, who was abducted Feb. 17, 1988, marked his 44th birthday
Jan. 15.
   ``Mrs. Robin Higgins and her daughter, Chrissy, apparently hoped
that the letter would be published on Jan. 15 to coincide with Mr.
Higgins' birthday. But the letter, mailed ... on Jan. 3, was
received by An-Nahar yesterday (Monday),'' the newspaper said in
Arabic.
   An-Nahar published the text in English, apparently hoping
Higgins' captors would allow him to read it.
   The letter said: ``Dear William Richard Higgins, my husband:
   ``I send you warm birthday greetings. We miss you very much
today, as always, but send you special love this day.
   ``We hope and pray that 1989 brings us happier days, and that we
can celebrate all the important days we've missed _ our anniversary,
our birthdays, Christmas _ together, soon.
   ``Your love has kept me warm and strong, my birthday wish for you
is that my love can do the same for you until we are together
again.''
   The letter was signed: ``Love always, Robin and Chrissy.''
   Higgins, of Danville, Ky., headed a 76-man team of U.N. observers
stationed along the border with Israel when he was kidnapped near
the southern city of Tyre.
   His captors, the pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth, said Dec. 12 that the Vietnam veteran had been
``sentenced'' to death for spying for Israel. The United States and
the United Nations have denied the charge.
   The same group claimed it has abducted 12 Lebanese Jews since
1984, and has said it killed eight of the Jewish captives. The
bodies of four of the Jews were found in Beirut.
   Higgins is among 15 foreign captives missing in Lebanon since
1985. Terry Anderson, 41, the chief Middle East correspondent for
the Associated Press, is the longest-held of the hostages. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
