<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-US     01-31 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Departs for Summit With Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita left Japan for the
United States today for talks with President Bush on U.S.-Japanese
cooperation in international affairs as well as trade and defense
issues.
   Takeshita's small delegation includes his wife, Naoko, and
Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno. They are to stay one day in New York
before traveling to Washington for the summit Wednesday.
   Senior Foreign Ministry officials said they expect the meeting _
Bush's first session with a foreign head of government since he took
office Jan. 20 _ will allow the two leaders to discuss issues of
global importance and get to know each other better.
   Takeshita, 64, wants to discuss with Bush ``how we can best
coordinate important issues with the United States, mainly on the
international situation. ... We do not intend to raise specific
issues,'' said Yukio Okamoto, director of the Foreign Ministry's
First North American Division.
   Recent criticism of Japan's large trade surplus and defense
spending by Bush appointees, including Trade
Representative-designate Carla Hills and Secretary of
Defense-designate John Tower, suggests the Americans may want to
discuss specific issues.
   While in Washington, Takeshita is to present to former U.S.
Ambassador Mike Mansfield his government's prestigious First Class
Order of the Rising Sun award. Mansfield, 85, retired last year
after being ambassador to Japan for 11 years. Foreign Ministry
officials said the medal has been awarded to only two other
foreigners: Gen. Douglas MacArthur and former West German Chancellor
Konrad Adenauer.
   Takeshita is to visit Los Angeles and meet briefly with former
President Ronald Reagan before returning to Tokyo on Feb. 7.
</TEXT>
