<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     01-31 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Reported Wounded in Uprising Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fought with youths who threw
stones and hoisted outlawed Palestinian flags today during another
general strike in the occupied territories, and 17 Arabs were
reported shot and wounded.
   Also today, a fundamentalist Moslem leader in the occupied Gaza
Strip said he would back elections in the territories under
international supervision and would be willing to meet with Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin. The minister has proposed a peace plan that
includes such elections.
   Today's general strike, which shut businesses and halted
transport, was called by the Palestinian uprising leaders, who are
backed by the Palestine Liberation Organization. On Monday, PLO
activists persuaded Palestinians to ignore calls for a work stoppage
ordered by a rival Moslem extremist group, Hamas.
   Arab doctors said 17 Palestinians were shot and wounded in
clashes throughout the territories. The army said it was checking
reported casualties.
   The worst clash was in the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya refugee camp,
where residents hung 10 outlawed Palestinian flags from utility
poles, Arab reports said. Nine Palestinian youths, including a
13-year-old, were shot and wounded, Arab doctors said.
   A 75-year-old woman was shot in the face during a clash with
soldiers in a village near the West Bank town of Jenin, said doctors
at Al-Ittihad Hospital in Nablus.
   Seven other Palestinians were wounded in clashes in Gaza City and
the Nusseirat refugee camp, as well as the West Bank's Balata and
Jenin refugee camps, Arab doctors said. The wounded included a
16-year-old boy shot in the head, they said.
   The 13-month revolt, which has spawned repeated protests and
general strikes, has claimed the lives of 370 Palestinians and 15
Israelis. The Palestinians are protesting occupation by Israel,
which seized the lands from neighboring Arab states in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual leader of the fundamentalist
Hamas movement, said he supported an Israeli proposal to hold
elections in the occupied lands, but he said the vote must be under
international supervision.
   ``There is no escape from a dialogue,'' Yassin said on Israel
television's Arabic-language program.
   Yassin said he would be ready to meet with Rabin if an invitation
were extended, said television reporter Yoni Ben-Menachem, who
interviewed him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
