<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Monument     01-31 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Monument,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afrikaners Plan Monument to Architect of Apartheid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afrikaner political leaders
hope to raise $420,000 to build a monument honoring former Prime
Minister Hendrik Verwoerd, one of the principal architects of
apartheid.
   State-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said a site has been
set aside for the monument in downtown Pretoria, the administrative
capital. The money would be raised through a nationwide campaign.
   It quoted Willem Cruywagen, chairman of the monument committee,
as saying Verwoerd deserved to be honored because he oversaw South
Africa's establishment as a republic when it left the British
Commonwealth in 1961.
   Verwoerd's policies showed enmity toward the Africans, the
British and Jews. He laid the groundwork for the government's racial
separation policies after becoming minister of native affairs in
1950. He became prime minister in 1958 and held the office until his
assassination in 1966.
   One of his chief creations was the homeland system. He envisioned
a future South Africa in which only whites would be citizens, while
blacks would have voting rights only in nominally autonomous tribal
homelands.
</TEXT>
