<FIRST>r i PM-BerlinElections     01-31 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin Elections,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mainstream German Parties Talk After Strong Far-right Showing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City conservatives shunned ultra-rightists who made
a surprisingly strong showing in West Berlin elections and instead
opened talks today on forming a mainstream coalition with leftists.
   The ultra-rightist Republicans, campaigning on a platform of
ridding Berlin of foreigners, captured 7.5 percent of the vote and
11 seats in the West Berlin legislature. It was the first time they
gained a place in that body since their party was formed in 1983.
   However, the conservative Christian Democrats, who suffered heavy
losses in Sunday's vote, ruled out a coalition with Republicans.
   The Republicans' national chairman is Franz Schoenhuber, a
66-year-old former Nazi Waffen SS soldier. Under West Germany's
complicated election laws, the party will also gain two seats in the
national parliament after the December 1990 federal elections.
   National party leaders instructed West Berlin's Christian
Democratic mayor, Eberhard Diepgen, to begin today's coalition talks
with his leftist Social Democratic rival Walter Momper.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats lost a natural ally
when the centrist Free Democrats failed to gain any seats in the
legislature. The two parties had governed West Berlin in a coalition
that also controls the federal government.
   Sunday's voting gave the Christian Democrats and Social Democrats
55 seats each in the 138-seat house, while the far-left Alternative
List came away with 17 seats.
   Momper said he would not govern with the Alternatives as long as
they insist on cutting back the number of Allied troops stationed in
West Berlin.
   The outcome was overshadowed by the success of the Republicans,
who say they have 1,000 card-carrying members in West Berlin and
more than 7,000 nationwide.
   Kohl told a news conference in Bonn on Monday the outcome was
worrisome because of the Republicans' appeal among West Germans, who
are increasingly worried by a wave of foreigners competing for jobs,
housing and social services.
   ``There is an urgent need to discuss these problems and come up
with better solutions,'' Kohl said.
   Mayor Diepgen, calling the elections ``a bitter loss,'' said the
obvious surge in ultra-right support poses a serious challenge for
the leading political parties in the city and country.
</TEXT>
