<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-LeVeque     01-31 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-LeVeque,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Of Early Keystone Kops Dies At Age 92</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eddie LeVeque, the last of the original
Keystone Kops, the troupe of slapstick gendarmes whose comic antics
endeared them to a generation of silent film fans, has died at age
92.
   LeVeque, who was born in Mexico, died Saturday, said his son,
Gilbert.
   The actor's first role in a major film was in 1914 in the D.W.
Griffith classic ``Intolerance.''
   He later joined the Keystone production company and appeared as
one of the Keystone Kops, which usually were featured in a series of
misadventures that involved split-second sight gags and an
inevitable chase scene.
   LeVeque quit the studio in 1917 to serve in World War I. That
same year producer Mack Sennett shaped a second group of Keystone
Kops that continued to perform into the 1920s.
   After the war, LeVeque appeared in such epic silent films as
``The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse'' with Rudolph Valentino and
``The Black Pirate'' with Douglas Fairbanks Sr.
   He later worked in radio as a disc jockey and continued to play
small roles in films, often cast as a kindly priest.
   He is survived by a son, two daughters and six grandchildren.
</TEXT>
