<FIRST>r a PM-Amish-Freed     01-31 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amish-Freed,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amish Man Freed From Jail In Dispute Over Treatment of Cancer-Stricken
Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has released an Amish man
jailed for contempt for refusing to turn over his 6-year-old son for
cancer treatments despite warnings the child will die without
medical help.
   Hardin District Judge Janet Coleman, who had found Danny Mast in
contempt of court Friday, ordered his release Monday after
concluding jailing the father would not help the child, Amos.
   In a brief statement, Coleman said: ``I have done my best to
convey to Mr. Mast the seriousness of his legal position in the hope
that he might relent and not allow this child to die untreated. He
has not done so.''
   But the judge overruled a motion to have all previous orders in
the case canceled _ meaning Mast was still held in contempt of court.
   Amos was diagnosed with cancer in October and was under the care
of Kosair Children's Hospital in Louisville. In December, a hearing
was held after the child's physician contacted the Hardin County
attorney about the case. At a second hearing in early January,
hospital officials said the child had not resumed chemotherapy.
   Without the treatment, the boy is expected to live only a few
months, said Assistant County Attorney Chris Shaw.
   ``There's really no doubt in my mind that, barring a miracle,
this boy is going to die,'' Shaw said. ``You keep hoping they're
going to listen to reason.''
   Relatives and family members said the child is not in the
community and may have been taken to another state.
   Monroe Miller, Mast's father-in-law, said last week that he
believes his grandson is being helped by a ``natural'' treatment of
herbs and vitamins.
   Mast is a member of an Amish community of 15 families living in
Sonora in southern Hardin County. Their religion teaches separation
from the world and stresses simplicity as a way of life.
</TEXT>
