<FIRST>r w PM-SkinnerNomination     01-31 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skinner Nomination,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs Bush's DOT Nominee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation
Committee voted unanimously to recommend that Samuel Skinner, head
of the Chicago area transit system, be confirmed as secretary of
transportation.
   The senators took less than five seconds to give voice-vote
approval to President Bush's nominee and send his name to the Senate
floor.
   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., praised all of Bush's Cabinet
selections and said that he was ``deeply impressed by the openness,
integrity and the smarts'' of both Skinner and Robert Mosbacher,
whose nomination as commerce secretary also was approved by the
committee.
   Skinner, 50, who is a licensed pilot, promised during his
confirmation hearings last week to support mandatory drug testing
for transportation workers in safety-related jobs and to combat air
terrorism.
   Skinner also said he would work to build up the Coast Guard and
the maritime industry and said he planned to formulate a long-range
national transportation policy.
   Committee Chairman Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., said he expected the
Skinner and Mosbacher nominations to be approved by the full Senate
later in the day.
