<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0512 01-31 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Missiles Reported to Kill 70 Amid Pullout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet missile attack; UPDATE
with U.S. Embassy staff departing; CLARIFY that diplomats believe attacks
aimed at forcing political settlement; picks up 7th graf pvs `In Washington...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Four long-range Soviet missiles slammed
into villages today near the main Soviet withdrawal route and killed
70 people, Moslem guerrillas said.
   Western diplomats said an upsurge in Soviet and government
attacks during the past week appeared to be aimed at pressuring the
guerrillas to reach a political settlement with the Soviet-backed
government in Kabul.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Red
Army is expected to be out of the Kabul area by Feb. 6.
   Moscow pledged in a U.N.-brokered accord last year to remove all
of its more than 100,000 combat troops from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   Although the final phase of the pullout is in full swing in
Kabul, the diplomats did not predict when the Soviets would leave
other parts of the country, notably Shindand air base in western
Farah Province.
   Jamiat-i-Islami, one of the major Afghan guerrilla factions, said
it received news of today's missile attack in a radio report from
its commander, Ahmad Shah Masood.
   The guerrillas said the SS-1 Scud missiles hit in the Khinja
section of the Panjshir Valley about 30 miles northeast of the
Salang Highway.
   There was no independent confirmation of the missile attacks.
   Official Afghan media have accused Masood of attacking convoys
carrying food to the capital. However, the Jamiat faction said the
convoys also were loaded with arms and ammunition for the Kabul
regime.
   Combined Soviet and Afghan government forces have leveled
villages and killed hundreds of people since Jan. 23 in coordinated
high-altitude bombing attacks, artillery barrages, missile launches
and ground assaults, according to Western and guerrilla sources.
   Most of the attacks were targeted along the Salang Highway, the
Red Army's main pullout route between Kabul and the Soviet border,
they said. But they said villages up to 30 miles away from the road
also suffered.
   Also today, the 11 remaining members of the U.S. Embassy staff in
Kabul left the country a day after closing their mission because of
concerns about fighting in Kabul after the Red Army leaves. The
embassy staff flew out of the Afghan capital aboard a chartered
plane to New Delhi, India, and they are expected to go to Washington
later this week.
   Although the embassy was closed Monday, the Americans could not
immediately depart because Kabul airport was shut by a three-inch
snowfall.
   In Washington on Monday, the State Department accused the Soviet
Union of pursuing what it called a ``scorched earth'' policy as its
troops withdraw.
   By contrast, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said,
U.S.-armed Afghan insurgents were showing restraint toward the
departing Red Army.
   ``The Soviets continue what might even be called a scorched earth
policy, as they continue very, very intensive air activity,'' Redman
said. ``We just don't believe that this kind of a policy is what is
called for at the time when Afghanistan ought to be looking to the
future.''
   One Western diplomat in Islamabad said ``the Soviet bombing and
missile attacks cannot be explained by a putative Soviet desire to
protect its retreating troops.''
   He said the guerrillas ``have not been attacking the withdrawing
Soviet troops on the Salang or elsewhere.''
   ``The situation for survivors of these attacks is bleak,'' said
another diplomat. ``Survivors have been left homeless in the midst
of one of the worst winters in recent memory, in most cases without
provisions.''
   The communists seized power in Kabul in a 1978 coup, touching off
a civil war with Moslem insurgents. Soviet forces intervened in
December 1979 to replace one pro-Moscow government with another,
then remained to fight the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BeefDispute     01-31 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beef Dispute,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Groups Back Europe's Ban Of Hormone-Treated Beef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer groups are supporting a European ban
of hormone-treated beef from the United States and say consumers
here also should demand the right to buy meat certified as
chemical-free.
   The Consumer Federation of America and other consumer advocates
are also urging President Bush to reverse the administration's
refusal to let Texas and other states export hormone-free beef while
Europe and the United States spar over the safety of growth hormones.
   The consumer advocates want Bush to negotiate a 90-day
cooling-off period with the European Economic Community to keep the
dispute from escalating into a trade war.
   ``If the European Community and the United States proceed in the
direction that they're going we very well could have a real trade
war in which consumers on both sides of the Atlantic are really
going to be the ones who get hurt,'' Rod Leonard, executive director
of the Community Nutrition Institute, said Monday.
   The EEC has said it will slap tough tariffs on American walnuts
and dried fruit if no progress is made by Feb. 20 to end the dispute
over hormones used by domestic producers to fatten cattle more
quickly.
   The EEC on Jan. 1 banned imports of beef treated with hormones,
contending they are a health threat. The United States disputes
those claims and retaliated against the loss of about $100 million
in annual beef sales by setting $100 million in higher tariffs on a
variety of Common Market goods.
   Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower has been working
with the EEC to certify hormone-free beef from Texas and find buyers
for the Lone Star exports.
   But the U.S. Trade Representative's office last week said such a
deal would not be allowed because the U.S. Department of Agriculture
has no way to certify beef is hormone-free.
   Leonard said he believes USDA ``can do a certification procedure
if it wants to'' and questioned the administration's decision to bar
such exports as farmers, inching toward recovery after their worst
recession in decades, have an opportunity to find new markets.
Leonard said a 90-day cooling off period would give Bush time to
develop a hormone-free beef certification procedure.
   The Consumer Federation of American said the EEC's ban is ``an
issue of consumer protection and not trade protection.''
   ``Serious questions have been raised about the necessity and
safety of hormone additives in meat. Through the ban, consumers in
Europe have expressed their preference for hormone-free beef. They
have opted to be safe, rather than sorry, and we believe that
preference must be respected,'' said Sandra Eskin of the CFA, which
represents more than 240 state, local and national organizations.
   She said U.S. consumers should push their preference for
hormone-free beef and urge the USDA to develop a procedure that
certifies beef has not been treated with hormones and other drugs or
chemicals.
   Rich Parker, a spokesman for the American Meat Institute, said
prices would increase if producers stopped using growth hormones.
The AMI contends the hormone issue is a trade barrier that has
``nothing to do with safety,'' Parker said. ``Europe wants to be a
net exporter, not a net importer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0082 </DOCNO>
