<SECOND>PM-BRF--Wedding Fraud,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty to Defeauding Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of marrying at least four women has
pleaded guilty to defrauding two women lured to the altar by his
promises to share an inheritance with them.
   Victor Barr, 49, married at least four women under false
pretenses, lived off their cash and credit, and then deserted them,
federal authorities said.
   He pleaded guilty Monday in U.S. District Court to charges
stemming from two of those marriages. Barr told U.S. District Judge
Barbara Hackett that he married Carol Kelly of Pontiac in April 1988
and defrauded her of $20,000.
   ``I told her I need a wife to marry me for six months and I told
her I'd give her $200,000 for marrying me,'' said Barr, who faces up
to 27 months in prison and a $120,000 fine under terms of his plea
bargain.
   He also admitted marrying Margaret Gearing of Cleveland in July
1988 under false pretenses and defrauding her of $30,000 by using
her credit cards and writing her bad checks to cover expenses.
   When Barr married Gearing, he was already married to Kelly and to
Lois Mauger of Cheektowaga, N.Y., federal investigators said. In
November, he married another woman from Reno, Nev., but she
discovered his scheme and had him arrested.
