<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-MafiaArms     01-31 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Mafia Arms,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Break Up Mafia-Terrorist Arms and Drugs Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have broken an international
ring of Sicilian Mafia and right-wing terrorists who trafficked in
drugs and weapons, newspapers reported today.
   Arrest warrants for 72 suspects wanted for criminal association,
arms and drug trafficking have been issued in Italy and abroad,
including the United States and Switzerland, the reports said
quoting authorities at a Monday news conference. Names of suspects
living outside Italy were not immediately disclosed.
   Authorities said they arrested at least 48 people Monday for
involvement in the ring, whose plots included plans to sell French
warplanes to the West African nation of Guinea-Bissau.
   The investigation extends to Chile, Argentina, Brazil and Peru,
Canada and Nigeria, the Turin daily La Stampa said.
   Warrants were issued by Judge Alba Dova of the Tuscan coastal
city of Massa Carrara, where the investigation was coordinated for
more than a year.
   Dova said the link between the Mafia and right-wing extremists
``leads one to think of the existence of an international extremist
right-wing political organization that finances itself through
illegal financial operations and ties with organized crime.''
   Much of the illegal trafficking was arranged through two Italian
import-export firms called Eurogross and Fininvest 2000, authorities
said.
   The ring's activities included deals in stolen art, cars and
foreign currency, with some money recycled through coded Swiss bank
accounts, they said.
   A key figure named in the warrants is Marco Affatigato, a reputed
leader of New Order, an extreme rightist group accused of a string
of terrorist attacks in Italy in the 1970s and early 1980s.
Affatigato is believed to be in France.
   Among Mafia suspects rounded up in raids were members of the
Corleone family, considered Sicily's most powerful Mafia clan, and
of the Minore family from Trapani, a Sicilian port linked to
clandestine drug and arms shipments. The man considered the Corleone
family's ``cashier,'' Michele Cillari, was among more noted figures
arrested on Monday.
   The judge said the investigation stemmed from the 1987 discovery
of arms and drugs aboard a Lebanese ship off Italy's Adriatic coast.
The ship set out from Beirut and was loaded with heroin, hashish, an
anti-tank bazooka, a Soviet grenade-launcher and other arms.
   Initially, it was linked to alleged arms smuggling between Italy
and the Middle East, including clandestine delivery of mines to
Iran. Several Italian industrialists and arms manufacturers were
arrested but later released and charges dropped.
   On Monday, official said documents seized in connection with the
ship led them to the ring. Evidence included false certificates of a
dummy bank called the ``Canadian Credit Bank'' of Detroit.
   The gang allegedly plotted to deliver French Mirage jetfighters
to Guinea-Bissau, acting as middlemen in return for kickbacks,
authorities said.
   The scheme allegedly involved an Italian representative of the
African country and an official of the French aircraft company
Dassault-Breguet. It was not known if the planes were delivered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
