<FIRST>u a PM-Prince-SkiDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0504 01-31 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prince-Ski Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cousin of Spain's King Dies in Colorado Skiing Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT that Alfonso not a prince, but
duke. Also CORRECTS spelling of Sophia to Sofia. A longer version moved
on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MOSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEAVER CREEK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain's Duke of Cadiz, who died after
skiing into a cable at the World Alpine Ski Championships, was
remembered as someone who liked to ``ski fast and drive fast.''
   Alfonso de Borbon y de Dampierre, a 52-year-old first cousin of
King Juan Carlos and member of the international governing body of
ski racing, had been skiing Monday with companions when he collided
with the cable, which was being raised to support a banner at the
finish line of a course at Beaver Creek Resort, officials said.
   No official cause of death has been determined, but he suffered
severe neck lacerations, said Jeff Beavers of the Eagle County
Sheriff's Department.
   King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia in Spain expressed their sorrow
over his death. The victim's brother, Gonzalo de Borbon, said he
would fly from Madrid to Colorado today to bring his body back to
Spain for burial.
   The accident occurred Monday afternoon as the slalom course was
being converted for downhill competition. Members of the ski patrol
and emergency personnel attended to the duke at the scene, but he
was pronounced dead on arrival at Vail Valley Medical Center,
Beavers said.
   Beavers said authorities were continuing to interview witnesses.
   All Monday night events were canceled by World Championship
officials, who ordered flags flown at half-staff and made plans for
a memorial service.
   De Borbon, who was not in the line of succession to the Spanish
throne, had served as Spain's ambassador to Sweden from 1969 to 1973.
   An avid skier, he was president of the Spanish Skiing Federation
from 1977 to 1984 and president of the Spanish Olympic Committee
from 1984 to 1987. He was a member of the Council of the
International Ski Federation.
   ``This is a very sad occasion,'' said Bob Knous, head of the
Vail-Beaver Creek World Championship Organizing Committee. ``This
was something none of us ever hoped to see anywhere, especially at
an event of this magnitude.''
   De Borbon's father was the elder brother of King Juan Carlos'
father. Both men's fathers were the sons of King Alfonso XIII, who
abdicated the Spanish throne in 1931.
   De Borbon was a descendant of Louis XIV, the French Sun King, and
was the Bourbon or ``legitimist'' candidate for king had the
monarchy ever been restored in France.
   In 1972, he married Carmen Franco, granddaughter of the late
Spanish dictator Francisco Franco, but they divorced in 1982.
   In February 1984, he again made headlines following an auto
accident in which the older of his two sons was killed on the way
home from a skiing trip in the Spanish Basque country. A judge ruled
that de Borbon, who was driving, had been negligent and stripped him
of the custody of his other son.
   Francisco Fernandez-Ochoa, the slalom gold medalist at the 1972
Olympics and a close friend of the duke, said de Borbon liked to
``ski fast and drive fast.''
   Referring to the duke's divorce, the fatal auto accident and the
skiing tragedy, Fernandez-Ochoa described the victim as ``an unlucky
person. Bad things happened to him.''
   It was the second tragedy involving a ski official during a major
event in the past year. In the 1988 Winter Olympics at Calgary, Dr.
Joerg Oberhammer, a prominent Austrian surgeon affiliated with that
country's ski team, was killed when he was knocked into the path of
a snow-grooming machine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
