<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Hirohito     01-31 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Hirohito,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hirohito Named Showa in Posthumous Palace Rite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito was given the posthumous name
``Showa'' in a palace ceremony attended today by top government
leaders and court officials.
   The ceremony, held in the Imperial Palace's Pine Room where the
late monarch's body lies in state, is among dozens being performed
before Hirohito is buried Feb. 24.
   Showa, which means ``enlightened peace,'' has been used over 62
years to refer to Hirohito's reign, which began in 1926 and ended
with his death from cancer at age 87 on Jan. 7.
   Among dignitaries at the ceremony were Hirohito's son, newly
enthroned Emperor Akihito, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and
Supreme Court Chief Justice Koichi Taguchi.
   Also today, the Cabinet declared Akihito's Dec. 23 birthday a
national holiday, while Hirohito's birthday on April 29 will be
renamed ``Greenery Day'' and remain a holiday.
   Prince Aya, second in line to the throne after Crown Prince
Naruhito, will return to Britain on Wednesday to continue zoology
studies at Oxford University, Imperial Household Agency officials
said. Aya is to return to Japan for his grandfather's funeral.
</TEXT>
