<HEAD>National Guard Troops Sent to Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRANSTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor ordered National Guard troops
to help with patient care today at a state hospital, where unionized
employees have staged a sickout since Saturday. Most of the workers
later showed up.
   General Hospital spokesman Dan Caley said hospital officials
requested the troops from Gov. Edward D. Diprete, and the
approximately 60 uniformed Guard members were assigned to work
throughout the hospital.
   ``They're not here for security at all,'' Caley said.
   About 80 employees eventually showed up at the state General
Hospital this morning, out of 106 scheduled to work, Caley said.
   ``Things seemed to have cooled off a little,'' said Fran
Segerson, a spokeswoman for the governor. ``With 80 percent of the
employees working, it seems like some of the employees are getting
tired of this.''
   Talks continued between the hospital and union leaders to end the
sickout by attendants and licensed practical nurses, but Caley had
no details of the talks. The union, which has refused to comment,
reportedly is angry over proposed schedule changes designed to
reduce the hospital's burgeoning overtime bills.
   Segerson said the governor called out the Guard after a meeting
Monday night between Thomas D. Romeo, director of the state
Department of Mental Health, Retardation and Hospitals, and
officials from Local 1350 of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Workers failed to produce a settlement.
   ``I think that last night they hoped to get the problem resolved,
but when it looked like they couldn't do that, he wanted to ensure
that patient services were not affected,'' Segerson said.
