<HEAD>Sightseeing Ship Stranded in Antartic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 tourists and 50 crew
members were evacuated from an Argentine navy oceanographic vessel
after the ship ran aground in the Antarctic, an official report said
today.
   The ship Bahia Paraiso sustained three gashes when it ran aground
Saturday in the Bismarck Strait near the U.S. exploration base
Palmer on the Antarctic Peninsula, the Telam state news agency said.
Three days later, it was listing 11 degrees to its port side in high
winds and heavy seas.
   The tourists, mostly from the United States and Europe, and crew
were taken first to Palmer.
   Some went on to the Chilean air force base on King George Island,
840 miles south of the Chilean port Punta Arenas. Others flew by
military transport to Argentina's naval base at Rio Gallegos in
southernmost Santa Cruz Province, and then on to the capital, Buenos
Aires.
   There were no reported injuries, and many passengers chose to
resume their vacations.
   Crew members and specialists waited at the Palmer base for a
break in the weather that would allow them to return to the ship and
begin repairs.
