<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Retrial     01-31 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Retrial,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Freed After 30 Years on Death Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today acquitted a man who spent 30 years on
death row for the kidnap and murder of a 6-year-old girl.
   It was Japan's fourth case in six years in which a death row
inmate was acquitted of murder in a retrial. In all four cases,
judges said confessions, which defendants made during interrogation
but later recanted, lacked credibility.
   After today's verdict, the court freed Masao Akabori, 59, who had
been sentenced to death by a district court in 1958. The sentence
was upheld by the Supreme Court in 1960, but a retrial began in 1987
in the Shizuoka District Court after four appeals by Akabori.
   ``I am glad I won the appeal because I am innocent. And I am so
thankful to my lawyers and all the people who have supported me and
encouraged me through the past 35 years,'' Akabori said in a
statement.
   His lawyers said he managed to avoid hanging because of an active
support group. Such a long stretch on death row is rare but not
unprecedented in Japan.
   Akabori was arrested two months after 6-year-old Hisako Sano was
kidnapped and strangled March 10, 1954, near her home in Shimada
about 125 miles west of Tokyo.
   Under police questioning, he confessed to the crime, but he later
withdrew the confession and pleaded innocent.
   Today's verdict by a three-judge panel said Akabori's confession
lacked credibility, and there was no other credible evidence linking
him to the crime.
   Akabori's lawyers said he is entitled to $930,200 in government
compensation for his wrongful time behind bars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0093 </DOCNO>
