<FIRST>r a PM-KennedyFliers     01-31 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kennedy Fliers,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homecoming For Kennedy Fliers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fliers from the aircraft carrier USS
John F. Kennedy returned home today feeling relieved and proud after
a six-month voyage that included the shooting down of two Libyan
jets over the Mediterranean.
   ``The way the crew reacted was in a very professional manner and
that's what we're all about. We did as we were trained to do,'' said
Capt. Jerry Norris, commander of Airwing 3 aboard the Kennedy.
   Two F-14 Tomcat jet fighters from the Kennedy shot down two
Libyan jets that approached them in a hostile manner on Jan. 4.
   While planes from the Kennedy returned today, the carrier and its
battle group will return to their homeports Wednesday.
   Today's return to the Oceana Naval Air Station and the Norfolk
Naval Air Station coincided with a visit by President Bush to the
carrier USS America at the Norfolk Naval Base, but he had no plans
to greet the aviators.
   A Navy spokesman said he doubted the fliers would feel left out.
``Mostly they're going to be concerned about their families,'' said
Navy spokesman Phil Wilkinson.
   Among the friends and relatives waiting to greet the returning
fliers were Loretta and Clyde Smith of Natrona Heights, Penn., along
with six relatives and a large banner reading ``Welcome Home
Shawn,'' to greet their son, Lt. Cmdr. Shawn Smith.
   This was the third time the family has gathered from around the
country to meet Shawn when he returned from a deployment, Mrs. Smith
said. ``This was the most frightening one of all.''
   The Navy did not release the names of the pilots involved in the
shooting for security reasons.
   The fliers said the shooting was a small part of a deployment
they were relieved to see end on schedule.
   ``It's our job,'' Shawn Smith said. ``Just the long separations
make it hard.''
</TEXT>
