<FIRST>u w PM-TowerConfirmation 1stLd-Writethru a0449 01-31 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower Confirmation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Get Their Turn in Tower Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOP 11 grafs new with Weyrich comments; picks up 9th graf pvs,
Tower told.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative activist told the Senate Armed
Services Committee today that he encountered Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower in an inebriated condition on several
occasions accompanied by women other than his wife.
   The witness, Paul Weyrich, chairman of the Free Congress
Foundation, has opposed Tower's nomination on grounds he is soft on
Star Wars. Today Weyrich questioned whether Tower had the moral
character to oversee the Pentagon reforms that President Bush has
promised he would initiate.
   ``I have made enough personal observations of this man here in
Washington to have serious reservations about his moral character,''
Weyrich said.
   Weyrich claimed that Bush's transition team received hundreds of
letters criticizing Tower, some containing specific allegations of
``moral impropriety'' against the nominee, but did not bring the
letters to the president's attention.
   Weyrich said he never saw the letters, but ``I have encountered
the senator in a condition lacking sobriety as well as with women he
was not married to.''.
   ``The encounters occurred frequently enough to make an
impression. I did encounter this on a number of occasions,'' he said.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the panel, immediately
suggested that discussions of any information Weyrich had on the
nominee's personal life be taken up in a closed session scheduled
this afternoon. Tower was to testify in that session.
   Tower was dogged by allegations of drinking and womanizing before
his nomination was announced by Bush. In divorce papers filed by his
second wife, Lila Burt Cummings, Tower was accused of ``marital
misconduct.''
   Bush has defended Tower, saying an FBI background check found
nothing that would prevent him from serving as defense secretary.
   Tower, a 63-year-old Texas Republican, served 24 years in the
Senate, including a brief tenure as chairman of the Armed Services
Committee from 1981-84.
   ``He considers SDI (Strategic Defense Initiative) a bargaining
chip. We don't,'' Weyrich has said previously. ``He's not in favor
of military reform. We think military reform is necessary
particularly in this year of budget crunch.''
   Tower told the committee last week he does not ``believe that we
can devise an umbrella that can protect the entire American
population from nuclear incineration. I think that's unrealistic.''
   Tower said a more limited system might work but cautioned that
``it remains to be seen whether that is a realistic objective.''
   In his two days of testimony, Tower also pledged to remain
objective in Pentagon decision-making despite receiving more than $1
million in consulting fees from defense contractors.
   But Jackson, a senior fellow and associate professor at the
Fulbright Institute of International Relations at the University of
Arkansas, questioned Tower's pledge.
   ``Mr. Tower is the wrong man for this job at this time,'' Jackson
said in a telephone interview Monday. ``I plan to focus on how he
symbolizes the revolving door syndrome in the defense culture as he
called it.''
   Jackson, onetime foreign policy adviser to former Secretary of
State Edmund Muskie, said Tower showed little interest in defense
reform when the Texas senator served as chairman of the Armed
Services panel.
   ``He's a bad choice when we need someone whose track record is
sound,'' Jackson said.
   Phillips, president of the National Council for Industrial
Defense, said Monday he is unsure whether Tower will implement the
reform recommendations of the Packard Commission, the presidential
panel that called for strengthening the authority of the chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   ``I'm not sure he knows what's involved, what kind of buzzsaw
he'll run into,'' said Phillips.
   Phillips, who heads a non-profit, non-partisan organization that
includes small defense subcontractors, also criticized Tower's
record on foreign sourcing for contracts.
   ``I don't know what his position is,'' Phillips said. ``When he
was on the committee he didn't do anything to help our industries,
then when he left he worked for British Aerospace (as a consultant).
A lot of our people have gone out of business.''
</TEXT>
