<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Expels 4 Civilians from Security Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied militiamen
today expelled four Lebanese from Israel's self-proclaimed security
zone in south Lebanon, police said.
   The action brings to 74 the number of people expelled from the
area this month.
   Police said three women expelled _ Majida Ghader, 29, Insaf Ali
Hinnawi, 21, and Youmna Markiz, 21 _ were teachers from the Sunni
Moslem village of Shibaa. A man, Yousef Sleem, 18, was expelled from
Houla.
   Ms. Markiz told reporters in Rashaya, north of the security zone,
that an officer of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia
told her they were expelled ``because we had participated in
demonstrations against the establishment of an Israeli-sponsored
local administration in Shibaa.
   ``They also accused us of inciting our students against this
administration,'' she said.
   On Jan. 25, Israeli troops and the militia expelled 40 civilians
from Shibaa, including seven women and 25 children, after residents
marched to protest creation of a local administration.
   Israel established the 6-to-10 mile deep security zone to curb
guerrilla raids from south Lebanon when it withdrew the bulk of its
army in 1985, three years after invading Lebanon.
