<FIRST>r a PM-McNamara 1stLd-Writethru a0506 01-31 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McNamara, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0506,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled U.S. Attorney For Massachusetts Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Jeremiah O'Sullivan ...' to UPDATE with swearing
in.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney for Massachusetts resigned
following months of allegations that he politicized his office and
lied about seeing his predecessor smoke marijuana.
   ``The work of this office is far too important to be sidetracked
by any controversy,'' Frank L. McNamara Jr. said in announcing his
resignation Monday.
   In his brief statement, McNamara did not mention a continuing
Justice Department investigation into his conduct that staff members
said had hindered the office's activities.
   He said he intended to return to private practice.
   Jeremiah O'Sullivan, head of the New England Organized Crime
Strike Force, was named the interim head of the office and was sworn
in this morning before U.S. Judge Edward F. Harrington in Boston.
   McNamara, a 41-year-old Republican, has been the target of a
Justice Department investigation since November, when investigators
found no evidence to support allegations that he saw William F. Weld
smoke marijuana. During the probe, McNamara admitted to smoking
marijuana himself.
   On Friday, 28 of the 39 assistant U.S. attorneys working for
McNamara wrote to U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, urging him
to expedite McNamara's departure.
   ``Mr. McNamara's conduct and performance while United States
attorney is resulting in a loss of confidence in the adminstration
of justice,'' the letter said. ``The credibility and operations of
this office will continue to be damaged ... unless he is removed.''
   Prosecutors who had been critical of McNamara privately expressed
relief over his decision to leave.
   President Reagan nominated McNamara to replace Weld in April
1987, when Weld ascended to head the Justice Department's criminal
division. But McNamara's confirmation was held up while the FBI
investigated his failure to pay income tax for several years, and
irregularities in his congressional campaign finances after his
unsuccessful 1982 race against then-House Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip''
O'Neill Jr.
   During the confirmation process, McNamara said he believed Weld
was trying to scuttle his nomination and told investigators that he
had seen Weld drunk on a couple of occasions. He also alleged he had
seen Weld smoke marijuana at a 1982 wedding party.
   A Justice Department investigation failed to support McNamara's
charges, and McNamara admitted that he had smoked marijuana at a
later date.
   Last weekend, McNamara denied urging a federal investigation into
marijuana-smoking charges against Democratic U.S. Rep. Joseph
Kennedy II and Robert Farmer, the top fund-raiser for Gov. Michael
Dukakis's presidential campaign.
   McNamara said the allegation stemmed from an unsubstantiated FBI
report that was leaked to reporters.
   In November, several assistant prosecutors said McNamara pursued
an investigation of a prison land deal by the Dukakis administration
in an attempt to discredit Dukakis, then the Democratic nominee for
president.
   Shortly after McNamara's announcement Monday, Dukakis commended
him for resigning, saying, ``It was long overdue.''
</TEXT>
