<HEAD>Wife Sentenced in Plot To Kill Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORRISTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge sentenced a woman to 3{ to nine
years in prison for plotting to murder her estranged husband and
using her teen-age son to hire someone to do the job.
   Carol Boyle-Lawton, a 39-year-old mother of three, pleaded guilty
last September to charges of solicitation to commit murder and
corruption of minors.
   Montgomery County Judge William H. Yohn on Monday ordered her
jailed in the state prison at Muncy.
   Assistant District Attorney Barbara McNulty presented testimony
at the two-day sentencing hearing that Ms. Boyle-Lawton a year ago
told her son Michael Boyle, then 17, that she needed his help to
kill her husband, Charles Lawton, to ``get him out of her hair'' and
collect on his $300,000 insurance policy.
   Michael Boyle found a ``hired killer'' in a classmate at
Wissahickon High School near Ambler, who was actually a state
trooper posing as a student while investigating drug trafficking at
the school, officials said.
   Trooper Mark Fulton testified that he met with Ms. Boyle-Lawton
several times to plan the killing and that she gave him money for a
gun and silencer.
   She provided him with a $1,000 down payment, pictures of her
husband and a written description of him, Fulton said.
   The trooper secretly wore electronic equipment to record their
conversations. Portions of the wiretap were played back in the
courtroom, including Ms. Boyle-Lawton's voice stating amid
obscenities, ``I want him dead. I want the insurance.''
   Ms. Boyle-Lawton said she had second thoughts about killing her
husband and had tried to back out of it.
   ``I wanted to get out, but he (Fulton) was the one who pursued
it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
