<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turtles     01-31 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turtles,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Disturb Breeding Turtles, Sultan Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sultan Qaboos of Oman has banned tourists
from sea turtle nesting beaches to allow the endangered species to
breed in private, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   Qaboos decreed that no one is allowed to watch the turtles in the
area around Ras al Hadd, about 125 miles south of the capital,
Muscat, according to the Oman daily, the Observer.
   Campers have been disturbing the turtles and leaving trash along
their nesting beaches, the largest in the Indian Ocean, the sultan
said.
   These beaches are of ``national, regional and worldwide
importance for the survival of this species which is threatened with
extinction,'' he said.
   ``To prevent further disturbance of the turtles and damage to the
environment, it has been decided that camping and turtle watching by
day or night is prohibited,'' the decree said.
   A government survey conducted from 1977 to 1980 highlighted major
nesting and breeding areas of the sea turtles. Omani rangers were
trained to take over protection and control activities in 1979 so
that the turtle population could be monitored properly.
</TEXT>
