<HEAD>Woman Faces Hearing On Charge Against Her Cat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to specify amount of fine, clarify that citations
came over six-month period; Picks up 3rd graf, ``The whole...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-year-old woman faces a possible
jail term and hundreds of dollars in fines for six citations
accusing her cats of digging up a neighbor's shrubs and using his
yard and van as a litter box.
   The city's Animal Control Department issued the citations against
Nan Farris over a six-month period because of complaints by her
neighbor. Mrs. Farris was ordered into Municipal Court this
afternoon to answer the citations.
   If convicted, she faces $943 in fines and an unspecified jail
term.
   ``The whole thing is about the silliest thing I've ever heard
of,'' she said. ``This thing is crazy, and I don't know why it's
happening.''
   The city takes a different view.
   ``Unfortunately, there is a violation involved _ animal at large
_ and it is normally our policy to prosecute,'' a spokeswoman for
the city attorney told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
   The neighbor, Ralph Neal, said he lived in a neighborhood overrun
by cats and didn't see any humor in the situation.
   ``All I want is for my property to be left alone,'' he said last
summer. ``I have a right to plant shrubs without getting my hands in
cat stuff.''
   Charles Baldwin, Mrs. Farris' attorney, wrote to the city
attorney's office seeking dismissal of the citations.
   ``I would appreciate it if the great city of Fort Worth could
find in its heart to show mercy and dismiss these tickets, as I
don't believe a conviction in this case would serve as a deterrent
to other cats with a compulsion to violate the law,'' Baldwin wrote.
</TEXT>
