<DOCNO> AP890131-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Soviet Bjt   01-31 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Soviet, Bjt,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Arrives for Crucial Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
arrives Wednesday to put the final touches on preparations for the
first Sino-Soviet summit since the two communist giants split in
bitter rivalry 30 years ago.
   Shevardnadze's visit comes after a year of rapid progress in
bilateral relations expected to culminate this spring when Mikhail
S. Gorbachev becomes the first Soviet leader to travel to China
since 1959.
   During his three-day stay, Shevardnadze is to hold two rounds of
talks with his Chinese counterpart, Qian Qichen, and will meet with
Premier Li Peng. He is also to travel to Shanghai for a meeting
Saturday with China's top leader, Deng Xiaoping.
   Shevardnadze is not scheduled to meet Communist Party head Zhao
Ziyang, Eastern European sources said. China apparently wants to
wait for Gorbachev before officially recognizing a restoration of
relations between the two parties.
   Qian, who in December became the first Chinese foreign minister
to hold talks in Moscow in 32 years, told Australian Foreign
Minister Gareth Evans on Monday that the Cambodian conflict would be
high on the agenda.
   Soviet support for Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia has been the
last and hardest sticking point in Sino-Soviet discussions on
normalizing political ties.
   But China, apparently satisfied that Moscow wants Vietnam to end
its war against the Chinese-backed resistance in Cambodia, accedes
that conditions for a summit have been met.
   The Gorbachev visit, which could come as early as the second half
of March, would be the first since Nikita S. Khrushchev met his
ideological foe Mao Tse-tung in Beijing in 1959.
   Khrushchev, already feuding with Mao over the leadership and
direction of world communism, at that meeting rescinded an offer to
provide China a prototype atomic bomb. The next year, Moscow
withdrew more than 1,000 technicians and ended all assistance for
China's industrial and military development.
   Relations reached a nadir in 1969 when troops along the border
clashed and Mao called on the nation to prepare for all-out war.
   Political normalization talks started in 1982, but made little
headway because of what China calls the ``three obstacles'':
Cambodia, the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan and Soviet military
presence along the Chinese border.
   But 1988 proved ``particularly auspicious'' for Sino-Soviet
relations, the authoritative weekly Beijing Review said in its
latest edition. It cited Gorbachev's decision to leave Afghanistan
and his announcement of major troop reductions in Soviet-ally
Mongolia and along the Sino-Soviet border.
   Last August the two sides for the first time held direct talks on
how to solve the Cambodian conflict, and in October they settled
most of their disputes along the eastern sector of the 5,000-mile
border.
   Qian, returning from his historic visit to Moscow in December,
said, ``the most important result was that we started the
normalization process.''
   But the Chinese also emphasize there will be no regression to the
relationship of the 1950s, when the newly founded communist state in
China depended on Soviet economic aid and followed the Soviet lead
in international affairs.
   Normal relations with Moscow, the Beijing Review said in an
indirect reference to the United States, ``will not affect the
development of friendly relations between China and other countries.
   Washington, whose own normalization of relations with China was
in part spurred by common concern over the Soviet military threat,
has welcomed the Sino-Soviet rapprochement, saying it will ease
tensions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-PayRaise 3rdLd-Writethru a0577 01-31 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0577,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Asking House Members if They Want Pay-Raise Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates in top 4 grafs with Wright quotes, picking up in 4th
graf pvs, An Associated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speaker Jim Wright today was conducting a rare,
hurry-up survey of House members that leaves open the possibility of
a public vote on the 50 percent congressional pay raise scheduled to
take effect next week.
   Wright, asked if he would schedule a vote should members demand
one in the survey, said, ``If the members want it, yes, of course.''
   But House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., said, ``I don't
think there will be a vote.'' He predicted that in return for the
raise becoming law on Feb. 8, the House will approve a day later a
package of outside-income and campaign-finance restrictions applying
to members.
   In the survey sent to House members late Monday, the speaker said
he wanted to be ``faithful to the wishes'' of lawmakers, and asked
whether they demanded a vote before Feb. 8.
   An Associated Press survey of the 100 senators, meantime, found
that 88 plan to vote against the pay raise and six for it, with the
other six either undecided or unwilling to disclose their position.
   Wright awaited the replies of his colleagues as the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee began two days of hearings on the
issue that has dominated the early days of the congressional session.
   Lloyd Cutler, the chairman of a federal pay commission that
recommended the increase, defended the proposed $45,000 raise before
the panel but said lawmakers should retain a similar increase for
judges and federal bureaucrats if they don't accept it for themelves.
   Wright has acted in other ways to blunt the impact of the
proposal to raise congressional pay from $89,500 to $135,000.
Negotiators for the speaker and the Republican leadership have
tentatively agreed to major elements of a package to severely
restrict outside income.
   Wright said he would keep the anwers confidential but asked
members, ``Tell me how you really feel.''
   In addition to asking about a vote, Wright asked if members:
thought the raises proposed by former President Reagan were fair;
would cut the 50 percent proposal to 30 percent, thus offsetting
what House members can keep in speech honoraria; would support a
strict ban on all honoraria, and would vote against rescinding the
raise if it meant a loss of income, assuming an honoraria ban passes.
   Most of the six senators who told the AP they planned to vote for
the raise said they will do so only if honoraria are banned in
return.
   It was unclear how many of the possible ``yes'' votes in the
survey were firm, since the language of the pay rejection resolution
was still under discussion. More than a quarter of the Senate has
sponsored legislation that would roll back the increase if it
becomes law on Feb. 8 as expected.
   Senate leaders also are negotiating whether to restrict outside
income beyond a simple ban on honoraria _ the catchall term covering
speaking fees, appearances and articles.
   House negotiators representing the leadership in both parties
have tentatively worked out restrictions that range far beyond an
honoraria ban.
   The raise from $89,500 to $135,000 for rank-and-file lawmakers
can only be stopped if both houses reject the increase. Senate
Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, has promised senators a
vote on rejecting the pay plan, but House Democratic leaders have
said they will not allow a vote.
   The pay proposal, submitted to Congress in former President
Reagan's final budget, would give lawmakers, federal judges and top
political appointees in the executive branch 50 percent increases.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said he will vote for the pay
raise but keep only the amount that will replace the money he now
earns from honoraria.
   Dodd said it is a politically tough choice, and he was critical
of those who would ``vote no and take the dough.''
   ``To me, that's the height of hypocrisy. That is why people have
so much difficulty with Congress and politicians,'' he said.
``That's where peoples' stomachs begin to turn. You've got to be
honest about it.''
   Several senators opposed to the raise said they will return the
money to the government or give it to charity.
   Those who said they will support a raise in some form included
Dodd, James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., Spark M. Matsunaga, D-Hawaii,
Mitchell, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. and Ted Stevens, R-Alaska.
   Senators who said they were undecided or refused to disclose
their views were Glenn, Slade Gorton, R-Wash., Richard Lugar,
R-Ind., Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, and
William V. Roth Jr., R-Del.
   The remaining senators said they are against the raise.
   In the House, the tentative agreement on outside income is
designed in part to soothe public anger over the size of the
increase and the lack of a House vote.
   The package, according to leadership sources, would:
   _End the honoraria system, which has allowed rank-and-file House
members to keep up $26,850 of the money they earn each year from
speeches, articles and other appearances.
   _Abolition of the ``grandfather'' loophole in campaign financing
law. The loophole has allowed 190 House members who were in office
as of Jan. 8, 1980, to stockpile more than $39 million in surplus
campaign money for their personal use. The provision does not apply
to senators.
   _Restrict travel, probably through time limits, that is often
paid for by special interests who invite lawmakers for speeches and
plant tours. This would prevent members from getting long vacations
at resorts, even if they speak for free.
   _Restrict non-honoraria income, such as fees for serving on
corporate boards.
</TEXT>
