<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Austria-Spying     01-31 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Austria-Spying,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Investigate Ring That Spied on U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are investigating an extensive
Polish espionage ring that spied on the U.S. Embassy and recruited
senior Austrian security officers, authorities said Tuesday.
   They learned of the network through an officer in the Polish
intelligence service who defected to the West German
counterespionage agency, said an official at the Interior Ministry
on condition of anonymity.
   Officials said the agents included senior officers of the
Austrian state police and Polish emigres.
   The spies' targets included the West German and U.S. embassies in
Vienna as well as Polish emigres and regime critics living in
Austria, according to police sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   A prosecutor's office has begun investigations, but no charges
have been filed in the year-old inquiry, a prosecutor said.
   Some suspects won't face prosecution since several offenses date
back five years or longer and can no longer be prosecuted under
Austrian law, the prosecutor said.
   The Vienna newspaper Der Standard said a journalist and a retired
state police colonel confessed, and some of the agents had worked
for the Polish secret service for more than 15 years.
</TEXT>
