<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeDemonstration 2ndLd-Writethru a0570 01-31 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Demonstration, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0570,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protest Stops Commute Traffic On GG Bridge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 20 arrests, further color
from scene; Picks up 5th graf, `Garcia said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 80 demonstrators shut down the Golden
Gate Bridge at the height of rush hour this morning to demand faster
government action in stopping the spread of AIDS.
   The demonstrators started blocking lanes about 7:30 a.m. and
quickly succeeded in stopping traffic in both directions, said
bridge officer Lou Garcia. The fog-shrouded bridge reopened at about
8 a.m.
   Highway Patrol cars and San Francisco police were sent to clear
lanes for commuter traffic heading into the city from Marin County.
About 20 people were arrested.
   The closure snarled traffic on Highway 101, which is normally
crowded at that hour under the best of conditions. Frustrated
motorists shut off their engines and got out of their cars to see
what was going on.
   The group spread a banner across the width of the famous span and
handed out leaflets to stalled motorists.
   Garcia said it was too foggy to tell what the demonstration was
about.
   But a caller to The Associated Press bureau in San Francisco said
the protest was organized by a group called Stop AIDS Now Or Else.
   The caller, who did not identify himself, said the demonstrators
either have the fatal disease or have been deeply affected by it.
   ``About 80 people are blocking traffic in protest of the
inactivity of the government the last eight years and telling George
Bush we're not going to remain inactive,'' said the caller. ``We're
going to continue to put pressure on Washington to do more for
people with AIDS.''
</TEXT>
