<FIRST>r a PM-JustSweatsProbe 2ndLd-Writethru a0554 01-31 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Just Sweats Probe, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0554,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Faking Own Death Arrested With Dead Man's License,
FBI Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS WITH 3 grafs to specify Hanson arrested for part in insurance
fraud and correct spelling of FBI agent's name to Douglass, sted Douglas.
Picks up 4th graf, `But the ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of faking his own death in
a $1.5 million insurance fraud was arrested carrying the driver's
license of the man whose body was part of the scam, an FBI agent
said.
   Melvin Hanson, co-founder of Just Sweats, a Whitehall, Ohio-based
athletic clothing store chain, was arrested in connection with the
insurance scam at Dallas-Fort Worth Airport Sunday night by U.S.
Customs Service agents, police said Monday.
   The suspect was carrying a driver's license and other papers that
belonged to Ellis H. Greene, a former Ohio man whose body was found
in a Glendale, Calif., doctor's office and reported to be that of
Hanson, said Douglass C. Ogden, agent in charge of the Columbus FBI
office. The body later was identified as that of Greene.
   But the arrested man denied he was Hanson and plans to fight
extradition to Ohio, Ogden said.
   Hanson, 47, and his business partner, John B. Hawkins, 25, have
been sought by police in Columbus and California since mid-1988,
when it was discovered that Hanson was not dead and Hawkins had
disappeared.
   Theft charges against Hanson and Hawkins were filed Oct. 14 by
Farmers New World Life Insurance Co. of Mercer Island, Wash., which
paid Hawkins $1 million in death benefits. Hawkins was Hanson's
beneficiary.
   Police in Los Angeles and Glendale, Calif., have been
investigating Greene's death as a homicide.
   Hanson was arrested upon his return from Acapulco, where he had
gone to see a plastic surgeon, authorities said. When he was
arrested, the suspect carried identification cards under 13 names,
authorities said.
   The suspect carried no identification under the name Melvin
Hanson but scars around his eyes, apparently from plastic surgery,
convinced authorities the man they arrested was Hanson, Ogden said.
   Ogden said fingerprints taken after the suspect was arrested
would be compared today with those in Hanson's military records.
   Danny Burns, who was appointed by U.S. District Court in Fort
Worth to represent the man, said his client is not Hanson, but
Wolfgang Eugene von Snowden, as indicated on the passport he was
carrying.
   The arrested man was charged with theft by fraud on a warrant
from Ohio. U.S. Magistrate Gene Grant set bond at $5 million, and
the man was jailed.
   Hanson and Hawkins also are accused of stealing about $2 million
from Just Sweats, which they founded in 1985. Just Sweats has filed
for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of U.S. bankruptcy
laws.
</TEXT>
