<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ReillyHearing     01-31 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reilly Hearing,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Nominee Promises Aggressive Enforcement of Environmental Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Reilly, designated to head the
Environmental Protection Agency, promised today aggressive and
timely enforcement of environmental laws, saying the environment can
be protected without hindering economic growth.
   Reilly's nomination by President Bush as head of the federal
government's key environmental agency is expected to win early
Senate approval. His appearance today before the Environment and
Public Works Committee prompted bipartisan praise from members.
   Sen. Quentin Burdick, R-N.D., committee chairman, called Reilly,
who is president of the World Wildlife Fund, ``a person ... who
appreciates that a great nation must be a good steward of its land,
its air, its water and its natural resources.''
   ``I'm pleased to join the chorus of admirers and welcomers,''
said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., noting that Reilly was
introduced to the panel by no fewer than five senators from three
states.
   Reilly told the senators that while he plans to enforce
environmental laws aggressively ``whenever it is warranted to
safeguard public health and environmental quality'' he also will
seek to deal with environmental problems through consensus and
cooperation.
   ``We no longer have the time or luxury of allowing the
bitterness, the polarization, the wasted resources and other
excesses'' that have marked the conflicts in recent yeas between
environmentalists and industry.
   Reilly said he has spent his career in the environmental movement
``advocating environmental protection and economic growth'' and
added that he was ``convinced we can find it.''
   Reilly ticked off a list of priority issues facing the EPA such
as finding ways to come to grips with the problems of acid rain,
depletion of the earth's ozone layer, global warming, ocean
pollution and cleaning up toxic waste dumps.
   But he said the problems posed by acid rain are ``ahead of
everything else'' and promised early EPA action to develop
legislation aimed at dealing with the issue.
   ``We expect to offer a comprehensive proposal for congressional
consideration as soon as possible'' aimed at achieving a
``substantial reduction of acid rain by the end of the century,''
Reilly said.
   Several senators noted Reilly's desire to deal with environmental
issues through consensus and expressed concern that the approach
might lead to inaction on part of the EPA.
   ``Will you conciliate, mediate, negotiate away our environmental
laws?'' asked Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who nevertheless expressed
support for Reilly's nomination.
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., urged Reilly to be ``an
environmental advocate'' in the Bush administration and allow the
EPA not to be a ``reluctant combatant as it often has been'' in the
Reagan administration.
   ``You can count on me being an advocate,'' replied Reilly.
</TEXT>
