<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-Hijack 2ndLd-Writethru a0597 01-31 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Hijack, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0597,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hijacked Plane Lands in Costa Rica</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with new quotes, radio report of hijacker's
demand, editing for transition. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lone hijacker seized control today
of a Colombian airliner with 116 passengers aboard, authorities
said, and surrendered after diverting the plane to Costa Rica.
   The Ace airline Boeing 727 was commandeered at about 11 a.m.
after taking off from San Andres Island, Colombia, en route to the
city of Medellin, the Civil Aeronautics Department of Colombia said.
   ``The hijacker during the flight told the pilot, Jaime Perez, he
would burn a passenger alive if he did not divert the flight to
Costa Rica,'' said Costa Rican air traffic controller Carlos
Paniagua.
   Radio Reloj, a Costa Rican radio station, said it received an
anonymous telephone call saying the hijacker was seeking the freedom
of an American and several Colombians under arrest in Costa Rica on
drug charges.
   Public Security Director Hernan Garron said the hijacker turned
himself in after the plane landed in Costa Rica at about noon.
   A Costa Rican anti-terrorist squad and Red Cross personnel went
aboard the plane, according to control tower officials at the
airport north of the Costa Rican capital.
   Some passengers were taken to an airport lounge for treatment for
shock, Garron said.
   Garron said the hijacker apparently acted alone.
   Officials in Colombia said the plane carried 116 passengers and
six crew members.
</TEXT>
