<FIRST>r w PM-YellowstoneFires     01-31 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Fires,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Park Service Workers Wanted to Let Natural Fires Burn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Denis correct in 5th graf, Nichols did</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staffers of the National Park Service at
Yellowstone National Park were ``determined to maintain the natural
fire regime'' as fires grew out of control there last summer,
according to a memo by a park service official visiting from another
park.
   The memo by Sequoyia National Park fire specialist Howard Nichols
said Yellowstone staffers ``were bemoaning the fact that new (fire)
starts, as mandated by the secretary'' had to be suppressed,
according to a copy of the memo made public today at a congressional
hearing on the fires.
   The Aug. 15 memo was submitted by Nichols to the western regional
director after a week-long visit to Yellowstone that began July 28.
On July 21, then-Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel ordered that
what some have called the ``let it burn'' policy be suspended and
all fires fought.
   Rep. Ron Marlenee, R-Mont., submitted the memorandum at a joint
hearing of the national parks subcommittee of the House Interior
Committee and the forests subcommittee of the House Agriculture
Committee.
   Nichols did not say that anyone disobeyed Hodel's order. But
Marlenee suggested to Denis Galvin, deputy director of the National
Park Service, that the memo showed that Hodel's policy ``was not
being carried out.''
   Galvin said the service would ``absolutely'' look into points
raised by the memo.
   Among other things, Nichols said, ``The tactics used for these
fires may well result in the suggestion that Yellowstone was using
suppression dollars to achieve natural resource benefits, a patently
illegal use of these funds.''
   Also, he said, Yellowstone's pre-existing fire plan ``was
deficient in not stating how many acres should be permitted to burn
at any time.''
   Marlenee and other members of Congress from the Yellowstone area
have protested that the park service endangered their constituents'
businesses and property in neglecting to fight the fires until they
were too far gone for effective suppression.
   The park service and environmental groups supporting it argue
that fire is necessary to regenerate the high lodgepole pine forests
of Yellowstone, and only the unforeseeable and exceptional drought
made 1988's fires so devastating to normal tourist and other
activity.
</TEXT>
