<FIRST>r a PM-DenverAirport     01-31 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denver Airport,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Transport Group Urges Delay Of New Denver Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful airline industry group has urged further
study before construction begins on Denver's proposed new $3 billion
airport.
   The Air Transport Association, which represents most major U.S.
airlines, including Denver's two largest carriers, opposes the
city's plan to break ground on the new airport this summer.
   It will voice that position during public hearings in Denver this
week. The new airport is planned about 20 miles farther out of the
city than Stapleton International Airport, located on the city's
eastern outskirts.
   ``This airport isn't needed right now,'' Leslie Rowland, a
spokeswoman for the Washington-based association, said Monday.
``We've already got a lot of unused capacity right now. This needs
further evaluation.''
   The group hasn't decided what an appropriate timetable should be,
she said.
   Rowland said the association decided last week to participate in
Denver's public hearings, partly on the advice of Continental and
United airlines. Both carriers argue that Denver is planning the new
airport too quickly, and both are represented on the transport
association's executive committee.
   Mayor Federico Pena and Gov. Roy Romer say a new airport is
needed because Stapleton, among the nation's busiest airports, can't
handle its traffic volume. Critics of the new aiport say Stapleton's
volume has fallen off somewhat in the past year and that Stapleton
should be expanded rather than building at a new site.
   The Federal Aviation Administration supports the airport plan,
said FAA spokesman John Leyden.
</TEXT>
