<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HousingAffordability     01-31 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Affordability,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Affordability Measure Down Slightly in December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An index measuring the ability of the typical
American family to buy a home edged down in December, leaving buyers
with slightly less purchasing power than they had a month earlier, a
real estate trade group said Tuesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said its affordability index
was 112.3 in December, down from 112.8 in November.
   The December figure means that a family earning the median income
of $32,100 had 12.3 percent more income than needed to qualify for a
mortgage covering 80 percent of the purchase price of a
median-priced home.
   For all of 1988, the index was 113.4, down slightly from 113.8 in
the previous year, as family incomes mostly keep pace with increases
in mortgage interest rates and home prices.
   The median price of an existing home in December fell $300 from
the previous month to $87,700, meaning half the homes sold for more
and half for less. Median family income rose $104 and the mortgage
rate used to calculate the index rose from 9.48 percent to 9.61
percent, representing a composite of fixed and adjustable rates.
   The affordability index, which has been above 100 since June
1986, was at its highest point for 1988 in April, when it reached
113.8.
</TEXT>
