<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Namora     01-31 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Namora,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer Fernando Namora Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Fernando Namora, one of Portugal's
best-known novelists, died Tuesday after a 50-year literary career.
He was 69.
   Namora, who was proposed for the Nobel Prize in 1981, was an
instigator of the neo-realist spirit in Portuguese literature that
tried to capture the texture of rural life in the 1940s.
   He was born in the central Portuguese town of Condeixa in 1919,
studied medicine in Lisbon and became a doctor serving remote
mountain locations.
   His experiences of the rough life of the mountain people in
Portugal's Serra de Estrela region formed the basis for his early
novels, including ``Mountain Doctor,'' which was translated into
many languages.
   Namora wrote more than 30 books and several volumes of poetry.
   In 1988, President Mario Soares awarded Namora the Order of Henry
the Navigator, Portugal's highest civilian honor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
