<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Budget     01-31 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Budget,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>1989-90 Budget Calls for Billion Dollar Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres on Tuesday
introduced a $30.7 billion budget for the 1990 fiscal year with a $1
billion deficit that was bigger than expected.
   The document presented to the Knesset, or parliament, calls for a
19 percent increase in the government's operating budget to be
partly offset by a reduction in the development budget and increases
in taxes and fees.
   Defense outlays are to rise to $5.9 billion in the fiscal year
beginning April 1, from $5.05 billion in the current year.
   Part of the rise in military spending is to cover increased costs
for countering the 14-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip. Dealing with the Arab revolt has been
costing the government about $14 million a month.
   The budget is expected to win easy approval in parliament, where
a coalition between Peres' Labor Party and Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's Likud bloc controls four-fifths of the seats. But tax
increases and cuts in food subsidies have already brought an angry
public response.
   Peres has pledged to hold down federal spending. In announcing
his economic austerity program on Jan. 1, he said the aim was to try
to hold this year's deficit to the same level as last year's $833
million in red ink.
   He did not explain Tuesday why the goal was not attained, but he
told parliament that ``We have learned that nothing feeds inflation
more than a budget deficit. ... Therefore, we decided to cut the
expected budget deficit.''
   The nation's massive Histadrut labor federation, which represents
about 80 percent of Israeli workers, has pledged to oppose Peres'
plan, contending it will increase unemployment and significantly
raise food, transport and insurance costs that workers can't afford.
   An announced earlier, the budget calls for reducing government
subsidies for food and public transport. Fees for universities,
hospitals and insurance are to increase, and new taxes will be
imposed on cars and imported services.
   Israeli TV estimated up to 4,000 government workers could lose
their jobs under the austerity program.
   The Israeli economy grew a sluggish 1 percent last year, down
sharply from 5.2 percent growth in 1987. About half of the slowdown
has been blamed on the uprising, which has reduced tourism, business
investment and sales to the territories.
  
</TEXT>
