<FIRST>d w AM-US-Uganda     01-31 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Uganda,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandan President Says Libya Too Small To Be Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uganda's President Yoweri Museveni said Tuesday
that Libya was too small a country to present a threat to other
states, ``but if they do, we'll kick them out.''
   Museveni, speaking at a National Press Club meeting with
reporters, also said that although the United States has accused
Libya of supporting terrorism, the Libyans have denied the charge.
``So we don't know what to think,'' he said.
   ``Libya has no power to destabilize anyone. They're just 3
million people,'' said Museveni, who is on a private visit here to
promote his country to business leaders and journalists. ``If they
do,'' he added, his government will ``kick them out.''
   Libya, as well as North Korea, provides Uganda with weapons and
military advisers. Uganda also got some $8 billion in 1988 from the
United States for development projects.
   U.S. officials are pleased with Museveni's three-year rule,
saying he is the best leader his country has had in recent years.
   Museveni came to power in 1986 after waging guerrilla warfare
against the governments of Idi Amin and Milton Obote. Museveni had
accused both men of bankrupting Uganda in pursuit of personal power
and wealth.
   The annual State Department report on human rights around the
world, which is to be published this month, praises Uganda for
progress it has made in offering amnesty to resistance groups and
allowing a free press, but also criticizes long jail periods without
trial and a slow judicial process, U.S. officials say.
