<HEAD>Exiled King Asks United Nations to Probe Human Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT word in quote to ``unhindered.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled King Michael of Romania on Tuesday accused
his homeland's communist government of ``an unhindered rule of
terror'' and asked for an urgent U.N. inquiry into human rights
there.
   In a message to the 43-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission, the
king said such an investigation should be granted priority because
``at stake is the survival of 23 million people forced to applaud a
regime that starves them, humiliates them, and destroys their cities
and villages.''
   ``Such infamy is possible only because the Romanians have been
deprived of all their rights, even the most elementary ones,
allowing an unhindered rule by terror,'' the message said.
   The king has condemned President Nicolae Ceausescu's plans for
``consolidating'' rural settlements. Critics say the plan would
involve razing thousands of villages.
   King Michael, 67, went into exile in 1948 and lives near Geneva.
