<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Priest     01-31 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Priest,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Says No Evidence Links Priests' Deaths to Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it has no
evidence that the suspicious deaths of two priests within 10 days
were politically provoked.
   ``There is no ground to suppose that there is someone going
around Poland and spreading death among priests,'' government
spokesman Jerzy Urban told a news conference.
   Authorities performed an autopsy Tuesday on the body of the Rev.
Stanislaw Suchowolec, 31, a pro-Solidarity priest found dead Monday
after a fire swept his apartment in the northeastern city of
Bialystok, 119 miles northeast of Warsaw.
   Urban said an investigation is continuing into the death of
another priest, the Rev. Stefan Niedzielak, 74, who died of a broken
neck on Jan. 21. Niedzielak was sympathetic to the Solidarity
movement.
   ``There is no evidence to assume or suppose the existence of a
political provocation'' in the deaths, Urban said.
   The Rev. Cezary Potocki, chancellor of Bialystok district, said
Roman Catholic Church officials attended the autopsy of Suchowolec,
who worked in the parish of the Immaculate Heart of Mary.
   Suchowolec died apparently from smoke inhalation, according to
results of an initial investigation by the local prosecutor and
church officials, Urban said. The cause of the fire still is unknown.
   A housekeeper sounded the alarm after smelling smoke early Monday
morning, Urban said.
   ``The doors which were closed from the inside were forced open.
There was a considerable amount of smoke in the room. Father
Suchowolec was lying next to the couch. His dead dog was lying there
too,'' he said.
   ``The windows in the room were shut. The window and door panes
were blackened with soot. Maybe the electric circuits were cut off,
which could have been the source (of the fire),'' said Urban.
   Suchowolec actively supported the banned trade union Solidarity.
   Early in his six years as a priest, he served for three years as
vicar in Suchowola, home village of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, who
was murdered by security police in 1984.
   Suchowolec had organized pilgrimages to Popieluszko's gravesite
in Warsaw.
   Zofia Romaszewska, of the Solidarity Commission on Intervention
and Law Abidance, said Suchowolec had informed the commission that
he had been assaulted and that his car had been tampered with at
least twice.
   Zbigniew Romaszewski, another member of the commission which
records human rights' violations, said Suchowolec's car had been
stoned Aug. 4, 1988, and two days later his parents' apartment was
burned.
   Romaszewski said the incidents were fully documented, but Urban
said no threats were reported to investigative authorities.
   Chancellor Zdzislaw Krol of the church's Warsaw district said
Niedzielak had received anonymous threats before his death, but the
chancellor had not taken them seriously at the time. Niedzielak
maintained a shrine to Poles killed in the Soviet Union during World
War II.
   More than 5,000 people attended his funeral in Warsaw.
</TEXT>
