<FIRST>r a AM-AstronautImpostor     01-31 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Astronaut Impostor,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Fraud After Allegedly Posing As Astronaut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed to be an astronaut sported
impressive medals, uniforms and badges and even wangled a 10-minute
audience with the lord mayor of Dublin.
   But Robert Hunt, 27, was grounded Monday when he was arraigned on
charges of larceny and fraud and ordered held on $100,000 bail. He
was charged with duping a youth into joining the Navy and then
claiming he could get him released from his commitment for $2,000.
   Hunt claimed to be a Marine captain, a decorated fighter pilot
and told convincing but false stories about himself to his wife, his
in-laws, some people at the Bedford Veterans Administration
Hospital, an Aer Lingus pilot and cadets at the U.S. Naval Academy
in Annapolis, Md., according to state Trooper Andy Palombo, a state
police investigator.
   Palombo said he started looking into the stories earlier this
month. ``I did some checking and found out there was no such animal
as Robert Hunt who was a Marine captain and fighter pilot or
astronaut,'' he said.
   The charges against the man stem from allegations he persuaded an
18-year-old Saugus youth to enlist in the Navy and then told the
teen-ager's parents their son could get out of his commitment for
$2,000, Palombo said. They paid him that amount twice; once in a
check he said was no good and then in cash, though he later cashed
the check, Palombo said.
   Last summer the man married a woman who, like her parents, was
convinced that he was an astronaut. The man showed them burned
kitchen tiles he claimed came from the explosion of the Challenger
space shuttle three years ago.
   ``When I arrested him Saturday noon at his home, his wife still
thought he was an astronaut,'' Palombo said.
   The charges against Hunt also include his alleged use of his
wife's credit card for a variety of charges, including the charter
of a private jet to Montreal.
   He later wrote the crew complimenting them on their performance.
   ``Being a former astronaut, I would like to make note that the
landing in Montreal was equal to our landing of the shuttle
Atlantis,'' the letter stated.
   Before he flew with his wife to Ireland just before Christmas, he
called ahead to tell officials in Ireland he was an astronaut,
Palombo said.
   ``He was given a big state welcome and made an honorary citizen
of Ireland by Lord Mayor of Dublin Benjamin Briscoe because he was
an astronaut,'' according to Palombo.
   But Briscoe's spokeswoman, who requested anonymity, said Briscoe
gave Hunt a 10-minute audience on Oct. 8 at Mansion House, his
official headquarters, after being told Hunt was a visiting
astronaut.
   A source close to Briscoe, also requesting anonymity, said Hunt
told him British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was arranging for
him to be married in Westminster Abbey in London. Briscoe quickly
realized the man was ``not the full shilling,'' but politely went
along with the charade, the source said.
   ``He's very good,'' the trooper said. ``I had him in the cruiser
and I asked him one question. He talked for 10 minutes, without
hesitating, from Medford to Boston.
   ``I said to him, `But you never answered my question,' and he
said, `That's right.'''
</TEXT>
