<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Greenspan     01-31 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenspan,650</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan called
President Bush ``a very good and old friend'' Tuesday and said the
two have only minor differences concerning the conduct of economic
policy.
   Greenspan played down reports of a rift between the Federal
Reserve and Bush which surfaced last week after Bush said in an
interview he did not believe the central bank should be trying to
slow economic growth because of a fear of inflation.
   ``Whatever differences do exist _ and I think they are minuscule
_ have been exaggerated,'' Greenspan said during an appearance
before the congressional Joint Economic Committee.
   In an interview, Bush had cautioned the central bank against
overreacting to the threat of inflation following testimony the
previous day by Greenspan in which the Fed chairman said the risk of
higher inflation was serious enough that Fed policy should err more
on the side of ``restrictiveness than of stimulus.''
   In his comments, Bush said, ``I don't want to see us move so
strongly against fear of inflation that we impede growth.'' On
Friday, Bush said during a press conference he didn't believe the
differences between the new administration and the central bank were
that great.
   Sen. Paul Sarbannes, D-Md., said he was concerned that
disagreements between Bush and Greenspan were being aired publicly
rather than being worked out in private. He questioned Greenspan
about his access to Bush and the role he has had in making
suggestions on what should be in the budget Bush will submit to
Congress next month.
   Greenspan said he had not met with Bush since December but that
he was meeting on a regular basis with Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, Bush's top economic spokesman. Greenspan said he expects to
be consulted on the contents of Bush's budget before the president
unveils it in a joint address to Congress on Feb. 9.
   ``I have no problem communicating with President Bush. He is a
very good and old friend of mine,'' Greenspan said. ``I am not the
least bit concerned about what is going on. I think the press is
trying to make this a cause celeb where none exists.''
   Many private economists have said the new administration, which
needs robust economic growth to drive the budget deficit down, could
be on a collision course with the Fed, which since last March has
been pushing interest rates higher in an effort to slow the economy
and keep inflation from getting out of hand.
   In his comments Tuesday, Greenspan sought to minimize any
differences he might have with the new administration.
   Greenspan said the economic predictions used by the Reagan
administration to construct its final budget were optimistic but
were ``well within the range of reasonableness,'' especially if
Congress and the Bush administration agree on significant spending
cuts that will meet the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction targets.
Those targets call for reducing an expected $161 billion deficit
this year to $100 billion in the fiscal year which begins Oct. 1.
   Bush budget director Richard Darman has indicated the new
administration will base its own budget revisions on the optimistic
forecasts contained in the Reagan budget.
   Greenspan said that while he expects that the current economic
recovery, which has lasted a peacetime record of six years, will
some day end in a new recession, he said the imbalances that
normally preceded a downturn were not now in evidence.
   Greenspan said that rather than pushing the economy into another
downturn, he believes the Fed's efforts to boost interest rates
would extend the length of the recovery by keeping inflationary
forces under control.
   On another matter, Greepspan said the huge U.S. trade deficit,
which has shown little improvement over the past six months, would
begin improving again this year without the need for a further drop
in the value of the dollar.
</TEXT>
