<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Cabinet     01-31 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Cabinet,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudan Reshuffling Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of war-scarred Sudan have begun
to reshuffle their nation's Cabinet, Egypt's state-run news agency
said Tuesday.
   Sudan's State Council, which acts as a collective presidency,
decided to remove seven ministers, according to the Middle East News
Agency. It said Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi of Sudan was expected to
form a new government within 24 hours.
   The decision has not been officially announced in Sudan.
   Among those affected was Hassan Turabi, minister of justice and
head of the fundamentalist National Islamic Front. He has been at
the center of a debate over a tentative agreement for peace with
southern rebels.
   Turabi, who opposed suspending Islamic law as part of a pact with
rebels in the heavily Christian south, is expected to become foreign
minister, the Egyptian report said.
   The Democratic Unionist Party, a member of the governing
coalition in Sudan, signed the peace agreement with the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army in November. But it withdrew from the
coalition when Mahdi refused to present the agreement to the
government, apparently to avoid angering Turabi's party.
   Mahdi is now expected to select ministers from groups including
his Umma Party, the National Islamic Front, and southern parties,
according to the Egyptian report.
   Since he came to power by general elections in April 1986, Mahdi
has reshuffled his Cabinet three times.
   Sudan has been shaken by chronic food shortages. Protests over
food prices broke out in December and killed four people. The
Sudanese also suffer from severe hunger and face a $14 billion
foreign debt.
</TEXT>
