<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-Refinery     01-31 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Refinery,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speed Opening New Refinery Because of Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT HARCOURT, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are trying to speed up
the opening of the nation's fourth oil refinery because of shortages
created by a fire at a nearby facility.
   The Jan. 24 blaze killed five people and destroyed a facility
that had been producing 60,000 barrels a day. The cause of the fire
was not known.
   Although the government diverted oil supplies from the north,
long lines formed at gasoline stations in several cities in the
heart of the oil-producing region.
   The fourth refinery, built to handle 200,000 barrels of petroleum
daily, was scheduled to open March 16.
   The government set up a task force to speed up the opening of the
new refinery.
   Aret Adams, managing director of the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corp., said replacing the destroyed refinery would cost $300
million. It was opened in 1965 by British Petroleum.
   Production from the new $850 million refinery had been scheduled
to go to overseas markets. Until the lost production capacity is
replaced, however, about half of it will be sold in Nigeria or
neighboring countries.
</TEXT>
