<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Ships     01-31 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Ships,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Arrested After Ship Collision off Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested a South Korean deck officer in
connection with a collision of cargo ships that left seven South
Korean seamen dead and 10 missing, a prosecution official said
Tuesday.
   The 2,400-ton Semba Wang of Singapore collided with the 2,900-ton
Panamanian-registered Catherine-Rose Thursday off western Japan. The
Catherine-Rose, which was carrying a crew of 17, sunk after the
collision.
   Choi Young-kyo, a 48-year-old deck officer of the Semba Wang, is
under investigation for negligence and blocking sea traffic, said an
official at the prosecutor's office in Moji about 520 miles
southwest of Tokyo.
   None of the Semba Wang's 16 South Korean crewmen was hurt, but
the vessel suffered heavy damage.
</TEXT>
