<FIRST>r i AM-Sharansky-Profile     01-31 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sharansky-Profile,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharansky: Human Rights Activist in Search of Unity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sharansky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natan Sharansky, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
choice to represent Israel at the United Nations, is a short,
balding man who spent nine years in Soviet prisons but seems never
to lose his sense of humor.
   ``I will say only what I want to say. I have enough experience
with interrogations and I know how to give answers,'' Sharansky, 41,
told a radio interviewer who pressed him to comment on the reported
appointment.
   In the early 1970s, Sharansky, a mathematician by profession, was
a member of a human rights watchdog organization headed by physicist
Andrei Sakharov, a Nobel Prize laureate.
   Sharansky gained prominence as a spokesman for the group. He had
wide contacts with foreign journalists in Moscow and emerged as a
champion of the Soviet Jewry emigration movement.
   Sharansky married in 1974. A day after the wedding, his wife,
Avital, left for Israel, hoping that he would soon follow.
   But Sharansky was denied exit visa. In March 1977, he was
arrested and in 1978 convicted of espionage and sentenced to 13
years in prison.
   He spent nine years in Soviet prisons and labor camps and became
a symbol of the Soviet Jews' plight, thanks to the efforts of
Avital, who tirelessy campaigned on his behalf in the West.
   Freedom came on Feb. 11, 1986, when Sharansky was released in a
dramatic East-West spy swap on Berlin's Glienicke Bridge.
   In Israel, Sharansky first kept a low profile, devoting himself
to family life. He and Avital now have two daughters, 2-year-old
Rachel and Hannah, born in November.
   Avital became an observant Jew during the years of Sharansky's
forced absence, but Sharansky has defines himself as non-religious.
Newspapers have speculated the marriage may fail apart because of
religious differences.
   Sharansky, for whom unity is a prime value, responded angrily to
the reports.
   ``I feel like my own bald pate has been conscripted into Israel's
Kulturkampf,'' or culture war, he said in a recent interview.
``People here concentrate too much on their differences ... instead
of principles and common aims.''
   Sharansky has successfully defeated attempts by many of Israel's
parties to lure him into their political embrace.
   But besieged by his former compatriots, he emerged last year to
found a lobby group that seeks to improve conditions for thousands
of Soviet immigrants plagued by shortages in jobs and housing.
   Unity, again, was the key, and Soviet Jewry activists said only
Sharansky could unite about 10 groups representing the immigrants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
