<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GrandHotel     01-31 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grand Hotel,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walk-in Closets, A Steward, 3 Phones _ Starting At $400 A Night</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the city of such hostelries as the Waldorf,
the Pierre and the Plaza doesn't have enough truly first-class hotel
rooms, architect I.M. Pei has a solution: a 50-story hotel where
singles start at about $400 a night.
   ``It's an expensive piece of property, it's going to be expensive
to build, and it's going to be expensive as hell to live in,''
Robert Burns of Regent Hotels, which will run the Regent of New
York, said Tuesday at a news conference.
   The 400-room hotel, which will be on 57th Street in the heart of
Manhattan, is to open in 1991. It is expected to cost $300 million,
according to the developer, EIE International of Japan.
   Burns said nightly rates would be nearly $400 to $700 for suites.
   The developers say some international travelers, especially
business people on expense accounts, already are paying as much as
$400 a night in many of the world's largest cities, and will happily
do the same in New York.
   Pei's design calls for a tower of honey-colored limestone that
steps back gradually from its base, rising to a crown marked by four
lanterns.
   The Regent's 600-square-foot standard room will be the size of
many one-bedroom apartments in Manhattan, and about 40 percent
larger than the average New York hotel room, its developers said.
   According to a Regent Hotels description, each room will feature
walk-in closets, separate dressing areas, three telephones and two
telephone lines, two or three color television sets, connections for
computers and fax machines, and a videocassette recorder and compact
disc player.
   In a touch borrowed from Asia _ Regent is based in Hong Kong _
each floor, even upper ones with as few as six rooms, will have a
steward to attend to guests' needs. According to a news release,
these might include ``having a button sewn, flowers delivered, a
limousine ordered.''
   The most expensive hotel in New York City is probably the Plaza
Athenee on the upper East Side, where single rooms cost about $300.
Others, according to the Convention and Visitors Bureau, include the
Pierre at $250-$340; the Plaza at $215-$290, or $450 for a Central
Park view; and the Peninsula $210-$365. Relative bargains include
the Hilton at $155-$200, the Marriott Marquis at $210-$235 and the
Waldorf-Astoria at $180-$240.
   Business has been good, with an occupancy rate of about 76
percent, 10 percentage points higher than the national average,
according to the bureau.
   But, as staffer Kathleen Astrom noted, ``now things are going to
spread out.'' Several luxury hotels have opened in Manhattan in the
past year, and six more are under construction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
