<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Priest</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Urges Rapid Polish Probe of Priests' Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States urged the Polish government
Tuesday to conduct a ``thorough and rapid'' investigation into the
recent deaths of two Catholic priests who were sympathetic to the
Solidarity labor union movement.
   ``We're following these cases with concern,'' said State
Department spokesman Charles Redman.
   The Rev. Stanislaw Suchowolec, 31, a pro-Solidarity priest, was
found dead Monday after a fire swept his apartment in the
northeastern city of Bialystok, 119 miles northeast of Warsaw.
Another priest, the Rev. Stefan Niedzielak, 74, died of a broken
neck on Jan. 21. Niedzielak also was sympathetic to the Solidarity
movement.
   ``We hope and expect Polish authorities will conduct a thorough
and rapid investigation, especially in light of (Suchowolec's)
reported relationship with opposition groups,'' Redman said.
   Of the Niedzielak case, the spokesman added, ``We also look
forward to the results of a thorough investigation of that killing.''
