<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-JunkBonds     01-31 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Junk Bonds,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bank Board Restricts Thrifts' Investments in Junk Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board on Tuesday
announced new restrictions on savings institutions' investments in
so-called ``junk bonds,'' which pay high interest rates but carry
more risk than investment-grade bonds.
   The agency, which regulates about 3,000 federally insured S&amp;Ls,
barred insolvent institutions from making new investments in junk
bonds and generally will require them to sell junk bonds they
already own.
   Exceptions to the rule are permitted if bank board examiners
believe holding the junk bonds is in the near-term interest of the
government insurance fund backing S&amp;L deposits.
   Solvent, but shaky, institutions that don't meet capital
requirements will be required to get government approval before
buying junk bonds.
   Existing regulations permit the purchase of junk bonds, but
institutions can invest no more than 5 percent of their portfolios
in a single junk bond mutual fund.
   Over the last several years, junk bonds have been a profitable
investment for many S&amp;Ls. Analysts worry, however, that if the
issuing companies default during an economic downturn, S&amp;Ls will be
stuck for a loss.
   At the end of last June, junk bonds accounted for $13 billion, or
1 percent, of the industry's $1.29 trillion in assets, the bank
board said.
</TEXT>
