<DOCNO> AP890131-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Budget     01-31 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Budget,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration To Propose Package Of Tax Breaks In Revised Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will propose a round of
tax breaks reflecting campaign promises in its Feb. 9 budget
rewrite, but disagreement has surfaced over a major component, a
reduction in the capital gains tax, officials said Tuesday.
   Administration budget writers have not reached a consensus on
whether the lower rates urged by Bush during his campaign should
apply equally to the sale of homes, stocks and other assets, said
sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Treasury officials hope to minimize any adverse effect on the
budget deficit that might result from lowering the tax on certain
assets, such as private real estate and art objects.
   Sources said it is likely that the budget plan Bush unveils at
the time of his address to a joint session of Congress next week
also will include:
   _A child-care tax credit of up to $1,000 per child that would be
available to low-income families, generally those earning less than
$10,000 a year.
   _New tax incentives for oil and gas exploration, likely coupled
with a call for removal of remaining price controls on natural gas,
now affecting about 40 percent of production.
   _A proposal for tax-free ``enterprise zones'' to be established
in some inner city areas to promote commercial growth, a program
championed on Bush's nominee for Housing and Urban Development
secretary, former Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   In addition, administration officials are still wrestling with
terms of a package to help bail out troubled savings and loan
institutions, and it appeared likely that some variation on a
proposal for an increased fee for deposit insurance would be part of
the new Bush budget plan.
   Bush said even before he took office that his campaign vow to
propose a reduction in capital gains tax rates would be part of the
budget revisions he makes to the $1.15 trillion spending plan for
fiscal year 1990 that former President Reagan submitted Jan. 9.
   And Bush reiterated his support for such a plan in a news
conference last Friday.
   However, sources say there is still disagreement over exactly
what form the tax cut should take.
   Capital gains _ profits from the sale of real estate, stocks and
other assets _ are currently taxed at the same level as other
income, at 15 percent, 28 percent or 33 percent, depending on
overall income.
   Bush would lower the rate to a maximum of 15 percent.
   He claims that such a move would be an incentive to investment,
generating up to $4 billion a year in new revenues. However, many
leading economists, including the bipartisan Congressional Budget
Office, argue that lowering the tax would have the opposite effect _
reducing revenues and further worsening the budget deficit.
   To make sure the proposal does have the potential for spurring
investment, administration budget writers are trying to fine-tune it.
   For instance, while it could be argued that a lower capital gains
rate for the sale of coprorate stocks and commercial properties
might spur additional investment, it might be more difficult to
argue the same for the sale of private homes and objects of art,
analysts suggest.
   The package of tax breaks to be included in Bush's budget plan
all reflect promises he made during last year's presidential
campaign.
   However, White House officials say it seems unlikely that all of
Bush's promises will make it into the document _ budget constraints
being what they are.
   Bush must propose a plan that will get the federal budget
deficit, currently hovering at about $150 billion, down to below the
Gramm-Rudman target of $100 billion for the fiscal year beginning
Oct. 1.
   And, he has repeatedly vowed, he will do it without proposing new
taxes.
   ``Obviously we'll be setting priorities. I think you'll see
education, environmennt, child care,'' said a senior White House
official, insisting on anonmymity.
   On education, the official said the budget plan would highlight
``a few guiding principles,'' such as excellence and achievement and
accountability and choice of schools.
   However, some of Bush's campaign promises on education _
including a $500 million National Merit scholarship program, an
expansion of the Head Start program and a $50 million increase in
school experimentation _ may be considerably pruned back, sources
said.
   The sources also said Bush's campaign proposal to expand Medicaid
coverage to more lower-income Americans and to allow low-paid
workers to purchase it was being given a low priority in budget
preparation talks.
   ``There's no question George Bush wants to make this a kinder,
gentler nation. But he also wants to reduce the federal deficit. The
two have to be reconciled,'' said the senior White House official.
   Budget Director Richard G. Darman and Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady have been meeting almost daily to discuss key budget
decisions, according to White House aides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
