<FIRST>r a AM-INS-CentralAmericans     01-31 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS-Central Americans,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says He'll Probably Let INS Restrict Travel Of Asylum Applicants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Tuesday he
probably will allow the Immigration and Naturalization Service to
return to a policy of restricting political asylum applicants to
southern Texas pending reviews.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela extended until Feb. 20 an order
blocking the procedure, but added: ``At that time, unless I'm
persuaded otherwise, the restraining order will be lifted.''
   ``We're pleased with the results,'' said William Joyce, associate
general counsel for the INS, who traveled from Washington for
Tuesday's hearing. ``The judge was fair.''
   INS critics cited a sharp increase in homeless Central Americans
living in squalid conditions in the area after the procedure took
effect Dec. 16. A group of immigration attorneys sued the INS over
the matter here on Jan. 6, and on Jan. 9 Vela issued a temporary
restraining order blocking the procedure.
   Under the procedure, the district began requiring asylum
applicants to file their claims in Harlingen and await decisions
there in 30 days, a period in which they were not allowed to work.
The most visible effect of the travel restriction was a rugged
campsite east of Brownsville, where more than 300 Central Americans
camped out on the ground under discarded cardboard and sheets of
plastic.
   Huge case backlogs in cities such as Miami and Los Angeles made
it necessary to keep the immigrants near their points of entry while
the government sorted out thousands of unfounded asylum claims, the
government maintains.
   The only issue Vela agreed to consider in the class-action
lawsuit, on behalf of Central Americans and other asylum-seekers in
the INS' Harlingen District, was whether the INS instituted the
change without allowing time for public comment as required in the
federal Administrative Procedures Act.
   ``I am somewhat inclined to believe that probably what was taking
place here would not require a notice and comment ... was more
procedural than substantive,'' Vela said.
   Robert Rubin, one of the attorneys suing the INS, said the
plaintiffs still hope the judge will rule against the INS after a
closer examination of the suit.
   ``The judge certainly indicated that he was not happy with the
situation as it existed, and strongly admonished the government that
he would be concerned if conditions ever returned to the state that
existed prior to his issuance of a temporary restraining order,''
said Rubin, with the San Francisco Lawyers' Committee for Urban
Affairs.
   Before Dec. 16, the INS allowed asylum-seekers who voluntarily
presented themselves to the Harlingen District to travel on to their
U.S. destinations, where they often were allowed to work while
pursuing their claims for refugee status.
   Hundreds of Central Americans left the area on northbound buses
and other vehicles after Vela made it possible for them to travel
again Jan. 9.
   Many headed for Miami. But officials from the Miami area visited
southern Texas to tell the refugees they had no shelter for them,
and joined officials in Texas in calling on the federal government
for help.
   Vela said he was concerned with past asylum statistics showing
that, of the thousands who traveled into the U.S. interior, 75
percent never showed up at INS offices to legally pursue their cases.
   More than 30,000 Central Americans, about half of them from
Nicaragua, passed through the Harlingen District in 1988, most
having crossed the Rio Grande illegally in the vicinity of the
border city of Brownsville, according to the INS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
