<FIRST>r w AM-Hospitals-Medicare 1stLd-Writethru a0647 01-31 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospitals-Medicare, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with Bentsen proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seek Moratorium on Cuts in Medicare Payments to Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 160 senators and representatives put
their names on a proposed resolution Tuesday seeking a one-year
moratorium on cuts in Medicare payments to hospitals.
   Reductions in Medicare payments to health care institutions will
accelerate the growing rate of hospital closures, putting the health
care of the elderly, disabled and even entire communities at risk,
the lawmakers said.
   Though they acknowledged the nation's budget pressures, the
sponsors said Congress also needs time to analyze the impact of the
payment policies of the $87 billion federal health insurance program
for the elderly and disabled.
   ``One year from now I think we're going to be in a position to
make a better judgment about where we should go and what we should
do,'' said Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a chief sponsor of the
non-binding resolution. ``But to devastate hospitals further today,
to put the squeeze on the poor and elderly of this nation is
unwise.''
   Former President Reagan, before he left office last month, sent
Congress a proposed budget for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1,
that trimmed $2.4 billion from Medicare Part A, the section of the
program that pays hospitals. He also proposed cutting about $1
billion from Medicare Part B, which pays physicians.
   Reagan called for a total 10 percent growth in total Medicare
spending, which would hold the program's budget to $94.9 billion
next year.
   President Bush is due to send Congress his budget proposal next
week, and according to Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., chairman of the
House Ways and Means subcommittee on health, the Medicare portion is
expected to be about the same as Reagan proposed.
   Stark told reporters that Bush budget director Richard Darman
told him last week that his budget proposal ``won't be much
different from the Reagan proposal relative to Medicare, and my
guess is the (House) Budget Committee will come out at somewhere
between $2 (billion) and $5 (billion) cut in Medicare.''
   ``I can't really see that we'll do anything different from what
we've done in previous years, and that means we'll take some out of
the hospitals and some out of the doctors and will try to give some
assistance in that to the inner city hospitals ... and rural
hospitals,'' he said.
   Members of the American Hospital Association are in Washington
this week for the group's annual meeting and they have been visiting
the lawmakers on Capitol Hill about issues of interest, including
the resolution for a one-year reprieve from cuts.
   ``This resolution is very important to say: Wait. We simply
cannot make further reductions without cutting into the quality of
care,'' said Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.
   The lawmakers noted that more than 80 hospitals closed last year,
more than 400 have closed since 1982 and many others are losing
money, particularly rural and inner city hospitals. Medicare
cutbacks are largely to blame, they said.
   ``Fifty percent of hospitals are losing money on every Medicare
patient,'' said Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn. ``We cannot cost-cut
with blindness to the consequences of that policy.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, introduced legislation
designed to save faltering rural hospitals by boosting government
reimbursements for patient care and improving physican recruitment.
   Bentsen blamed inequities in the Medicare prospective payment
system for contributing to the problems of rural hospitals. Under
the program, hospitals are reimbursed for the average costs of their
elderly Medicare patients and not on actual costs.
</TEXT>
