<FIRST>r w AM-ReillyHearing     01-31 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reilly Hearing,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Chief Promises Acid Rain Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Reilly, picked to head the
Environmental Protection Agency, said Tuesday his chief
anti-pollution priority will be acid rain and he promised to produce
a legislative proposal for the problem as soon as possible.
   ``Acid rain for our point of view is first out of the box,'' he
told the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee. The panel is
expected to vote later this week on Reilly's nomination as head of
the federal government's top agency dealing with the environment.
   ``It's ahead of everything else,'' Reilly said at another point
when asked by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., if he believed acid
rain was a serious problem.
   For more than six years, Congress has been grappling with
legislation to curb acid rain. But tough national legislation didn't
gain White House support under former President Reagan and last year
became bogged down in Congress.
   Acid rain, blamed for polluting vast areas of vegetation, streams
and lakes along the country's northern tier and in Canada, is caused
primarily by emissions from fossil fuel burning plants in the
Midwest and Ohio Valley.
   Reilly said President Bush is committed to ``the substantial
reduction of acid rain by the end of this century'' and the EPA is
working to develop proposed changes in the federal Clean Air Act to
deal with the acid rain problem.
   During the 2{-hour hearing, both Republicans and Democrats,
including senators who are often on opposite sides, praised Reilly,
who for 16 years has been executive director of the Conservation
Foundation and the president of World Wildlife Fund.
   Sen. Quentin Burdick, R-N.D., committee chairman, called Reilly
``a person ... who appreciates that a great nation must be a good
steward of its land, its air, its water and its natural resources.''
   ``I'm pleased to join the chorus of admirers and welcomers,''
said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., noting Reilly was introduced to
the panel by no fewer than five senators from three states.
   Sen. Steven Symms, R-Idaho, objected to what he called the EPA's
often ``heavy handed'' approach to enforcing environmental laws. But
he praised Reilly's nomination.
   Reilly promised to enforce such laws ``aggressively and timely
whenever it is warranted to safeguard public health and
environmental quality,'' but said he also hopes to deal with
environmental problems through consensus and cooperation.
   Denouncing the ``bitterness, the polarization, the wasted
resources and other excesses'' that have marked conflicts between
environmentalists and industry in the past, Reilly said he is
convinced the country can both protect its environment and have
economic growth.
   Several senators, noting Reilly's desire for consensus, expressed
concern that the approach might lead to inaction on part of the EPA.
   ``Will you conciliate, mediate, negotiate away our environmental
laws?'' asked Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who supported Reilly.
   Lieberman urged Reilly to be ``an environmental advocate'' in the
Bush administration and not allow the EPA to be a ``reluctant
combatant as it often has been'' in the Reagan administration.
   ``You can count on me being an advocate,'' replied Reilly.
</TEXT>
