<FIRST>r a AM-People-O'Neill     01-31 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-O'Neill,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests Prove Governor's Polyps Benign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two tiny polyps removed from Gov. William
A. O'Neill's colon were found to be non-cancerous, according to test
results released Tuesday.
   The polyps were discovered and removed Monday during O'Neill's
regularly scheduled six-month checkup. A year ago, one of three
polyps removed from O'Neill's colon contained cancer cells. Three
removed in June were benign.
   ``We are very happy to report that the pathology analysis has
confirmed that the two polyps are a common type of benign polyp,''
said Dr. Jay Benson, coordinator of gastroenterology at St. Francis
Hospital and Medical Center in Hartford.
   ``There was no evidence of any malignancy or pre-cancerous
changes. Removal of the polyps constitutes complete and definitive
treatment,'' Benson said.
   He said O'Neill, 58, would be required to return for another
checkup in six months because there is, on average, a 5 percent to
15 percent chance of recurrence.
   O'Neill went to his office after Monday's procedure and resumed
normal working hours Tuesday.
</TEXT>
