<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-YellowstoneFires     01-31 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone Fires,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memo Says Park Service Staffers Fought Fires Unenthusiastically</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Denis is correct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Park Service staffers in Yellowstone
National Park fought last summer's forest fires so
unenthusiastically that critics might well charge them with illegal
use of funds, according to an internal memo given to Congress on
Tuesday.
   The Aug. 15 memo was written for the western regional director by
Sequoia National Park fire specialist Howard Nichols, who paid a
one-week visit to Yellowstone starting last July 28 to help project
the courses of the fires.
   On July 21, Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel ordered the
service to drop its ``let it burn'' policy and fight all fires. By
the time snow arrived in late September, more than 700,000 acres, a
third of the park, had been burned over, though the service says
almost all of that will quickly rejuvenate.
   Under the ``let it burn'' policy, fires that met certain
conditions were supposed to be allowed to burn themselves out, but
fires that threatened lives or developed areas or areas outside the
park were supposed to be fought.
   The Forest Service, part of the Agriculture Department, conducts
commercial timbering on most land adjacent to Yellowstone, and
fights all fires there.
   ``The tactics used for these fires might well result in the
suggestion that Yellowstone was using suppression dollars to achieve
natural resource benefits, a patently illegal use of these funds,''
said the Nichols memo.
   Rep. Ron Marlenee, R-Mont., submitted the memo at a joint hearing
of the national parks subcommittee of the House Interior Committee
and the forests subcommittee of the House Agriculture Committee.
   On the memo, another official, Bruce Kilgore, chief of resource
management and research in the western region of the service, had
written, ``Perhaps not circulated widely at this time ... until we
get our act together.''
   Projections made on July 3 by the Yellowstone staff ``showed, as
we did, that the Fan fire would eventually leave Yellowstone and
burn Forest Service lands. Yet no firm suppression action was taken
until the fire was within a mile of the boundary,'' Nichols wrote.
   The memo said the Yellowstone staff often ``seemed to be
satisfied to call the ... park boundary the confinement line''
corresponding to natural boundaries that could be relied on to check
fires, ``although few natural barriers could be found there.''
   After Hodel's order, ``in spite of millions being spent and 2,000
fires, Yellowstone staffers were bemoaning the fact that new starts,
as mandated by the secretary'' had to be fought, the memo said.
   Despite his criticisms, Nichols said the fires had improved the
ecosystem of the park.
   Marlenee said the memo showed that Hodel's policy was ``not being
carried out,'' though it did not make specific allegations that the
secretary's order was disobeyed.
   Denis Galvin, deputy director of the park service, said points
raised in the memo would be ``absolutely'' checked out by an
internal investigations team.
   Marlenee and other members of the Congress have accused the park
service of disregarding the interests of residents dependent on
tourism through the ``let it burn'' policy.
</TEXT>
