<DOCNO> AP890131-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WindErosion     01-31 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wind Erosion,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wind Damage to Land Worse in November, December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wind damage to land in the Great Plains is up
sharply, reflecting the 1988 drought that hit much of the nation in
the spring and summer, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Wilson Scaling, chief of the department's Soil Conservation
Service, said nearly 2.2 million acres were reported damaged in
November and December, up more than 80 percent from 1.2 million
acres in the same two months of 1987.
   ``A lot of the damage is a result of drought,'' Scaling said.
``The reasons vary by area, but major factors are lack of (crop)
residue and poor vegetative cover _ both caused by a lack of
moisture.''
   Scaling said more than 80 percent of the land reported damaged
was cropland, the remainder primarily rangeland.
   Texas accounted for more than 30 percent of the erosion damage in
November and December with 664,128 acres.
   Scaling said that in addition to the damaged land in November and
December, nearly 19 million acres were ``in condition to blow,''
with five months still remaining in the critical wind season.
   November and December are the first two months of an annual
seven-month season when winds are highest and the soils are driest
in the Great Plains. Surveys were made in 541 counties of the
10-state region.
   Although the 1987-88 season began with relatively light damage,
it picked up as moisture conditions worsened. When the season ended
last May 31, more than 13 million acres had been damaged, the
second-largest acreage since the agency began records in 1935.
   The most widespread was in 1955 when about 16 million acres of
Great Plains land were damaged by wind. Another bad year was 1980-81
when 12.5 million acres were damaged.
   According to the survey, the state-by-state breakdown comparing
damaged acres in November and December with the damage during the
same two months of 1987-88, included:
   _Colorado, 28,795 acres damaged this season and 17,070 in 1987-88.
   _Kansas, 135,550 and 31,520.
   _Montana, 510,875 and 304,023.
   _Nebraska, 54,405 and 74,590.
   _New Mexico, 51,100 and 3,300.
   _North Dakota, 188,200 and 230,000.
   _Oklahoma, 68,480 and 31,288.
   _South Dakota, 112,250 and 69,400.
   _Texas, 664,128 and 250,220.
   _Wyoming, 346,754 and 190,885.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sharansky 1stLd-Writethru   01-31 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sharansky, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0585,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Soviet Dissident Israel's U.N. Ambassador?</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Pazner saying Sharansky not
officially nominated yet. Pick up 6th pvs, `Sharansky, 41...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after stepping out of Soviet prison,
human rights activist Natan Sharansky appears headed for a new
career as Israel's ambassador to the United Nations.
   An aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and another senior
government official Tuesday confirmed radio reports that Shamir
chose Sharansky for the post, which will have to be approved by the
Cabinet.
   Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokesman, said the prime minister hopes the
former refusenik's worldwide popularity will be a boon to Israel's
public image that has taken a beating during the Palestinian
uprising.
   ``We hope he could help improve our image,'' Pazner said. ``This
is definitely the consideration.''
   Later, however, Pazner said in a statement that Sharansky had not
yet been officially nominated. ``Such an idea was indeed raised, but
there is no decision yet on that nomination,'' he said.
   The report that Sharansky was chosen took many Israelis by
surprise and prompted concern among some diplomats about angering
the Soviet Union at a time when Moscow has ended a 20-year
diplomatic break to improve ties with the Jewish state.
   Sharansky, 41, served nine years of a 13-year sentence in Soviet
prisons and labor camp on charges of anti-Soviet espionage before
being freed in a dramatic East-West spy swap on Berlin's Glienicke
Bridge on Feb. 11, 1986.
   Sharansky was an outspoken activist for the emigration movement
of Soviet Jews and belonged to a human rights committee headed by
Nobel Peace Prize laureate Andrei Sakharov that sharply criticized
Soviet treatment of prisoners and national minorities.
   Sharansky's case was made famous largely by the efforts of his
wife, Avital, who waged a tireless campaign during their forced
separation of 12 years.
   Sharansky did not answer his telephone Tuesday and declined
direct comment when interviewed by Israel army radio, saying he had
not been formally appointed.
   Pressed by the interviewer, Sharansky added: ``I will say only
what I want to say. I have enough experience with interrogations and
I know how to give answers.''
   A government official said Sharansky also was the choice of
Israel's Russian-born Foreign Minister Moshe Arens. His appointment
will need approval from Finance Minister Shimon Peres under his
Labor Party's coalition agreement with Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc. It also will need Cabinet approval.
   One government official said on condition of anonymity that the
approval may be delayed over fears of offending the Soviet Union,
which has warmed ties with Israel recently. The Soviets broke
relations after Israel occupied Arab land during the 1967 Middle
East war.
   ``Now that we're on the eve of renewing diplomatic ties, on such
a delicate time in our relations with Moscow, it could take some
time to determine whether this would not offend them,'' said the
official.
   Sharansky has kept a low profile in Israel. Last year, he founded
a lobby group that seeks to improve conditions for thousands of
Soviet emigres plagued by shortages in jobs and housing.
   He has stayed out of politics and said in a recent interview with
The Associated Press that he had not found his place in any of the
parties.
   He was critical of the divisiveness in Israel's 120-member
Parliament that has 15 parties and said he would like to see the
electoral system changed. ``I'm concern that everything in Israel is
partisan. I'd like to see more mutual values and consensus in party
politics,'' Sharansky said.
   At the United Nations, Sharansky may find himself being called on
to defend Israel's strong tactics in trying to quell the nearly
14-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Arab groups once sought his support in vain, he said. ``To say
that because Sharansky was against the Soviet Union this should also
make him against the Israeli government, this isn't true. There is
no parallel between them,'' he said.
   Sharansky said he investigated complaints about Israel's behavior
in the territories and defended the stance of his new homeland.
   ``For a country in a state of war, you cannot have the same rules
as for a country not at war. But it is important to keep
democracy,'' Sharansky said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
