<FIRST>r w AM-BurleyProgram     01-31 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burley Program,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tobacco Quotas, Price Supports Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burley tobacco farmers will have a 1989
national marketing quota of 587.6 million pounds, up 24 percent from
last year's 473 million pounds, the Agriculture Department announced
Tuesday.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said the 1989 crop
price support will be $1.532 per pound, up 3.2 cents from the 1988
level.
   Goldberg said the budget deficit assessment _ an assessment on
payments mandated by 1987 budget legislation _ on this year's crop
will be 0.34 cents per pound, divided equally between the producer
and buyer of burley tobacco. The assessment to finance the
no-net-cost burley program will be announced later, he said.
   Burley tobacco producers will be polled Feb. 27 to March 2 to
decide whether marketing quotas on a poundage basis will continue
for the next three years, he said. More than a two-thirds majority
of those voting are required for approval of the quotas. In the last
vote, 97 percent favored quotas for the 1986, 1987 and 1988 crops.
</TEXT>
