<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Newspaper     01-31 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Newspaper,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Newspaper Folds After 112 Years, Bans By Bismarck and Hitler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newspaper Vorwaerts (Forward),
which survived bans by Bismarck and Hitler and championed Social
Democratic causes for 112 years, is folding because of heavy
financial losses, the party said Tuesday.
   The Social Democratic Party has spent about $27 million since
1970 to cover the weekly newspaper's losses.
   But rising costs and falling circulation forced the party to
close the newspaper, party treasurer Hans-Ulrich Klose told
reporters.
   The decision, reached ``with a heavy heart,'' came after it
became clear that the leftist-liberal newspaper would not be able to
raise its circulation of 46,000 by 50 percent.
   The weekly's staff of 44 will lose their jobs when the last issue
goes on sale on Saturday.
   Founded in 1876 by Wilhelm Hasenclever and Wilhelm Liebknecht,
Vorwaerts stopped appearing for 12 years when Chancellor Otto von
Bismarck banned the Social Democrats in 1878.
   Vorwaerts took a strong anti-Nazi line and was banned by Adolf
Hitler in 1933. Its staff went into exile and continued to publish
in Prague and then Paris until German troops marched into Paris in
1940.
   The newspaper returned to German soil in September 1948 as the
official organ of the Social Democratic party.
   The national printers trade union criticized the decision by the
party's leadership to fold the paper, saying the public was losing
``an important voice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
