<FIRST>r w AM-BarbaraBush     01-31 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Grandmother Helps Out at Center for the Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush on Tuesday helped make
sandwiches for the homeless and read to children at a daycare center
for poor children as she visited a drug-infested area of the
nation's capital to laud the work of volunteers.
   Arriving at Martha's Table about 20 blocks from the White House,
Mrs. Bush put on a red apron to make salami and cheese sandwiches
for a food truck operated by the non-profit center to feed the
homeless.
   That done, she sat in a rocking chair as children from the
facility's daycare center gathered around, quietly munching cookies
she had brought from the White House.
   Mrs. Bush, the mother of five and grandmother of 10, read from
the book ``How Fletcher Was Hatched.''
   At one point, a dog in the book was described as howling. Mrs.
Bush looked at the children's upturned faces and asked, ``Who can
howl like a dog?''
   That produced a cacaphony of yelping with little resemblence to a
howl but Mrs. Bush smiled and said, ``You got it.''
   The book proved to be longer than she had anticipated _ ``This is
the longest book,'' she exclaimed at one point _ so she deftly
summarized and improvised to avoid reading page after page.
   The children seemed to take her visit in stride. When she had
finished, one girl asked her to quiz the audience on what they'd
just heard.
   Mrs. Bush merrily complied, asking about the name of the
protagonist dog and the story's plot as the children chorused the
answers.
   Asked by reporters if she planned to make the homeless and needy
a special project, she noted that she is also involved in fighting
illiteracy and said, ``Anybody who needs help and I can help them,
I'm planning to try to help.''
   She said she hoped her visit to Martha's Table would help
Americans realize how important volunteers are, ``what a job they do
and how really important it is to help people who need a little
help.''
</TEXT>
