<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     01-31 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Charges Coverup On Chun; Students Attack U.S. Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition accused the government
of a coverup after prosecutors issued a report Tuesday that did not
link former President Chun Doo-hwan to corruption and power abuse.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, dozens of students demanding
punishment for Chun and the withdrawal of American troops threw
firebombs at a U.S. cultural center for the second time this month.
   The three main opposition parties said they will jointly seek to
appoint a special prosecutor to make a thorough investigation of
alleged wrongdoing involving Chun, his family and associates during
Chun's seven-year rule.
   In a report wrapping up nearly a year of investigation, the
prosecution said 47 people have been arrested, including 13 members
of Chun's family, a former intelligence chief, two ex-Cabinet
ministers, a governing party lawmaker and a former Seoul mayor.
   Senior prosecutor Park Chong-chul said 20 others have been
indicted but not detained. No dates for trial were given.
   Those arrested or indicted were charged with embezzlement and
abuse of authority for personal gain, but none was accused of
raising illegal political funds for Chun, a major charge raised by
the opposition.
   Prosecutor General Kim Ki-choon said the prosecution conducted
its investigation in a ``neutral and independent manner.''
   Rep. Lee Sang-soo, spokesman for the largest opposition group,
the Party for Peace and Democracy, said the report showed the
prosecution took its cue from President Roh Tae-woo and did not look
into alleged wrongdoing by Chun.
   Roh, who has carried out broad reform and sought to distance
himself from Chun, has opposed punishment for the authoritarian
former president, saying it would amount to retaliation.
   Suh Chung-won, spokesman for the No. 2 opposition group, the
Reunification Democratic Party, also accused the government of a
coverup and called for the appointment of a special prosecutor.
   Chun, 58, who left office last February, denied any personal
corruption, but he surrendered $24 million in political funds before
going into rural exile in November.
   Radical students and dissidents have demonstrated frequently in
recent months, demanding that Chun be punished on charges of
corruption and human rights violations.
   About 50 radical students, shouting anti-Chun and anti-U.S.
slogans, hurled dozens of firebombs at the U.S. cultural center in
Kwangju, an opposition stronghold 180 miles southwest of Seoul.
   The U.S. Embassy in Seoul reported no casualties or property
damage. Local news reports said about 100 South Korean riot police
guarding the center fired tear gas and chased the attackers away in
a few minutes.
   Earlier Tuesday, the U.S. Embassy in Seoul denied reports it
decided to close the Kwangju center but said it could be shut down
after more attacks, of which there were 26 since 1981 and six last
year alone.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the
United States has been seeking promises from South Korean
authorities that they would provide adequate protection for the
Kwangju center and its staff.
</TEXT>
