<FIRST>r w AM-Mexico-Drugs     01-31 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department to Review State Request on Mexico Drug Info</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Tuesday it will
review a State Department request that it give Mexico information
linking top law enforcement officials in that country to narcotics
trafficking.
   David Runkel, an aide to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh,
confirmed that the department had received the Jan. 13 letter
written by then-Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Shultz's letter relayed a request from Mexican President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari for information in U.S. law enforcement files
that might link Mexican officials in his government to illegal drugs.
   The request is expected to be greeted cooly by federal law
enforcement officials who fear that sharing such information with
Mexico could compromise intelligence and endanger the lives of
informants.
   Runkel declined to comment on how the department might respond to
the request, saying only: ``There are some issues'' raised by
Shultz's letter.
   Illegal drug traffic has been a sore subject of U.S.-Mexican
relations over the past few years. U.S. officials, notably some
members of Congress, have accused Mexico of not doing enough to rid
law enforcement agencies of corrupt officials.
   Mexico, for its part, has accused the United States of being the
source of the drug problem, pointing to the deman for illegal drugs
among Americans.
</TEXT>
