<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-31 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold And Warm Weather Clash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Record Highs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe cold, high wind and blowing and drifting snow moved into
the north-central part of the nation Tuesday, while southerly
breezes from the Gulf of Mexico spread unseasonable warmth across
the central part of the nation.
   At least 39 cities reported record high temperatures for the
date, from Colorado to Ohio and from Fort Worth, Texas, to St.
Cloud, Minn.
   But elsewhere, a blizzard warning was posted through the night
for the eastern slopes of the Rockies in Montana, where East Glacier
had received 6 inches of snow by mid-afternoon and wind gusting up
to 45 mph caused blowing and drifting snow and create very low wind
chill factors.
   Storm warnings and watches also were posted for the rest of
Montana, northern Idaho, Wyoming, northern Colorado, northeastern
North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota.
   Elsewhere, snow fell over parts of the Northwest, including the
Cascade Mountains of Washington state and the mountains of Oregon,
and a winter storm watch was posted for northwestern Oregon.
   A few showers were scattered across New York state and Vermont.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 20
degrees below zero at Cut Bank, Mont., to 82 at Fort Myers and
Naples, Fla. Tuesday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 19
degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Wednesday, snow was forecast over the mountains of the
Pacific Northwest through the northern high Plains to Upper
Michigan, accompanied by strong, gusty wind over the northern
Plains. Scattered showers were forecast from the central Pacific
Coast through the mid Mississippi Valley to New England.
   Highs remaining below freezing were predicted from the central
Rockies through Nebraska and the Dakotas to Upper Michigan,
including highs remaining below zero across Montana and North
Dakota; above 50 from the southern and central coast of California
through the southern half of the Plains to the Atlantic Coast, as
far north as southern New England; and in the 70s and lower 80s over
much of the area from the southern Plains to the southern Atlantic
Coast.
</TEXT>
