<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PublicBroadcasting     01-31 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public Broadcasting,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ledwig Re-Elected CPB Head, Sets Priorities in Budget Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald E. Ledwig was re-elected president and
chief executive officer of the Corporation for Public Broadcasting
on Tuesday, and urged public broadcasters to join together to fight
for money from Congress.
   The election of the 51-year-old Ledwig, who has held the position
since July 1987, took place at the CPB board meeting in San Juan,
Puerto Rico, the CPB said.
   The board also discussed CPB's proposed operating budget for
fiscal year 1990. The budget calls for $254.3 million for public
broadcasting purposes.
   The budget, which will be voted on at the board's March meeting,
calls for increasing to $9 million program funds for independent
producers and minorities.
   In all, Congress has designated $233 million in fiscal year 1990
for CPB, a private, non-profit corporation that develops
non-commercial radio and television services.
   President Reagan's fiscal 1990 budget proposal, which includes
CPB funds for the following two years, calls for $242 million in
fiscal year 1991 and a freeze on spending in 1992.
   Reagan's budget calls for elimination of funds for the Star
Schools satellite delivery program operated by the Satellite
Educational Resources Consortium.
   His budget also calls for no additional funds to replace an aging
satellite that delivers programs to public radio and TV stations.
   Ledwig said Tuesday he would urge Congress this spring to fully
fund CPB's fiscal 1992 authorization of $265 million and to free the
remainder of the $200 million authorized for the satellite's
replacement.
   Ledwig told Congress last year that unless the satellite is
replaced, the skies will go dark for public stations that rely on it
to receive programming from the Public Broadcasting Service.
   At its meeting Tuesday, the board also re-elected Paul E.
Symczak, vice president, general counsel and secretary; Frederick L.
DeMarco, vice president and treasurer; and Rozanne Weissman, vice
president for corporate communications.
</TEXT>
