<FIRST>u w AM-Tower 2ndLd-Writethru a0706 01-31 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0706,980</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   Critic Says He's Seen Tower Inebriated, With Other Women
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf of Nunn comment after 5th graf, `Senators emerging,'
INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs, `The committee,' with committee continuing
hearings Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative activist testified Tuesday he
has ``on a number of occasions'' seen Defense Secretary-designate
John Tower publicly inebriated and in the company of women other
than his wife.
   But members of the Senate Armed Services Committee said after a
closed session with the witness that he failed to provide specifics
to support his allegation.
   ``I have made enough personal observations of this man here in
Washington to have serious reservations about his moral character,''
Paul Weyrich told the Senate panel, which is conducting Tower's
confirmation hearing.
   Weyrich's comments prompted quick criticism from Sen. Malcolm
Wallop, R-Wyo., who complained about ``innuendos ... and
insinuations'' against the former Texas senator.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the chairman, suggested any further
discussion of Tower's personal fitness take place in a previously
scheduled afternoon session that was closed to the public.
   Senators emerging from that session sounded unimpressed.
   ``A number of allegations prove to be wrong,'' said Nunn, who
added that the committee is ``continuing to pursue all allegations.''
   ``I heard nothing that you didn't hear in the open session. I
didn't hear anything persuasive to me,'' Wallop said.
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., said, ``As an old trial lawyer, I would
have to say that most of what I heard has to fall into the hearsay
category, even given the high motives of the witness.''
   Weyrich was unclear if Tower was married on the occasions he saw
him, according to Dixon.
   ``Beyond statements of seeing Senator Tower on a couple of
occasions carrying a little more alcohol than he should have, he
hasn't been able to add anything specific that wasn't hearsay,''
said Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   Tower refused to comment on the allegations or executive session
as he left the committee office.
   The committee has been expected to approve Tower to head the
Defense Department, and there was no immediate indication that
Weyrich's remarks would change that.
   A closed session is scheduled Wednesday morning followed by an
open session on conflict of interest, Nunn said. Asked if the
committee's work would be completed, Nunn responded, ``I hope so.''
   The committee chairman said he was unsure if they would vote this
week on the nomination. Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., said he expected a
vote next week.
   Tower was not present when Weyrich took the witness chair and
uttered in public the allegations that had simmered for several
weeks while President Bush was deciding on a candidate to head the
Pentagon.
   ``Over many years, I have encountered the nominee in a condition
lacking sobriety as well as with women to whom he was not married; I
recognize senators' wives because I worked here in the Senate for
many years,'' Weyrich said.
   ``I did encounter this on a number of occasions.''
   Other witnesses also spoke out against the nominee, questioning
Tower's support for the Star Wars defense proposal and his ability
to institute Pentagon reforms in light of his past ties to defense
contractors.
   But it was Weyrich, head of the Free Congress Foundation and a
longtime proponent for the most conservative of Republican causes,
who got the most attention.
   He contended that Bush's transition team received hundreds of
letters criticizing Tower, some containing specific allegations of
moral impropriety against the nominee, but did not bring the letters
to the president's attention. But Weyrich said he never saw the
letters.
   Tower was dogged by allegations of drinking and womanizing before
his nomination was announced. In divorce papers filed by his second
wife, Lilla Burt Cummings, Tower was accused of ``marital
misconduct.''
   Bush has defended Tower, saying an FBI background check found
nothing that would prevent him from serving as defense secretary.
When he announced the nomination he dismissed ``a lot of rumors that
proved to be groundless.''
   Tower, a 63-year-old Texas Republican, served 24 years in the
Senate, including a tenure as chairman of the Armed Services
Committee from 1981-84.
   Weyrich also criticized Tower's record on the Strategic Defense
Initiative, saying that the nominee sees Star Wars as a ``bargaining
chip'' for negotiations.
   Tower said last week he does not ``believe that we can devise an
umbrella that can protect the entire American population from
nuclear incineration. I think that's unrealistic.'' He said a more
limited system might work but cautioned that ``it remains to be seen
whether that is a realistic objective.''
   William G. Phillips, president of the National Council for
Industrial Defense, questioned Tower's commitment to Pentagon reform
in the wake of last year's Pentagon procurement scandal and the
former senator's ties to defense contractors.
   ``His confirmation would signal to the defense contractor
community that they have little to fear from any meaningful reform
of defense procurement procedures,'' Phillips said.
   ``It would signal that the `revolving door' of Pentagon-defense
contractors relationships was still in vogue,'' he said.
   Tower said last week in two days of testimony that he received
fees of more than $1 million for consulting work for seven defense
contractors, including such industry giants as Rockwell and
Martin-Marietta.
   He promised to implement reform recommendations of a presidential
commission and the Goldwater-Nichols Act.
   William E. Jackson Jr., senior fellow at the Fulbright Institute
of International Relations at the University of Arkansas, accused
Tower of stonewalling Pentagon reforms and said the former senator
``never met a weapons systems he didn't like.''
   ``I do not see the need for someone associated with a `fire hose'
approach to the defense budget and someone who is mired in the
`revolving door' culture,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
