<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Skinner comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted unanimous approval Tuesday
evening of Samuel K. Skinner as President Bush's transportation
secretary.
   Skinner, whose confirmation came only hours after a Senate
committee swiftly approved the nomination, said, ``I will work hard
to make all modes of transportation safer, more efficient and less
expensive for the American consumer.''
   He also pledged to work with Congress, the public, transportation
industries and all interested groups to develop a new national
transportation policy ``for the 1990s and beyond.''
   Both Democrats and Republicans on the Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee praised Skinner as an excellent nominee.
The panel took less than five seconds to give unanimous voice-vote
approval to the former federal prosecutor who flies airplanes and
has been running the nation's second-largest transit system in
northern Illinois.
   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., praised all of Bush's Cabinet
selections, saying he was ``deeply impressed by the openness,
integrity and the smarts'' of both Skinner and Robert Mosbacher,
whose nomination as commerce secretary also was approved by the
committee.
   On one controversial issue, in written response to a committee
question submitted after last week's hearing, Skinner said he would
review the mileage standards required of automakers for 1990.
   Unless the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration acts,
the standard would increase from 26.5 miles per gallon for 1989 to
27.5 for 1990. The auto industry opposes the tougher standard set
under a federal fuel conservation law.
   Skinner, 50, also promised during his confirmation hearing to
support mandatory drug testing for transportation workers in
safety-related jobs, to combat air terrorism and to push for
fairness to U.S. airlines abroad even if it means putting him at
odds with the State Department.
   He said he would work to build up the Coast Guard and the
maritime industry.
   Skinner, nicknamed ``Sam the Hammer,'' gained a reputation for
toughness as he headed up a special investigative team that
successfully prosecuted former Illinois Gov. Otto Kerner for bribery
in 1973.
   His nomination faced no opposition after the committee cleared
away a brief controversy over Skinner's failure as U.S. attorney to
prosecute a major drug manufacturer.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, had questioned Skinner's failure
to prosecute G.D. Searle Co. on allegations that it falsified test
results on its Nutrasweet artificial sweetener.
   Metzenbaum withdrew his objections after talking with Skinner,
however, and announced his support for the nomination. Skinner told
the committee the decision not to prosecute was made by his
successor but he acknowledged making minor mistakes as he recused
himself from the case and joined the law firm that had represented
Searle.
   Metzenbaum and other committee members said they were convinced
Skinner had acted honorably and honestly in the matter.
   Skinner has been a close associate of Illinois Gov. James R.
Thompson and headed Bush's 1980 and 1988 presidential campaigns in
Illinois.
</TEXT>
