<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-MafiaArms     01-31 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Mafia Arms,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italians Break Mafia-Terrorist Arms and Drug Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say they smashed a drug and
weapons operation by the Sicilian Mafia and right-wing extremists
that included plans to sell French warplanes to Guinea-Bissau in
West Africa.
   Newspapers said Tuesday at least 48 people had been arrested.
   At a news conference Monday, authorities said 72 arrest warrants
were issued on charges of criminal association and trafficking in
arms and drugs for suspects in Italy and abroad, including the
United States and Switzerland. Names of suspects living outside
Italy were not disclosed.
   La Stampa, a Turin daily, said the investigation also extended to
Argentina, Brazil, Canada, Chile and Nigeria.
   Judge Alba Dova issued the warrants in Massa Carrara, a Tuscan
coastal city where the investigation was coordinated for more than a
year.
   Dova said the link between the Mafia and right-wing terrorists
``leads one to think of the existence of an international extremist
right wing political organization that finances itself through
illegal financial operations and ties with organized crime.''
   Much of the illegal traffic was said to have been arranged
through two Italian import-export companies.
   Other illegal activities included trafficking in stolen art, cars
and foreign currency. Some of the money was allegedly recycled
through coded Swiss bank accounts.
   A key figure in the warrants is Marco Affatigato, a reputed
leader of Nuova Ordine (New Order), which is accused of several
terrorist attacks in Italy in the 1970s and early 1980s.
   Affatigato is believed to be in France. Whether he had been
arrested was not known.
   Among Mafia suspects caught in raids Monday were members of the
Corleone family, considered Sicily's most powerful Mafia clan, and
of the Minore family from Trapani, a port in western Sicily linked
to clandestine drug and arms shipments.
   The man thought to be the Corleone ``cashier,'' Michele Cillari,
was among better-known figures arrested.
   Judge Dova said the investigation stemmed from the discovery of
arms and drugs in 1987 on a Lebanese ship off Italy's Adriatic
coast. The ship, from Beirut, carried heroin, hashish, an anti-tank
bazooka, Soviet grenade-launcher and other arms, authorities said.
   Police initially linked the shipment to alleged smuggling of arms
between Italy and the Middle East, including clandestine delivery of
mines to Iran. Several Italian industrialists and arms manufacturers
were arrested, but they were freed later and the charges dropped.
   On Monday, officials said documents seized in connection with the
ship _ including false certificates of a dummy ``Canadian Credit
Bank'' of Detroit _ put them on the trail of the Mafia-terrorist
operation.
   The gang allegedly plotted to deliver French Mirage jets to
Guinea-Bissau, acting as middlemen in return for kickbacks.
   An Italian representative of the African country and an official
of the French manufacturer, Dassault-Breguet, identified only as Mr.
Covanschi, also were said to be involved. Whether planes were
delivered was not clear.
</TEXT>
