<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Somalia     01-31 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Somalia,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Somali Leader Meets with US Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somali Prime Minister Mohamed Ali Samater said
Tuesday his government has taken a series of steps designed to
achieve peace and prosperity internally and to improve relations
with its neighbors.
   Samater spoke in an interview at the outset of a visit partly
aimed at refuting allegations that Somalia has engaged in widespread
human rights abuses while attempting to put down an insurrection in
the northern part of the country.
   The United States has imposed sharp cutbacks in aid to Somalia as
has the United Nations and Great Britain. An Australian-based aid
agency pulled out of Somalia three weeks ago, citing political
repression.
   But Samater said, ``Our position is that we have not committed
human rights abuses.''
   Samater's visit is part of a diplomatic offensive the Somali
government has initiated in an effort to bolser its international
image. He will meet with Assistant Secretary of State Chester
Crocker on Wednesday and also plans consultations on Capitol Hill.
   As evidence of Somalia's new approach, Samatar said all political
prisoners, numbering between 200 and 250, are being released and
that steps have been taken to ensure that persons detained on
suspicion of criminal conduct have a prompt judicial proceeding.
   He also said that state controls over the economy are being eased
in order to revitalize the country's productive capacity. In
addition, he said the government is willing to move toward a
political settlement with the northern-based insurgency.
   Somalia has enjoyed close political and military ties with the
United States for years but many in Congress were appalled last year
over a reported dramatic increase in human rights abuses. Under
congressional pressure, the administration placed a hold on about
$55 million in economic assistance.
   Holly Burkhalter, who monitors the rights situation in Somalia in
her role as associate director of Human Rights Watch, a private
group, disputed Samatar's account about the situation in Somalia.
   ``It's very, very serious indeed,'' she said. ``The fact that
nearly half a million Somalians left their country for the dubious
privilege of refuge in Ethiopia says more than anything else about
human rights conditions in Somalia.''
   In addition, the United Nations last month decided to withhold
food aid from an estimated 400,000 Ethiopian refugees in Somalia,
contending that Somalian authorities were using the Ethiopians for
military activities. A U.S. official said the U.N. finding had been
corroborated in interviews with eyewitnesses.
   But Samatar said the U.N.'s own figures show that 77 per cent of
the Ethiopian refugees are women or children and that the rest are
too aged to fight.
   ``Only a small percentage is able bodied,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
