<FIRST>r w AM-UMW-Pittston 1stLd-Writethru a0638 01-31 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Pittston, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners' Union Drops Strike Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new grafs 5-6, bgng ``Pittston thanked,'' with Pittston
reax; subs pvs graf 8, which began ``Crestar spokesman,'' with new graf
10, also bgng ``Crestar spokesman,'' with bank reax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers, complying Tuesday with
a request by governors in three coal-producing states, dropped a
strike deadline and said its 1,700 workers at Pittston Coal Group
mines would continue working without a contract.
   At the same time, the union expanded its effort to pressure
Pittston through protests and other actions aimed at the company's
business partners, announcing a boycott of Virginia-based Crestar
Financial Corp. and its banks.
   Despite the decision not to strike at midnight Tuesday, union
president Richard L. Trumka had harsh words for Pittston management
and said he was ``not overly optimistic'' an agreement would be
reached in the next 30 to 60 days, the extension period requested by
the governors of Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky.
   Trumka accused Pittston officials of failing to bargain seriously
and of trying to break the union.
   Pittston thanked the union for its action and, meeting a
longstanding UMW request, said its chief executive officer, Paul
Douglas, would accept Trumka's invitation for a face-to-face
meeting. UMW officials have sought the meeting because they contend
company negotiators do not have the power to make concessions.
   Pittston Coal Group President Michael Odom suggested the two
sides ask the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service to
intervene in the talks and promised the company would ``exert every
effort to assure that the time during the cooling off period is
utilized effectively to achieve a settlement.''
   Govs. Gaston Caperton of West Virginia and Wallace Wilkinson of
Kentucky hailed the decision to postpone a strike and urged both
sides to reach agreement on a contract. Virginia Gov. Gerald
Baliles, through a spokeswoman, expressed similar sentiments.
   Trumka said Crestar's decision to give Pittston a loan in
December 1987 amounted to helping the company build a strike fund.
The union's contract expired less than two months later and the
miners have been working without a contract since then.
   Union action against the bank, Trumka said, began with the
withdrawal of $29.7 million _ $23 million by the Bakery and
Confectionary Union and Industry International Pension Fund and $6.7
million by the UMW.
   Crestar spokesman Neil Cotiaux said the bank regretted the union
action and considered it to be unfair. ``Crestar has no dispute with
union or its members,'' Cotiaux said in a statement. ``Our
participation in the credit arrangement with Pittston is an
extension of previous credit arrangements.''
   Pittston Coal Group, based in Lebanon, Va., is a subsidiary of
The Pittston Co. of Greenwich, Conn. Pittson last February refused
to sign a wage agreement the miners union negotiated with other
major eastern coal producers.
   Over the past week, the company has been considering a union
offer made a week ago in response to an offer Pittston made in
November. Pension and health benefits are the major sticking points
in the talks, union officials said.
   Pittston has said it planned to operate its mines in the event of
the strike and possibly would hire permanent replacements.
</TEXT>
