<FIRST>r i AM-FetusEarrings     01-31 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fetus Earrings,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Hears Case on Earrings Made of Human Fetuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury at the Old Bailey criminal court will decide
whether earrings made of human fetuses are art or obscenity.
   Exhibit One, in a glass case, is a mannequin's head with a black
curly wig, a scarf and a pair of human fetuses, of three to four
months' gestation and freeze-dried, attached to its ears.
   Police seized the head Dec. 1, 1987, opening day of an exhibition
of 40 items at the Young Unknowns art gallery in Waterloo, south
London. The show was called In Animal.
   Canadian sculptor Richard Gibson, 36, the creator, and gallery
owner Peter Sylveire, 43, were charged with outraging public decency
and causing a nuisance.
   They pleaded innocent, and this week a jury of 10 women and two
men began listening to lawyers argue whether the work is art or
outrage.
   Geoffrey Robertson, who represents Sylveire and sees the case as
an important test of obscenity laws, said in court Monday one
purpose of art is ``to shock and jolt the public from its
complacency.''
   He said the fetal sculpture could be seen as demonstrating that
``women wear abortions as lightly as they wear their earrings.''
   Prosecutor Michael Worsley said Tuesday the issue was not
artistic merit or lack of it, but whether the earrings would shock,
disgust or revolt a decent member of the public.
   He declared the fetuses, which were obtained from a pathology
lecturer, to be an outrage to public decency.
   Sylveire was said to have told a journalist at the gallery he did
not think the earrings were ``any more immoral than sculptors using
human hair.''
   Gibson said he found the police reaction ``over the top'' _ too
extreme.
   Worsley told the jury Gibson ``saw nothing wrong with his work,
but said that some people might have a moral objection to it.''
   Britain legalized abortion in 1967, and the law allows abortions
up to the 28th week of pregnancy.
</TEXT>
