<SECOND>AM-Peru,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Police Commander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas shot a police commander to
death as he walked on a dark street in an Andes mining town,
officials reported Tuesday.
   Six gunmen killed Cesar Chavez Vila on Monday night while he was
vacationing in Cerro de Pasco, a mining town 120 miles northwest of
Huancayo, police said.
   Chavez Vila commanded the national police detachment in Huancayo,
the Junin state capital and an important trading center for the
central Andes. It is 140 miles east of Lima.
   Guerrillas of the Shining Path movement have increased attacks in
the area recently. Officials say the rebels want to cause economic
chaos by disrupting mine production and delivery of agricultural
products from the central Andes to Lima.
   More than 12,000 people have been killed in political violence,
most of them peasants in the Andes, since the Shining Path began its
guerrilla campaign in 1980.
