<FIRST>r w AM-US-SaudiArms     01-31 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Saudi Arms,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Tells Of Dialogue With Saudis For Jet Fighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has told Congress it
may seek permission to sell more than 100 F@A-18 fighter jets to
Saudi Arabia if the Saudis want the planes, sources said Tuesday.
   The possibility was raised in a cover letter to a classified list
of proposed foreign arms sales submitted to the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee last month.
   The annual list details possible U.S. arms sales. For each
large-scale sale, Capitol Hill must be notified and Congress then
has 60 days to block the deal.
   The letter left open the possibility the administration will
notify Congress during the coming year of its intent to sell Saudi
Arabia the F-18s, but the letter doesn't commit the United States to
such a sale.
   The list was compiled by the Reagan White House and could be
changed by the new administration.
   The list includes the sale to Saudi Arabia of M1-A tanks and
multiple rocket launchers. Most of those items are not expected to
be controversial, said the sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Saudi Arabia has told the United States it is still shopping
around Europe for alternatives to the F-18, such as the French
Mirage 2000 or a fighter jet produced by a joint British-French
venture, the sources said.
   The Saudi decision may only come next year, once all the European
models are available, they said. The Saudis are not in a rush to
make the decision because the new jets are designed as replacement
for its current U.S. fleet of F-5s and F-15s, which is good at least
until 1995.
   While the Europeans are offering the Saudis better financial
terms than the United States, the Saudis are still attracted by the
quality of U.S. aircraft, which have been the mainstay of their
arsenal, and the pilot training program offered by the United
States, the sources said.
   The Saudis are also seeking to avoid an embarrassing fight with
Congress over such a sale, which many on Capitol Hill oppose.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., last month put the administration
on notice he would try to block an F-18 sale on the grounds it
endangers Israel. The two nations are technically still in a state
of war.
   The Reagan and Bush administrations have both argued that
persistent congressional rejections of such aircraft sales have
driven the Saudis to look elsewhere, at the expense of U.S.
businesses and foreign policy interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
