<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Troops     01-31 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Troops,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Detail Troop Withdrawal From Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will withdraw 10,000
soldiers in 22 units from Hungary by the end of next year, Soviet
military officers told reporters Tuesday.
   A total of 50,000 troops will be withdrawn from Hungary,
Czechoslovakia and East Germany under a plan announced by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   In Hungary, the units include a full tank division, a training
tank regiment, an airborne assault battalion, a fighter aircraft
group and a chemical defense battalion, the Soviet officers said.
   Col. Gen. Matvei Burlakov, commander of the Soviet southern army
group stationed in Hungary, said the withdrawal would reduce the
strength of the southern army group by 10,000 troops, including
2,400 officers. Soviet troop strength in Hungary now is 62,000.
   Burlakov said the troops will be withdrawn from the Austrian
border.
   More than 2,200 artillery pieces and trench mortars, 450 tanks
and more than 3,000 motor vehicles will be withdrawn in stages
beginning in May or June, he said.
   Eleven Soviet garrisons will be disbanded and the facilities
handed over to the Hungarians, including 900 apartments and 19
barracks, he said.
</TEXT>
