<FIRST>r w AM-AronsonAppointment     01-31 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aronson Appointment,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aronson Gets State Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bernard Aronson has been chosen by
Secretary of State James A. Baker III for the key post of assistnat
secretary for inter-American affairs, congressional sources said
Tuesday.
   A Democratic Senate source, who spoke only on condition of
anonymity, said Aronson was picked because he is a moderate who can
appeal to both Democrats and Republicans on divisive Central
American policies, particularly Nicaragua.
   But the appointment may provoke controversy among some
congressional liberals because Aronson once helped lobby Congress on
behalf of a military aid package for the Contra rebels fighting
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   ``I think it's more than just a trial balloon,'' said Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum, R-Kan., a member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee.
   Aronson emerged from a group that included at least two other
contenders to succeed Elliott Abrams in the job. Abrams became the
lightning rod for the Reagan admistration's Nicaragua policy, the
longest-running dispute with Congress of Reagan's presidency.
   Baker had reportedly also been considering Robert C. Helander, a
New York attorney, and Deane R. Hinton, U.S. ambassador to Costa
Rica, but both were objectionable to conservatives who saw them as
not sufficiently devoted to the Contras.
   Aronson had met in recent days with both House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, and paid courtesy calls to other congressional leaders on
Tuesday.
   Aronson, a former speechwriter for Walter F. Mondale, now is a
member of a Council on Foreign Relations study group on Central
America.
   When the Reagan administration was trying to sell a Contra aid
package on Capitol Hill in 1986, Aronson joined a group of other
liberals to help and wrote a speech for Reagan that admitted Contra
human rights violations and sought to condition military aid for the
rebels on improving their human rights record.
   ``I'm cautiously optimistic that we'll be able to work
together,'' said Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., who visited with
Aronson and said the appointee spoke in support of the regional
peace plan drawn up by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias.
</TEXT>
