<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-SovietSubs     01-31 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Soviet Subs,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Deny Subs Intrude In Swedish Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Embassy on Tuesday denied
allegations by Sweden's naval chief that Soviet submarines continue
to intrude into Swedish waters.
   Embassy spokesman Anatoly Novikov was quoted by Swedish radio as
saying Soviet captains ``have been ordered not to come any closer to
Swedish territorial waters than 30 kilometers,'' about 19 miles.
   Sweden says it has evidence of about 40 violations of its waters
a year, but efforts to catch an intruder or force a sub to the
surface have failed.
   Admiral Bengt Schuback charged Monday that Soviet submarines from
secret Baltic bases keep violating Swedish waters.
   ``They can't come from anywhere but hidden bases in the Baltic,
and we know Western countries have no such bases,'' he said at a
military seminar.
   But his superior, Torsten Engberg, chief of the defense staff,
told the seminar that ``there is not enough evidence to identify any
nationality.''
   Last week the navy said it ``had indications'' that a submarine
had penetrated waters outside Stockholm. ``Indications'' usually
refer to tracks on the seabed left by mini-subs, sightings of a
periscope by fishermen or sonar signals.
   Sweden has not officially accused any nation of violations since
1983, when the government protested Soviet incursions to Moscow. Two
years earlier a Soviet submarine ran aground a naval base in
southern Sweden.
</TEXT>
