<FIRST>r a AM-WayneCustody     01-31 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wayne Custody,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Actor's Daughter Denied Custody Of Her Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Witnesses said a daughter of actor John
Wayne is a loving but emotionally immature parent, so a judge plans
to award custody of the late actor's 1-year-old granddaughter to the
girl's father.
   Orange County Superior Court Judge Ronald E. Owen announced his
tentative ruling in a memorandum issued Monday.
   Owen said Aissa Wayne, 32, is unfit for custody of Anastasia
Wayne.
   ``The various mental-health professionals that testified seemed
to have one common thread running through their testimony,'' Owen
said in his ruling. ``That is, that the mother, although loving,
lacks familiarity with the child, is emotionally immature and lacks
direction herself.''
   The judge said he would grant custody of Anastasia to Dr. Thomas
A. Gionis, a Pomona orthopedic surgeon, while allowing Ms. Wayne to
visit every other weekend beginning Feb. 10.
   ``I've spoken to Aissa several times already,'' Gionis said.
``I'm sure we will always remain close for the mutual benefit of the
child.''
   Ms. Wayne shares custody of two children by a previous marriage.
   Gionis' attorney, George L. Stephan, called private
investigators, psychologists and family counselors to testify during
a lengthy hearing to show that Ms. Wayne spent little time with
Anastasia when the girl was home for visits, often leaving the child
to the care of housekeepers.
   In an unrelated development, the spacious Newport Beach estate
where Ms. Wayne and a friend, financier Roger Luby, 52, were bound
and pistol whipped by two intruders last October has been put on the
auction block to pay off the mortgage. The attackers were never
caught.
   The minimum bid on Luby's 7,000-square-foot, six-bedroom house
must be nearly $1.2 million cash in order to pay off the mortgage,
according to a notice of trustee sale filed Jan. 23.
</TEXT>
