<FIRST>r a AM-DeathAppeals     01-31 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Death Appeals,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Double Execution Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted killer Ian Lightbourne got a
stay of execution Tuesday, less than 15 hours before he was to die
in the electric chair. A second convicted killer also slated for
execution Wednesday was saved by an earlier stay, and officials were
unsuccessful in getting that ban lifted.
   The state Supreme Court voted to block indefinitely Lightbourne's
execution scheduled for 7 a.m. Wednesday at Florida State Prison
near Starke. Earlier Tuesday, Lightbourne lost an appeal in circuit
court in Ocala.
   Raymond Robert Clark got a stay last week from his scheduled
execution Wednesday. Had both killers gone to the chair, it would
have been the first double execution in Florida in nearly 25 years.
   State Attorney General Bob Butterworth asked the U.S. Supreme
Court to allow Clark's execution to proceed by vacating the stay
granted by the U.S. 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. Clark
was under his fourth death warrant.
   By the end of business Tuesday, however, Carolyn Snurkowski,
chief of death penalty appeals for Butterworth, said she didn't
expect a ruling before Wednesday morning. The warrant authorizing
Clark's execution doesn't expire until Feb. 7.
   The last execution in Florida was Jan. 24 when confessed serial
killer Ted Bundy was put to death for the 1978 kidnap-murder of a
Lake City schoolgirl.
   The last double execution was May 12, 1964, when Sie Dawson and
Emmett Blake died 28 minutes apart.
   Lightbourne, 29, under his second death warrant, was sentenced
for the 1981 murder of Nancy A. O'Farrell, 41, near Ocala.
   Clark, 47, was convicted of the 1977 murder of St. Petersburg
businessman David Drake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
