<FIRST>r a AM-Steinberg     01-31 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Will Appeal Manslaughter Conviction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Steinberg Overview, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for convicted child killer Joel
Steinberg said Tuesday he will appeal his client's first-degree
manslaughter conviction on the ground the judge allowed evidence
that inflamed and prejudiced the jury.
   Attorney Ira London said state Supreme Court Justice Harold
Rothwax prejudiced the case by letting the jury see a videotape of a
seriously beaten Hedda Nussbaum, the defendant's former live-in
companion, and by his instructions to the jury on intent.
   The lawyer objected to Rothwax's statement at a pretrial bail
application that second-degree murder defendant Steinberg was
``probably guilty, probably would be found guilty and probably would
be sentenced to life in prison.''
   ``I think that statement the judge made is something he may
regret in view of the appellate issues we are going to raise in the
case and we will include that,'' London said.
   Steinberg, 47, was convicted of first-degree manslaughter Monday
in the death of Lisa, the 6 year old he obtained at birth and raised
but never legally adopted.
   The jury found Steinberg guilty after eight days of deliberations
following a 12-week trial. Steinberg faces up to 25 years in prison.
   ``There is no question in my mind from the length of the
deliberations and from talking to the jurors ... there is no
question that Joel got a fair shake from the jurors,'' London said.
But ``it is a serious issue whether Joel got a fair trial because of
the judge's rulings.''
   London said the judge hurt Steinberg unfairly when he refused to
answer ``no'' to the jurors' question about whether they should
infer intent on the basis of the victim's injuries even though they
had been unable to find intent.
   ``We felt a simple one-word answer would have answered the
question,'' the lawyer said. He noted that the jury came in a short
time later.
   ``He chose not to say `no,' and he chose to go into some long
explanation which later, according to what the jury has told us, led
to the conviction on manslaughter in the first degree,'' London said.
   And allowing the jury to see the tape of Ms. Nussbaum's injuries
inflicted by Steinberg ``was a prejudice that I don't know any
criminal defendant could recover from.''
</TEXT>
