<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Chess     01-31 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Chess,0365</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Yusupov And Spraggett Draw; Move To Sudden-Death Finish ^By DAVID
GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artur Yusupov of the Soviet Union and Kevin
Spraggett of Canada drew the seventh game in the World Chess
Championship Candidates quarterfinal on Tuesday, leaving the match
to be decided in a sudden-death finish.
   The 27-move draw left the match score tied 3.5 points apiece. The
victor of the eighth game, scheduled for Thursday, will win the
contest and advance to the semifinal stage.
   In the event of a draw, a series of sudden-death tiebreakers at
increasingly high speeds on Saturday will decide the contest.
   Canadian observers are hoping Spraggett, a 34-year-old from
Montreal who will play with the advantage of white on Thursday, will
defeat the pre-match favorite and become the first North American
since Bobby Fischer to reach the semifinals.
   The winner of the Candidates, a series of knockout matches, will
challenge world champion Garri Kasparov for his title.
   In the seventh game, Yusupov, playing white, gained a clear edge
from the opening and began to build a dangerous initiative, experts
said.
   But Yusupov, a 28-year old Muscovite, chose a safe but passive
continuation on his 21st move that enabled Spraggett to neutralize
white's advantage.
   Both players used up most of their allotted time in their early
stages and left themselves only half an hour to ponder 20 moves.
Each player has two hours in which to mkae their first 40 moves.
   Canadian observers said Yusupov appeared nervous in the latter
stages of the game.
   ``Spraggett is in good physical shape and his nerves will be good
if it comes down to a blitz finish,'' said Canadian International
Master Jean Hebert. British Grandmaster Jonathan Speelman is already
through to the semifinal stage of the Candidates.
   Former world champion Anatoly Karpov of the Soviet Union leads
Iceland's Johann Hjartarson by 1.5-0.5 in the third quarterfinal in
Seattle, Wash.
   The first game of the remaining match, between Dutch Grandmaster
Jan Timman and Lajos Portisch of Hungary in Antwerp, Belgium, was
adjourned Tuesday after 61 moves.
</TEXT>
