<FIRST>r a AM-FirefightersInjured 1stLd-Writethru a0731 01-31 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Firefighters Injured, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0731,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Firefighters Sent to Hospital After Mattress Fire `Explosion'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The most...', to UPDATE firefighter out of surgery
and condition.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion triggered by a mattress fire ripped
through a fourth-floor apartment Tuesday, propelling three
firefighters out windows and injuring eight, officials said.
   ``It's called a flash-back,'' said Fire Department spokesman
Frank Szwedo explained. ``It has the same properties as an
explosion.''
   The firefighters were extinguishing what had started as a
mattress fire when oxygen reached the smoldering material, causing a
blast with such force that it apparently sent the firefighters out
the windows, Szwedo said.
   The most severe injury was sustained by Joseph Gaska, 39, a
firefighter who fell four stories, officials said. Gaska underwent
surgery for abdominal injuries and was in serious condition with
second-degree burns, said Michael Reese Hospital nursing superviser
Joyce Gaines.
   No residents of the South Side apartment building were reported
injured, Szwedo said.
   Five firefighters suffered burns to the head or neck areas,
another had multiple fractures and another had a broken ankle and
possible back injuries, Szwedo said.
</TEXT>
