<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   01-31 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0695,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business, Opposition Leaders Unhappy With Government's Economic Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS lead to CORRECT to 1989; ADDS 4 grafs too UPDATE with La
Prensa comment and Ortega reported seeking Venezuelan aid.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders and businessmen said
Tuesday they were puzzled and dissatisfied with the leftist
Sandinista government's austerity plan for 1989 and will not support
it.
   President Daniel Ortega's speech outlining the inflation-fighting
plan ``is rather nebulous,'' said Ramiro Gurdian, president of the
Union of Nicaraguan Agricultural Producers and vice president of the
Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate, an opposition coalition.
   ``He (Ortega) did not mention he had the backing of the producers
because he simply doesn't have it,'' Gurdian said in an interview.
   Ortega, in a speech before the National Assembly on Monday,
outlined a 1989 economic plan that includes budget cuts of more than
40 percent, a decrease in capital investments and restricted credit.
   The budgetary cuts will mean laying off about 35,000 government
workers, Ortega was quoted as saying in an interview published
Monday in the Venezuelan newspaper El Nacional.
   The plan's aim is to curb rampant inflation, which reached 20,000
percent last year and is projected to run at 300 percent a month
through May.
   It also seeks to increase productivity in this Central American
country, Ortega said exports plummeted from $450 million in 1980 _ a
year after the Sandinistas took power _ to $267 million in 1988.
   The Sandinistas have been meeting with labor groups and
businessmen to seek their support for the plan, which Ortega said
would cause an economic downturn initially.
   ``The measures have an element of a recessive character,'' Ortega
said in his speech. ``This is inevitable, although temporary.''
   The president said idle workers could be absorbed into
agriculture, including 10,000 needed in coffee harvesting.
   Gurdian said the coffee harvest was about to end and doubted an
office worker could be very effective as a field hand.
   ``Maybe they can be employed for a month, but when it's over,
then what? What are you going to do with those people?'' Gurdian
said.
   Ortega said his government is ``trying to apply a capitalist
policy different from the other countries which have been held up to
us as models.'' But he added that ``we as Sandinistas, Marxists,
Marxist-Leninists'' are trying to develop socialism within
Nicaragua's reality as a Central American country.
   ``I've been trying to find messages of political economy, and I
must confess that I'm lost,'' said Enrique Bolanos, a cotton grower
and former president of the Superior Council of Private Enterprise.
   ``He's cutting investments nearly to zero, and if there's no
investment, there's no growth; if there's no growth, there are no
new jobs,'' Bolanos said. Ortega also said production costs will be
strictly controlled because they ``cannot be higher than in the
Central American markets.''
   Gurdian and Bolanos blamed high production costs on the state,
which sets the price of raw materials and buys products from growers
at a set price.
   ``They (government) tell you, `Here's the raw materials, here's
your tractor and these are going to be your profits,''' Gurdian said
angrily. ``I am not going to work so the state can tell me how much
I'm going to earn. I work to earn money.''
   The Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate includes four political
parties, three labor unions and the Superior Council of Private
Enterprise.
   The opposition newspaper La Prensa said Ortega's speech left
Nicaraguans disillusioned, and it called for reforms that would let
them elect a new government ``that is more efficient and
advantageous for the people.''
   Meanwhile, Venevision, a private television station in Caracas,
Venezuela, said Ortega has asked Venezuela for economic aid.
   Ortega met with Venezuelan President-elect Carlos Andres Perez
after his arrival in Caracas for Perez' inauguration, scheduled for
Thursday.
   Venezuela and Mexico provide cheap oil to some Caribbean and
Central American nations under the San Jose Accord, begun in 1975 by
Perez during his first presidency. But since 1982, Venezuela stopped
providing oil to Nicaragua because Managua did not pay its bills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
