<SECOND>AM-Hospital Sickout, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0710,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Halts Sickout After National Guard Called In</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with governor threatening to fire absent
workers. INSERTS one graf after 6th graf, `Gov. Edward...', with governor's
threat. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `We're kind...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRANSTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unionized attendants at a state-run
hospital temporarily halted their sickout Tuesday after they were
threatened with dismissal and National Guard troops were called in
to feed, wash, and dress patients.
   Eighty of the 91 workers scheduled to work the 3 p.m. shift
showed up, and the Guard was sent home, said hospital administrator
James Benedict.
   The union and the state will negotiate their disputes over
staffing, scheduling and overtime during a two-week cooling-off
period, said Robert K. Vincent, a governor's aide who met with union
officials for 1{ hours.
   ``If they can't agree, they'll shake hands and agree to disagree,
but they'll address that disagreement through the normal procedure''
of grievances and arbitration, Vincent said.
   Union officials were not at the union hall and did not return
telephone calls seeking comment.
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete called out the Guard to fill in for absent
workers after talks collapsed Monday between Local 1350 of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees and
Thomas D. Romeo, director of the state Department of Mental Health,
Retardation and Hospitals.
   Vincent said DiPrete had warned the workers that any who did not
show up for Tuesday's third shift, beginning at 11 p.m., and could
not prove they were ill would risk being fired.
   ``We're kind of out of our element, but we seem to be doing OK,''
said Sgt. Dean Mansfield, one of about 60 Guardsmen who rolled up
the sleeves of their fatigues and went to work Tuesday morning.
   The state-run hospital provides long-term care to 425 patients,
about 75 percent of whom are elderly.
   Romeo, under heavy pressure from DiPrete to cut overtime costs,
ordered changes in the hospital work-schedules that angered the
union.
   The changes will remain in place during the cooling-off period,
Vincent said. He said the hospital's overtime budget has been
$55,000 for each two-week pay period, but actual spending has been
closer to $95,000. The changes are aimed at bringing that figure
down to $85,000 per two weeks, Vincent said.
   Eighty-five of the 106 workers scheduled for Tuesday's first
shift reported for work, said Joan M. Wilkicki, the hospital's
administrative coordinator.
   The absentee rate has varied greatly from shift to shift. On
Monday, most of the first shift reported for work but well over half
of the second-shift workers called in sick.
   The Guard pitched in to perform ``non-skilled'' care, such as
feeding, washing and dressing patients and changing their linens,
under the direction of medical staff, said Capt. John Loughlin II,
the Guard's public information officer.
</TEXT>
