<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-BoatSinking     01-31 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Boat Sinking,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Says Boat in New Year's Eve Sinking Was Overcrowded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The navy on Tuesday reversed its
position and said the tourist boat that sank on New Year's Eve,
killing 55 people, was overcrowded and not fit to venture into sea
waters.
   A two-week examination of the boat, which was hauled from the sea
floor in mid-January, showed the Bateau Mouche should have carried
not more than 62 when it capsized and sank with at least 150
revelers aboard, a navy report said.
   The report said the popular sightseeing craft was badly
maintained, had a waterline above the basement portholes, had a
second-floor addition that affected the boat's stability and was
full of loose, heavy tables and chairs.
   The boat sank while on a midnight excursion to watch fireworks
off Copacabana beach.
   Days later, the Navy Ministry released a report that declared the
boat was fit for 153 people and seaworthy, according to port
authority guards.
   But the navy and police investigating criminal responsibility in
the sinking have been under constant pressure from civic groups
comprised mostly of friends and relatives of victims.
   The navy said Tuesday it would open an investigation to determine
why naval engineers approved the boat for large tourist excursions.
   The navy said it also would investigate why port authority guards
allowed the midnight sail despite obvious overcrowding and severe
rocking of the boat in high waves.
   The owners of the boat and the tourist agency that organized the
excursion were imprisoned briefly last week and released on bail.
Police have not yet determined criminal responsibility.
</TEXT>
