<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq     01-31 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Expects Foreign Ministers of Iran and Iraq In New York Next
Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq are
expected to visit New York next week when the Security Council
debates the peacekeeping force separating their armies, a U.N.
spokesman said Tuesday.
   The presence of both foreign ministers would give
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar a chance to discuss ways
of breaking the stalemated Iran-Iraq peace talks.
   Negotiations on ending the eight-year war deadlocked immediately
after they began Aug. 25.
   U.N. officials hope Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz and his
Iranian counterpart, Ali Akbar Velayati, will be present when the
Security Council considers extending for six months the mandate of
the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group on Feb. 8, said U.N.
spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   A diplomatic source close to the talks said the foreign ministers
were informally invited to New York.
   The foreign ministers have not announced whether they will attend
next week's council session.
   Perez de Cuellar received a briefing Tuesday from his special
representative to the peace talks, Swedish U.N. Ambassador Jan K.
Eliasson, who returned from visiting Baghdad and Tehran during the
last week.
   Eliasson's talks with senior Iranian and Iraqi officials produced
no sign of progress on the major stumbling blocks in the peace talks
_ freedom of navigation in the Persian Gulf or the Shatt-al-Arab
waterway; the exchange of 100,000 prisoners of war; or withdrawal of
military forces to the border.
