<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     01-31 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>13 Killed; Gov't Assigns Bodyguards, Invites Foreign Monitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 13 more people were killed in
pre-election violence, officials said Tuesday. The government
assigned armed bodyguards to candidates but took steps to control
their movements.
   The government also invited foreign groups to monitor the Feb. 15
parliamentary election.
   Eleven of the latest slayings were blamed on Sinhalese radicals
of the People's Liberation Front and occurred in southern and
central Sri Lanka late Monday and Tuesday, a police officer said on
condition of anonymity.
   Indian troops stationed in Sri Lanka to enforce an
Indian-brokered Tamil peace accord on Tuesday shot and killed two
people believed to be members of the most powerful of the Tamil
separatist group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam in northern
Sri Lanka, police said.
   A senior police officer, also speaking privately, said the
government has assigned 8,376 bodyguards _ six to a candidate.
   ``In addition to the politicians being issued two pistols, one
for himself and the other for his most trusted bodyguard, police
have issued four repeater shotguns'' for each candidate, the officer
said.
   Political violence before the election prompted the government to
order candidates to keep their gun-toting bodyguards off the streets
after sundown, a senior police officer said Tuesday.
   Ten candidates have been slain in the past 3{ weeks.
   The governing United National Party, headed by President
Ranasinghe Premadasa, blames the Sinhalese front and opposition
parties for most of the political killings.
   The biggest opposition group, former Prime Minister Sirimavo
Bandaranaike's Sri Lanka Freedom Party, and other opposition groups
say the political assassinations were carried out by bodyguards and
other gunmen working for members of the United National Party.
   Police statistics say 600 people were killed in political
violence in January, but a Western diplomat said he thought the
figure was too high. The diplomat, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, declined to say what he thought the actual toll might be.
   The government on Tuesday said it was inviting international
groups to monitor the election in which nine political parties and
10 independent groups are fielding 1,396 candidates for the
225-member Parliament.
   The government said the People's Liberation Front killed 800
people prior to January. Most of the victims were government
officials, policemen or supporters of the United National Party.
   The front vowed to kill anyone who supported the government's
attempts to end an insurrection by members of the Tamil ethnic
minority. The front said a July 1987 peace accord offered too many
concessions to the Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people.
   Tamil guerrillas have been waging a guerrilla war and terrorist
campaign since 1983 in their quest for a separate homeland, which
they say is needed to combat what they call discrimination by the
Sinahlese majority.
   More than 8,500 people, including at least 600 Indian
peacekeeping soldiers, have died in the Tamil revolt. Most of the
victims were Sinhalese civilians massacred in their villages or
ambushed on buses and trains.
   The Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population, dominate
the government and the military.
</TEXT>
