<SECOND>AM-People-Sadler, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0792,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Sadler Acted Confused</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with family agreeing to independent
guardian. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `The responses...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The feuding family of brain-damaged
singer-composer Barry Sadler has agreed to allow a judge to name an
independent guardian to handle his affairs, another judge said
Tuesday evening.
   Cuyahoga County Probate Judge John J. Donnelly said Sadler's
family ``has gotten together'' and agreed to let Probate Court Judge
James Everett, in Nashville, Tenn., name an independent guardian.
   Under the agreement, the guardian must consult with family
members before making major decisions for Sadler, said Donnelly, who
said relatives indicated a preference for naming as guardian a
Vietnam veteran like Sadler.
   Sadler's mother, Bebe, and son, Thor, 24, had made competing
appeals to be named guardian for Sadler, who was interviewed Monday
night by Donnelly at Southwest General Hospital in suburban
Middleburg Heights.
   ``The responses were confusing,'' said Donnelly. Sadler
repeatedly referred to this year as 1980 even after being told the
correct date, the judge said.
   Sadler, 48, could name only two of his three children, Donnelly
said.
   Sadler is best known for his ``Ballad of the Green Berets,''
which was a hit in 1965. He reportedly lost 30 percent of his brain
when he was wounded by gunfire last fall in Guatamala City, where he
had lived for five years.
   The nature of the attack has never been disclosed.
   A psychiatrist and psychologist, both of whom interviewed Sadler
at the hospital, testified Tuesday at the guardianship hearing and
were split on whether he was mentally competent.
   Gintautas Z. Sabataitis, a psychologist from Parma Heights, said
Sadler was competent but ``severely limited'' in his abilities and
needed a guardian to look after his affairs.
   Joel S. Steinberg, a Lyndhurst psychiatrist, said he had not
determined whether Sadler was competent.
   ``I didn't reach a conclusion about that,'' he said. ``I had to
leave it in the air.''
   Steinberg said Sadler had suffered ``profound neurological loss''
but said he was surprised by Sadler's capacities.
   Sadler's mother, who moved to Cleveland from Denver to be close
to her son, filed for guardianship after Thor Sadler was appointed
guardian for his father by a judge in Nashville.
   Sadler was treated there for two months before coming to the
Cleveland Veterans Administration hospital Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
