<FIRST>r a AM-DGAAwards     01-31 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DGA Awards,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Directors' Guild Unveils Nominations For Achievement Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Directors Guild of America on Monday
announced its nominations for the prestigious DGA achievement award,
marking the five directors as favorites for Academy Awards in March.
   Alan Parker, who brought the controversial civil rights film
``Mississippi Burning'' to the screen, was one of the five nominated
for outstanding directorial achievement in 1988.
   Also named were Charles Crichton, director of the crime-caper
comedy ``A Fish Called Wanda''; Barry Levinson, who guided the
autism film ``Rain Man''; Robert Zemeckis, the creative force behind
the animated, live action hit ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit''; and Mike
Nichols, director of the corporate comedy ``Working Girl.''
   Only three times in motion picture history has the DGA award
winner failed to go on to win the Academy Award for best director.
   In 1985, Steven Spielberg won the DGA honor for ``The Color
Purple'' but Sydney Pollack took the Academy Award for ``Out of
Africa.'' The two other non-repeaters were Francis Ford Coppola in
1972 when his ``Godfather'' lost to ``Cabaret'' and Anthony Harvey
in 1968 when ``The Lion in Winter'' lost to ``Oliver.''
   Clint Eastwood, who won a Golden Globe for best director
Saturday, wasn't among the nominees, who are chosen by a vote of
their peers. But ``Working Girl,'' which won four Golden Globes, and
``Rain Man,'' winner of two, both are in the running.
   ``I was hoping Clint Eastwood would be nominated this year, but
(his film ``Bird'') wasn't,'' said Spielberg, who announced the
nominations at a news conference at the DGA headquarters. ``I
thought `Bird' was an outstanding directorial accomplishment,'' he
said.
   The DGA winner will be announced March 11 at the 41st annual DGA
awards dinner-dance, to be held concurrently in Los Angeles and New
York.
   All 9,000 members of the DGA were eligible to vote on the
nominations, and all are eligible now to vote for the winner. The
guild includes film and television directors and their assistants.
</TEXT>
