<FIRST>u w AM-US-Japan 2ndld-writethru a0781 01-31 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan, 2nd ld-writethru, a0781,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds new last graf with Mexican ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush intends to nominate Michael H.
Armacost, currently Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs,
as the new U.S. ambassador to Japan, a U.S. official said Tuesday.
   Armacost is the highest-ranking career foregin service officer at
the State Department. He succeeds former Sen. Mike Mansfield, who
has retired.
   Armacost's pending nomination was confirmed by U.S. sources who
declined to named.
   He is a former U.S. ambassador to the Philippines and is also the
ranking Asian specialist on the National Security Council staff.
   Bush is due to visit Japan for the Feb. 24 funeral of Emperor
Hirohito. U.S. relations with Tokyo are at a crucial stage, with
pressure building in Congress to have the Japanese increase their
contribution to the country's defense.
   Another problem in the relationship is the U.S. trade deficit of
$57 billion caused by an influx of Japanese products.
   But Mansfield, announcing his retirement late last year, said he
was leaving with ``our heads high'' because the deficit had been
narrowed as a result of hard bargaining to open Japanese markets and
efforts to get Japan to boost its domestic consumption as well as
imports.
   Japan is also beset with domestic problems, including allegations
that top politicians or their aides profited from shares in a real
estate development firm by buying them before the firm was publicly
traded.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita will hold talks Thursday and
Friday with Bush, Secretary of States James A. Baker III and
Congressional leaders.
   Under former Secretary of State George P. Shultz, Armacost played
a key role in dealing with Soviet authorities on regional disputes
in Afghanistan, southwest Africa, Cambodia and Central America.
   An imposing 6-footer, Armacost has a quiet demeanor and low-key
style.
   Twenty years ago, he served in Tokyo as a visiting professor of
international relations at the International Christian University in
Tokyo.
   Armacost, 51, is a graduate of Carleton College and Columbia
University. He is married and has three children.
   He is expected to be succeeded in the job of under secretary of
state by Robert Kimmet, a Washington lawyer. Bush is breaking
precedent by not naming a career diplomat to the post, but Lawrence
Eagleburger, another former foreign service officer, is to be
nominated Deputy Secretary of State.
   In another move, Bush is expected to name Richard T. McCormack,
former ambassador to the Organization of American States, to the
post of Under Secretary of State for Economic Affairs.
   Late Tuesday, congressional sources said Bush is expected to pick
Bernard Aronson, a Democrat, as assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs.
   A Democratic Senate source, who spoke only on condition of
anonymity, said the choice had been made because Aronson was a
moderate who could appeal to both Democrats and Republicans on
divisive Central American policies, and Nicaragua in particular.
   Aronson would succeed Elliott Abrams in the post. Abrams became
the lightning rod for the Reagan admistration's Nicaragua policy,
which was the longest-running dispute with Congress of his tenure.
   Meanwhile, a White House source said President Bush is expected
to name John Negroponte, deputy national security adviser, as
ambassador to Mexico. Negroponte, a former ambassador to Honduras,
also has served in a variety of foreign postings, including in Hong
Kong, Vietnam and Ecuador.
</TEXT>
