<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-PLO     01-31 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-PLO,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abba Eban Rebuts PLO Accusations Israel Using Nazi Methods</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abba Eban, Israel's former foreign
minister, on Tuesday rebutted accusations by a senior PLO official
that the Jewish state is using Nazi methods to suppress the uprising
in its occupied territories.
   The Monday statements by Bassam Abu Sharif, a senior aide to
Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat, were
``intellectually ridiculous and morally outrageous,'' Eban told
reporters.
   Abu Sharif and Eban spoke outside a privately sponsored
conference on ``The Israeli-Palestinian Problem in European
Perspective,'' which involves prominent figures from both Israel and
the PLO.
   But both men's public addresses to the three-day gathering, which
opened Tuesday, reflected a far more conciliatory mood and called
for direct Israeli-PLO talks to end the Mideast conflict.
   Abu Sharif told a Monday news briefing that ``even the Nazis did
not dare to implement several of the measures'' being used by
Israeli troops to stop the 14-month uprising in the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   So far, the uprising has cost the lives of at least 370
Palestinians _ including 47 killed by supposedly non-lethal Israeli
plastic bullets _ and of 15 Israelis.
   ``Our people and our organization are suffering under organized
state terrorism,'' Abu Sharif said. He charged that Israel had set
up ``concentration camps'' for Palestinians that he compared to Nazi
Germany's Auschwitz death camp of World War II.
   Eban told reporters on Tuesday, ``That sort of rhetoric is going
to be an obstacle to peace. ... It is a stupid thing to say.''
   But he also noted that ``I notice that neither he (Abu Sharif)
nor his colleagues used such language in our presence here today.''
   Instead, the PLO official said in his conference address, ``We
hope the future developments (in the Mideast) will help to convince
(Israeli premier Yitzhak) Shamir there is no other way to peace but
to sit down and talk.''
   Palestinians realize ``realize they cannot build their future on
the ruins of another people,'' Abu Sharif said.
   In his address, Eban told the conference that he believed the
PLO's recent renunciation of terrorism and its acceptance of
Israel's right to exist behind secure borders.
   ``If it is real, it would be reckless not to probe it and if it
were a fraud, it would be important to expose'' the PLO claims, Eban
said. ``We must surely have reached the negotiating hour.''
</TEXT>
