<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     01-31 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leader Hints Major Leadership Changes Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief said in an
interview published Tuesday that a split in the party leadership is
slowing reform and indicated high-level personnel changes are
possible.
   Karoly Grosz, reviewing the first 10 months of his tenure as
party leader, said the leadership is ``waging a battle within
ourselves'' which has slowed its ability to implement reform.
   Differing views are leading to a ``deterioration'' of the party's
ability to implement reform, which could be grounds for personnel
changes in the party elite, he told journalists from the government
daily Magyar Hirlap and the Communist newspaper Nepszabadsag.
   If the party's policy-making Central Committee ``reaches the
conclusion that the political committee (Politburo), or the general
secretary ... cannot fulfill their tasks in this situation, it
should draw the appropriate conclusions,'' Grosz was quoted as
saying.
   ``A leadership and a leader has to reckon with all this,'' he
said in excerpts of the interview, carried by the state news agency
MTI.
   In the same interview, Grosz appeared to criticize Imre Pozsgay,
a member of the party's 11-member ruling Politburo.
   Pozsgay, one of the country's leading reformers, said in a
weekend radio interview that the 1956 anti-communist revolt was not
a counterrevolution, as officially termed for the past 30 years, but
a popular uprising.
   Grosz said Pozsgay's statement, based on work by a party
committee he heads that is reviewing the country's past 40 year
history, was premature.
   But in a television interview broadcast Monday evening, Grosz
said the Central Committee could reach the same conclusion as
Pozsgay ``if the facts justify it.''
   Many of the demands voiced in the short-lived revolution, such as
increased democracy, a multiparty system and opposition to a
Stalinist-style leadership are reflected in Hungary's reform process
now.
</TEXT>
