<FIRST>r a AM-Seabrook-LowPower     01-31 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook-Low Power,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Licensing Board Clears Obstacle To Low-Power Tests at Seabrook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two obstacles to low-power testing of
the Seabrook nuclear power plant was cleared Tuesday when a federal
board decided not to hold hearings on workers' performance during an
emergency exercise.
   Seabrook's owners now can get their long-awaited low-power
license if they prove that they can come up with $72.1 million to
decontaminate and dismantle the reactor if it conducts the atomic
tests but never operates commercially.
   The $5.8 billion Seabrook reactor was completed in July 1986
after years of delays and cost overruns. It remains idle because of
evacuation-planning and financial obstacles.
   In a Dec. 21 ruling, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission set two
conditions for low-power testing: establishment of the
decommissioning fund, and a decision by one of its licensing boards
on whether to open hearings on plant workers' performance during the
two-day exercise in June.
   Seabrook spokesman Sean O'Neill said Tuesday plant owners expect
to submit a decommissioning-fund plan ``within the next couple of
weeks.'' John Eichorn, chairman of the Seabrook owners' executive
committee, said recently the owners are trying to buy a surety bond
to meet the $72.1 million commitment.
   On procedural grounds, the licensing board Tuesday dismissed
Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon's request for the
hearings, NRC spokesman Frank Ingram said. The plant is near the
Massachusetts border, and six Massachusetts communities lie within
the plant's 10-mile evacuation plan.
   Shannon's request was based on an NRC staff inspection report
dated July 15 but the request was not filed until Sept. 16.
   The licensing board said Shannon waited too long to file the
request.
   A spokeswoman for Shannon, Mary Breslauer, promised an appeal.
   ``Obviously we believe we were well within the legal time frame''
for filing the contention, she said. ``What we got (from NRC
inspectors in July) was an initial report, very undetailed ... We
did not get detailed backup reports until mid-August. Clearly until
then we couldn't file.''
   The initial NRC inspection report said Seabrook control-room
support staff displayed ``questionable engineering judgment'' and
other shortcomings during a hypothetical accident under the exercise
scenario.
   The NRC concluded, however, that plant workers passed the test,
which was part of a federal exercise of Seabrook's evacuation plans.
   O'Neill, the Seabrook spokesman, said plant officials also had
not yet seen the licensing board ruling, but ``it sounds like good
news.''
   Licensing delays last year forced the key Seabrook owner, Public
Service Company of New Hampshire, to seek bankruptcy protection, and
other owners' finances also have become strained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
