<FIRST>r f PM-YugoBankruptcy Bjt   01-31 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugo Bankruptcy, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Automaker Files For Chapter 11 Bankruptcy Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugo America Inc., the importer of
inexpensive Yugoslav-made cars, is trying to throw its financial
problems into reverse by filing for protection under federal
bankruptcy laws.
   Yugo, its parent company and an affiliated corporation asked a
bankruptcy judge Monday for protection from their creditors. Their
petition said more than 300 companies and individuals may hold
claims against the firms.
   Yugo's sales slipped to 31,546 cars in 1988, a plunge of 35
percent from its 1987 performance.
   Former company president William Prior cited sagging sales and
the loss of dealerships when he resigned in November.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Vincent J. Commisa signed an order Monday
allowing Impex Car Corp. to provide financing and take management
control of the company, said Kenneth A. Rosen, a company attorney.
Impex is an affilliate of Zavodi Crevna Zastava, the Yugoslavian
manufacturer of the Yugo car.
   ``The purpose of the financing is to continue the sale of Yugo
automobiles to dealers and to provide the supply of parts to
dealers,'' said Rosen.
   Yugo was joined in its filing by its parent Global Motors Inc.,
and affiliate Proton America Inc.
   Toma Savic, a Yugo sales representative from Yugoslavia, said
Monday after the National Automobile Dealers Association Convention
in New Orleans the filing could ease Yugo's efforts to stay in the
United States, where it has about 250 dealers.
   Some of those dealers objected to the decision.
   Dick Loehr, a dealer in Kalamazoo, Mich. who also sells other
lines of cars, said Yugo dealers tried to talk company officials out
of filing the bankruptcy papers.
   ``The dealers thought that the investors group (behind Yugo) was
a bottomless pit,'' he said, adding that the dealers had heard
rumors about a possible bankruptcy filing for some time.
   The filing did not shock industry analysts.
   ``It's really not a surprise at all'' said analyst Chris
Cedergren of California-based J.D. Power and Associates.
   ``Global Motors has had some financial difficulties for a while
now,'' Cedergren said. ``They put a great deal of money into Global
Motors hoping they would turn it around.''
   ``It really didn't help that much,'' he said.
   Analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc. said the car's design may have been to blame for the filing.
   `I just think it wasn't attractive and you might as well spend
the extra thousand and get something else,'' she said. ``That's what
happened.''
   Yugo, based in Upper Saddle River, touted its boxy subcompact
cars as the cheapest new auto in the United States when they went on
sale in August 1985 at $3,995.
   Sales topped 39,100 in the first 10 months of 1987, but dropped
to 26,000 in the same period of 1988, according to figures released
by the company.
   Several calls placed Monday to the company were not answered.
   In its filing, Yugo listed $30.5 million in assets and the same
amount in liability and equity. Global Motors listed $27.4 million
in each category. Proton America listed $10,000 in each.
   Mabon Nugent and Co., a New York investment banking company which
invested $10.5 million in Global Motors and owns 33 percent of the
company, said the bankruptcy filing was welcome.
   ``It is appropriate that the Yugoslavian manufacturer of the car
has come forward with support necessary for the company to proceed.
Hopefully, they will be able to complete a plan of reorganization
and continue to serve Yugo dealers and customers,'' the banking
concern said.
   Court papers said the filing was authorized by Marcel Kole, the
company's chief financial officer and acting chief executive officer.
   He said the company is committed to doing business in the United
States.
   In April 1988, Yugo had 300 employees and now has 60, Kole said.
</TEXT>
