<DOCNO> AP890131-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-YugoBankruptcy-Dealers     01-31 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugo Bankruptcy-Dealers,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugo Dealers Learn of Company's Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Yuto Bankruptcy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Hanks has about 30 Yugos on the lot of
Sundance Chevrolet in Lansing, Mich., and he's wondering what's
going to happen to them.
   Yugo America Inc., the troubled importer of inexpensive
Yugoslavian-made cars, its parent company and an affiliate on Monday
filed for protection under federal bankruptcy laws.
   Yugo officials maintain they want to continue doing business in
the United States and that another marketing system would be set up.
The company said the supply of cars, which sell for about $5,000
apiece, would continue along with warranty work.
   That was good news for dealers like Hanks, many of whom tried to
talk the company out of filing the bankruptcy papers.
   ``It's a good little car,'' Hanks said, calling the bankruptcy
filing a ``shame.'' Hanks said in a telephone interview that his
dealership sells about 400 cars a month, 30 of which are Yugos.
   But he also said it was possible the dealership would get rid of
the franchise if Yugo's price rose too much.
   Jeff Van Hill, sales manager of Elhart Dodge-Yugo in Holland,
Mich., agreed that the boxy, economy car is a good seller. ``The
Yugo has done a good job for us,'' he said. ``It's filled a good
(car market) niche.''
   He said the Yugo has outsold every model Dodge offers except its
popular Caravan minivan. Nationwide, Yugo sales dropped 35 percent
in 1988 compared with 1987.
   Bob Mackie, general manager of Classic Chevrolet in Grand Rapids,
Mich., said his organization decided two months ago to drop the car.
   ``We had written a letter to them to resign our franchise,'' he
said. ``Basically, we are sitting with 37 of their automobiles that
they are to purchase back from us.''
   Co-owner Ken Shephard of O'Donnell Motors in San Gabriel, Calif.,
also has bailed out of a Yugo franchise.
   ``We're done with Yugo,'' he said. ``We canceled in August, took
a 90-day extension on parts and warranty and delivered our last Yugo
earlier this month.''
   Shephard said Yugo still owes him about $20,000 for unpaid
warranty claims and factory incentive costs for which he put up the
money.
   ``We thought pretty much in October that we would not see that,''
he said.
   Shephard said he didn't think anything was wrong with the car, it
just didn't sell. But Yugos began leaving his lot when he slashed
the price to $2,900, at a loss of about $2,500 per car.
   ``I'm glad to say that we don't have any more,'' he said.
</TEXT>
