<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TreasuryBills     01-31 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Short-Term Rates at 3-Week High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the government's latest auction to the highest
level in three weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 8.33 percent on Monday, up from 8.26
percent last week. An additional $7.2 billion was sold in six-month
bills at an average discount rate of 8.39 percent, up from 8.31
percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Jan. 9, when three-month bills
sold for 8.36 percent and six-month bills averaged 8.48 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.63 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,789.40 and 8.88 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,575.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable-rate mortgages, rose to 8.97
percent last week from 8.96 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
