<FIRST>u f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock 1stLd-Writethru f0009 01-31 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Polaroid Buyback Plan Could Be Hindered By Shamrock Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with lawsuit filed by Shamrock.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Since July ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. has filed a
lawsuit to block Polaroid Corp.'s $1.1 billion stock buyback plan,
which analysts believe was designed to thwart a hostile takeover by
the television and radio concern.
   Shamrock, the Disney-owned company that has been pursuing
Polaroid since last summer, filed suit Monday in Delaware State
Court.
   The suit asks the court to prohibit both Polaroid's buyback
program and its plan to issue $300 million in convertible preferred
stock, which also were announced on Monday. Polaroid said it
indicated it had invited two members of the investor group,
Corporate Partners L.P., to join its board of directors.
   In its suit, Shamrock alleges Polaroid's directors ``breached
their fiduciary duties by issuing additional, dilutive voting
securities to persons friendly to management in the face of
Shamrock's announced intention to wage a proxy contest at Polaroid's
upcoming annual meeting.''
   Since July, the instant photography pioneer has been fighting a
hostile buyout offer from Shamrock, which is offering $45 a share in
a tender offer that values Polaroid at about $3.2 billion.
   Shamrock, a television and radio concern owned by the Roy E.
Disney family, also has indicated it will wage a proxy fight for
control of Polaroid's board at the company's annual meeting in May,
and if successful would force the sale of Polaroid either under its
offer or a higher third-party bid.
   Shamrock president and chief executive officer Stanley Gold
called Polaroid's actions irresponsible and a sign of entrenched
management.
   ``The placement of preferred stock, together with the proposed
stock buy-back program, is clearly a defensive action designed to
park even more Polaroid shares in `friendly hands' at the expense of
Polaroid's public shareholders,'' Gold said.
   Polaroid stock closed Monday at $40.62{, up 62{ cents in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Polaroid spokesman Sam Yanes denied the planned stock issue was a
defensive move designed to discourage Burbank-based Shamrock's
advances.
   ``It's designed simply to deliver a portion of the company's
current value while enhancing the growth prospects for its values,''
Yanes said.
   Companies frequently buy their own stock to reduce the number of
shares outstanding and to raise the stock price. Such practices have
become common among companies seeking to discourage takeovers.
   Some analysts said Polaroid's stock buyback was unlikely to
attract shareholders unless the market price of Polaroid stock tops
Shamrock's $45-a-share offer.
   ``There's no incentive for people to sell the Polaroid stock,''
said Alex Henderson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   Henderson said stockholders would do better to tender their stock
to Shamrock and wait for the market price to rise. If the stock
appreciates, he said, stockholders could withdraw the tendered
shares and sell them on the open market.
   ``The catalyst to all this restructuring is Shamrock, whether
(Polaroid officials) admit it or not,'' he said.
   Peter Enderlin, an analyst with New York's Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co., predicted Polaroid's stock price would rise due to the
repurchase plan. He said the company was prepared to pay more than
the $45 offered by Shamrock.
   ``Unless Shamrock comes back with another increase I think
definitely the pendulum has swung to Polaroid protecting their own
company,'' said Charles K. Ryan, an analyst with Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets.
   The preferred stock to be issued to Corporate Partners, a firm
managed by New York investors Lester Pollack and Ali Wambold, is
convertible to common stock at a price of $50 a share.
   The group also received warrants to purchase 635,000 shares of
Polaroid common stock at $50 a share.
   Polaroid has 71.6 million common shares outstanding.
   Polaroid's board of directors last week rejected as inadequate
Shamrock's sweetened $45 offer, which includes 9.7 million shares
issued under Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan.
   Shamrock is appealing a Delaware court ruling that upheld the
Polaroid employee stock ownership plan. Polaroid is incorporated in
Delaware.
   Shamrock contends the employee stock was issued specifically to
block a takeover. If the plan is invalidated, Shamrock says, it will
raise its offer to $3.36 billion, or $47 per share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
