<FIRST>r f PM-Mosbacher 1stLd-Writethru f0020 01-31 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mosbacher, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Refuses to Postpone Vote on Mosbacher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs new to UPDATE with committee vote. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, Common Cause ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Commerce Committee voted today to
recommend that the Senate confirm President Bush's nomination of
Texas oilman Robert Mosbacher as commerce secretary.
   The committee's voice vote came despite a request by the public
interest lobbying group Common Cause group to delay action on the
nomination of Mosbacher until more is known about the nominee's
fund-raising on behalf of Bush.
   Mosbacher, 61, was warmly received at his confirmation hearing
before the committee last week as he promised to work to increase
U.S. exports and to vigorously enforce laws designed to protect U.S.
business from unfair foreign competition.
   But Common Cause said Monday the committee's vote should be
postponed until more complete information is obtained on corporate
donors to the Republican National Committee. The group says it wants
to ensure against a conflict-of-interest between those corporate
contributors and Mosbacher's work as commerce secretary.
   Common Cause says the RNC has yet to release a full and accurate
list of the people and corporations that gave at least $100,000 each
to the ``Team 100'' fund-raising drive led by Mosbacher, who was
Bush's chief fund-raiser.
   The Republicans released a list of people who had made
contributions, but said much of the money was given on behalf of
corporations that were not identified.
   Common Cause President Fred Wertheimer said the information on
corporate donors was needed ``to allow the public to be able to
identify any possible connections that might arise between the
soft-money contributions and any direct interest the contributors
may end up having in issues before the Commerce Department under Mr.
Mosbacher's leadership.''
   Committee Chairman Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., responded that he
would not delay the vote because it would be wrong to ``raise sand''
over conduct that was allowed under federal election law.
   Hollings did say that he would introduce legislation to limit
spending in federal elections.
   ``The fault here lies with the Congress and not with Mr.
Mosbacher,'' he said.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
