<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Coca-Cola     01-31 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Coca-Cola,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Earnings Up 22 Percent, Annual Rise 14 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coca-Cola Co. said Tuesday its net income for
the fourth quarter rose 22 percent as the soft drink company
benefited from increased international sales and a drop in costs.
   Annual earnings for the Atlanta-based company were up 14 percent,
going over the billion-dollar mark for the first time in the
company's 103-year-history. The previous record was $934 million in
1986 before the company spun off its bottling and movie subsidiaries.
   For the quarter ended Dec. 31, Coke earned $235.5 million
compared with $193 million a year earlier. After a $5.2 million
deduction for preferred stock dividends, the earnings were 65 cents
per share, compared to 52 cents in the 1987 quarter, when there was
no preferred stock deduction.
   Fourth-quarter revenue edged up 1.8 percent to $2.03 billion from
$1.99 billion a year earlier.
   The cost of goods sold fell 8.1 percent for the quarter to $912.8
million from $993.4 million.
   For the year, net income was $1.04 billion from $916.14 million
in 1987. After a $6.43 million preferred stock dividend, earnings
per share were $2.85, compared with $2.43 in 1987 when there was no
preferred stock dividend.
   The company said foreign soft drink shipments grew 7 percent last
year, led by combined volume and operating income increases of 26
percent in Canada and 12 percent in the Pacific.
   Domestically, soft drink concentrate and syrup shipments rose 6
percent and operating income was up 9 percent. Retail case sales
advanced an estimated 5 percent.
   Coca-Cola Foods, which includes Hi-C and Minute Maid brands, had
a 15 percent increase in volume for its boxed fruit juices. However,
volume for frozen orange juice was down 22 percent and chilled
orange juice volume fell 6 percent.
   The company reported a 34 percent increase in operating income
growth for the division, however, because of a restructuring in 1987.
   Coca-Cola reported a 57 percent decline in equity income because
of lower earnings at Columbia Pictures Entertainment resulting from
the one-time writedowns associated with restructuring.
   In December 1987, Coca-Cola's Columbia Pictures subsidiary was
combined with Tri-Star Pictures to form Columbia Pictures
Entertainment Inc., which is now a free-standing company in which
Coca-Cola owns 49 percent of the stock.
   Coca-Cola also owns 49 percent of Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc., the
largest bottler of Coke products. Those two companies contributed
$29.5 million in income for the quarter and $48.3 million for the
year.
   During 1988, the company said it repurchased 18.9 million shares
of common stock, decreasing outstanding shares by 3.4 percent. In
all, the company has bought back 25.5 million of the announced
repurchase of 40 million shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
