<FIRST>r f PM-UMW-Pittston 1stLd-Writethru f0053 01-31 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0053,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW President Postpones Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Trumka throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers today agreed to extend
its deadline and continue negotiations with the Pittston Coal Group,
averting a walkout by 1,700 miners scheduled for midnight tonight.
   Union President Richard L. Trumka told a Washington news
conference the union would accept a request by the governors of
Kentucky, Virginia and West Virginia to call off the strike deadline
in favor of continued negotiations.
   Govs. Gerald Baliles of Virginia, Gaston Caperton of West
Virginia and Wallace Wilkinson of Kentucky made the request last
week, asking the union to agree to a 30-to-60-day cooling-off period.
   Trumka promised to comply with that request.
   At the same time, however, Trumka announced the latest
development in the union's ``corporate campaign'' of trying to put
pressure on Pittston through protests and other actions against the
company and its business partners.
   Today's target was Crestar Financial Corp., one of five banks
that in December 1987 extended to Pittston a $100 million line of
credit. That was one month before the expiration of the miners'
contract. They have been working wothout a contract since.
   Trumka said the Crestar boycott began today with the withdrawal
of $29.7 million from the bank _ $23 million by the Bakery and
Confectionary Union and Industry International Pension Fund and $6.7
million by the UMW.
   ``I anticipate that millions more will be withdrawn from Crestar
to protest its financial support of Pittston,'' Trumka said.
   In a letter to the three governors announcing the extension of
the strike deadline, Trumka thanked them for their support and said
the union for the most part has ``walked the road alone'' in its
search for a fair settlement to the contract squabble with Pittston.
   And he again called on Pittston chief executive officer Paul W.
Douglas to meet face-to-face with him to discuss the negotiations.
   The Pittston Co., based in Greenwich, Conn., is the corporate
parent of the coal group, based in Lebanon, Va.
   Miners have been on the job with no contract at Pittston since
last Feb. 1. After Pittston refused to sign a wage agreement the UMW
reached at other major eastern producers.
   The sides met again Monday, but dd not resolve their differences.
   Over the past week, the company has been considering a union
contract offer made last Tuesday in response to an offer Pittston
made on Nov. 9. During the year of negotiations, each side had
accused the other of hindering progress by refusing to bargain in
good faith.
   Pittston had said repeatedly it planned to operate through a
strike, perhaps by hiring permanent replacement miners. The union
responded with a ``corporate strategy'' in which it tried to
pressure Pittston through demonstrations and other actions against
its business partners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
