<DOCNO> AP890131-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-FaxFollies Adv03   01-31 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fax Follies, Adv 03,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Friday Feb. 3 and thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Facsimile Machines Transform Life But Can Create Headaches _ and
Lawsuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facsimile machines, the latest office
rage, have made it easier and possibly more fun for workers to work,
stay in touch, and even order lunch, but they also have fallen prey
to human goofs and greed.
   A presidential candidate used a fax machine to enter the race at
the last minute. A Boston radio station accepts contest entries by
fax _ and notifies winners the same way.
   But a leading retailer recently lost a $73 million lawsuit in
federal court here partly because a confidential document was faxed
to the wrong place, and irritation is growing as ``junk fax''
increases.
   Still, ``Once you have one you can't live without it, and you use
it more and more,'' said Elliot King, co-author of ``The Book of
Fax: An Impartial Guide to Buying &amp; Using Fascimile Machines.''
   The machines convert a page of information into an electronic
format, then transmit it via telephone line to another machine on
the other end, where it is decoded and printed. The average office
fax costs $1,000 to $4,000.
   More than 4 million fax machines will be purchased by 1991, and
sales are expected to grow at 30 percent a year well into the 1990s,
according to King's book.
   ``To a lot of people the fax machine has become a fact of life in
the office,'' said Barbara Crouse, advertising and promotion
director for Boston's WROR-FM.
   The radio station has been using the fax to entice office workers
to listen. It has been running a contest asking workers to fax in
the funniest thing found lying around the office. The chuckle of the
day wins, with the victor receiving notification from the station
via fax.
   ``They not only have to send us the fax, but they have to watch
their fax machines to see if they've won,'' said Crouse.
   Office workers can also use the machines to place lunch orders at
``fax food'' restaurants.
   ``We do a lot of delivery and takeout and for them to just fax
over their order, it goes through less hands and it keeps the order
more correct,'' said Evie Young, manager of Maxine's Seafood Cafe in
Los Angeles. ``It saves us in tying up phone lines.''
   She said the restaurant, which got its fax machine in October,
gets about half its takeout requests via fax, roughly 15 to 20
orders per day.
   The portable fax opens up a whole new world to faxaholics.
   ``I had a guy come in here once who wanted a portable one so he
could take it golfing,'' said Anthony J. Villaloando, owner of
Citifax Information Systems in Northbrook, Ill.
   Portable fax machines were used constantly during the
presidential election, said Tad Devine, director of delegate
selection for Michael Dukakis' Democratic primary campaign and
campaign coordinator for vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen.
   Both candidates traveled in planes equipped with fax machines.
They also had portable fax for use in their hotel rooms, he said.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri almost missed his chance to run
for the Democratic presidential nomination when his filing papers
failed to show up for the primary deadline.
   ``When it was not there late that afternoon, his campaign was
contacted by the secretary of state in Oklahoma and Gephardt's
campaign sent in a fax,'' said Devine.
   But fax fiascos can be expensive.
   A federal lawsuit that ended in a $73 million judgment against K
mart Corp. earlier this month was initiated when a clerk mistakenly
faxed a confidential document to Fashion House, a Pawtucket-based
merchandise wholesaler.
   The document, an estimate of the commissions owed, was intended
for K mart headquarters in Troy, Mich. K mart is appealing the
judgment.
   ``It is a danger,'' agrees King. ``It's like mail without an
envelope and you can make a lot of mistakes.''
   Just like the U.S. Postal Service, junk mail is a problem.
   A Connecticut legislator recently proposed legislation that would
ban the unsolicited use of fax machines to send advertising messages.
   ``It's a really effective way for people to direct sales and
services,'' King said, explaining the 10 percent return on mass
faxings is more than double that of bulk mailings.
   In addition, the ``fax attacks'' cost the solicitor less money
than mailings because there are no printing, envelope stuffing or
postage fees. The owners of the targeted telecopier, however, gets
stung $3 to $4 for the price of paper, printing and manpower, said
King.
   Daniel Fishman, King's co-author, envisons another problem _
fax-a-porn.
   ``Some enterprising young person sometime will enter the business
of pornography,'' he said. ``Call up and get a pornographic
photograph'' faxed to you.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for PMs Friday Feb. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
