<HEAD>Company Expects Charges in Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittaker Corp. says it expects the company or
a subsidiary will be charged in a federal investigation, apparently
the Pentagon fraud investigation.
   The company said in a terse news release Monday that Justice
Department investigators had presented evidence that ``certain
employees or a unit of Whittaker caused money to be paid to a
government employee in connection with certain government
contracts.''
   ``Whittaker believes that it is likely that the investigation
will result in criminal charges being brought against Whittaker or
one of its subsidiaries,'' the release continued.
   The company didn't name the employees or the subsidiary, but
Whittaker's now-closed command and control systems unit in
Farmington, Ark., was searched in connection with the probe in June.
   Investigators have been examining dealings between the company
and Jack Sherman, a Marine Corps contracting official who pleaded
guilty last week ot taking bribes of $43,500 from an unidentified
industry consultant serving as a government informer, the Wall
Street Journal reported.
   Investigators found documents showing contact between Sherman and
an official of Lee Telecommunications Corp., a company that
Whittaker bought in 1986, the Los Angeles Times reported.
