<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-USX     01-31 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-USX,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>USX Reports Fourth-Quarter Turnaround</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. on Tuesday reported profits of $158
million in the fourth quarter of 1988, saying a rejuvenated steel
division helped it rebound from a $14 million loss in the same
period a year earlier.
   The nation's largest steelmaker said the profit, equal to 55
cents a share, came on sales of $4.4 billion, up from $4.3 billion
in the last three months of 1987.
   USX Chairman David Roderick attributed the turnaround in part to
the company's improved steel division, USS.
   Operating income there was $501 million on sales of $5.8 billion,
four times higher than the $125 million on sales of $3.7 billion
reported for 1987.
   USX, formerly known as U.S. Steel, also is the parent of Marathon
Oil Co. and Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp.
   For the entire year, USX said earnings tripled to $756 million,
or $2.62 a share, on sales of $16.9 billion. That compares to
profits of $219 million, or 54 cents a share, on sales of $14.9
billion in 1987.
   ``All of our major segments were profitable in 1988, and we
expect improved profitability in both our steel and energy segments
in 1989,'' Roderick said in a statement. ``We are stronger
financially now than in any recent year.''
   Operating income from energy operations rose 7 percent, to $475
million from $444 million in 1987, despite continued trouble at
Texas Oil &amp; Gas.
   The unit reported losses of $31 million for 1988 and $7 million
for the fourth quarter, compared with operating income of $2 million
for 1987 and a loss of $4 million for the 1987 fourth quarter.
   USX blamed diminished margins on gas gathering and weak crude oil
prices for the Texas Oil &amp; Gas losses.
</TEXT>
