<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Computer     01-31 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computer,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data Posts $12.8 Million Loss In Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. on Tuesday reported a fourth-quarter loss of
$12.8 million and annual profits of only $1.7 million, while its
chairman forecast another disappointing year for 1989.
   The fourth-quarter results of the Bloomington, Minn.-based
computer maker compared to net earnings in the same period a year
ago of $10.8 million, or 26 cents a share. Sales for the quarter of
$933 million were slightly ahead of last year's $927 million.
   It was the second consecutive quarter of losses after four
profitable quarters.
   For the year, Control Data's net income dropped to 3 cents a
share on sales of $3.6 billion from the 1987 level of $19.3 million,
or 45 cents a share, on sales of $3.4 billion.
   The computer maker suffered from poor results in its mainframe,
supercomputer and semiconductor businesses, Chairman Robert Price
said.
   ``Although we anticipate the majority of Control Data businesses
to be profitable in 1989, the company's overall operating
performance will continue to be disappointing until we fix the
problems that undermined 1988 results,'' Price said. ``The goal for
the coming year is to resolve those problems and lay a foundation
that is the basis of strong performance in subsequent years.''
   Mainframe computer shipments in 1988 were hurt by delays in
getting critical logic ships from a supplier and by soft demand,
especially in the United States, Price said.
   In July the company temporarily shut down several of its
mainframe plants and temporarily idled 7 percent of its work force
in response to the trouble.
   The company's new ETA Systems supercomputer subsidiary had poor
1988 results, and semiconductor revenues were off partly because the
data storage market continues to be weak, he said.
   Nancy Foltz, a spokeswoman for the company, said layoffs,
attrition and the sale of some businesses in 1988 resulted in a 2.3
percent decrease in Control Data's work force from 34,500 employees
at the end of 1987 to 33,700 at the end of 1988. In addition, the
company has told its 27,000 U.S. employees that they must take five
days off without pay in the first quarter of this year.
   Other changes at Control Data included changes in top management
in December, including the appointment of Lawrence Perlman as
president.
</TEXT>
