<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Borden     01-31 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Borden,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Borden Posts 15.4 Percent Gain In Fourth-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borden Inc. said Tuesday its fourth-quarter
profit rose 15.4 percent despite drought-related costs that severely
affected the company's dairy products earnings.
   For the three-month period ended Dec. 31, Borden's net income
totaled $93.9 million, or $1.27 a share, up from $81.3 million, or
$1.10 a share in the year-earlier period. Revenue rose 9.9 percent
to $1.98 billion from $1.8 billion in the 1987 quarter.
   For all of 1988, the giant food producer posted a 16.8 percent
increase in after-tax profit to $311.9 million, or $4.22 a share,
from $267.1 million, or $3.62 a share in the previous year. The
company's revenue for the year totaled $7.2 billion, up 11 percent
from $6.5 billion in 1987.
   Borden Chairman R.J. Ventres attributed the latest gains to
``internal business growth spurred by the benefits of
acquisitions,'' including the purchase a year ago of The Prince Co.,
which makes pasta products.
   Strong performances by the company's Snacks and International
Consumer Products Division and the Grocery and Specialty Products
Division, including Eagle Brand products, were largely responsible
for Borden's yearlong gains, the company said.
   But drought-related costs resulted in a 12 percent slump in
operating income for the company's dairy sector, to $102.3 million
in 1988 from $116.3 million in 1987.
   Borden said profit margins were squeezed, especially in the
second half, by unprecedented cost jumps for raw milk.
   ``Fierce competition at the retail level delayed cost recovery in
product pricing,'' Borden said.
</TEXT>
