<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished higher today in active
trading, rebounding briskly late in the session.
   Analysts said the market succumbed early today to profit-taking
in the wake of last week's impressive rally, which continued on
Monday.
   ``We're pretty overbought,'' said Edward Nicoski, an analyst at
Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood Inc. in Minneapolis. ``It just looks like
we're undergoing a bout of profit-taking.''
   Wall Street's bullish enthusiasm was dampened somewhat by
comments today by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan,
analysts said. Among other things, Greenspan told Congress' Joint
Economic Committee that the potential threat of inflation still
persists in the economy.
   The Fed chairman had made similar statements last week, but the
stock and bond markets were unruffled by them at that time.
   After the market tested lower levels, however, it bounced back
late in the day and again showed the strength characterizing its
recent rally. As the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell toward
the 2,300 level, a massive buying surge was said to be triggered.
   ``This is a market that shows resilience,'' said Monte Gordon,
director of research at Dreyfus Corp.
   The comeback reinforced market players' belief that many foreign
investors and U.S. institutions are poised to jump on the rally
bandwagon.
   ``I remain bullish on the market,'' said Peter DaPuzzo, manager
of the retail equity group at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``I think
the ingredients are still there for the market to continue with the
rally.''
