<DOCNO> AP890131-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoDealers     01-31 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Dealers,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>NADA President Issues Challenges to Automakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers are discriminating against the
nation's automobile dealers, who must unite to make buying and
selling cars a fairer game in the United States, the president of a
dealers' group said Tuesday.
   ``We dealers are swivel-necked from turning the other cheek, and
it simply has to stop,'' said Ron Tonkin, the 1989 president of the
National Automobile Dealers Association.
   ``We want automakers to be healthy and profitable, but not by
wreaking havoc on the best, most loyal friends they ever had, their
dealers,'' said Tonkin, a dealer with 10 stores holding 14
automobile franchises in the Portland, Ore., area.
   In his speech to about 20,000 peopel attending NADA's annual
convention, Tonkin singled out the subsidies from automakers to
companies that buy fleets of cars.
   He said he wanted the makers to ``simply tell us `We will sell to
no one for less than we sell to our franchised dealers.'''
   But company officials for the Big Three automakers said their
fleet brokers are franchised dealers.
   C.N. Moore, General Motors Corp.' vice president for customer
sales and service, said from his office in Detroit that all GM's
fleet sales are through franchised dealers, except for sales to the
federal government.
   ``These people that Ron Tonkin was talking to today are the
people who deliver all these cars to fleet customers,'' Moore said.
   Ford Motor Co. spokesman Ray Windecker and Chrysler Corp.
spokesman Tom Houston each said their companies' fleet sales are
arranged through dealers. Chrysler's cars for the federal government
must go through dealers, Houston said.
   Ford sells directly to the federal government and the Red Cross.
   But Tonkin said dealers who handle fleet sales frequently handle
only the paperwork associated with them, not the vehicles themselves.
   ``While technically what they're saying is correct,'' Tonkin
said, ``after you go out beyond the dealer that's doing the
paperwork, there are dealers who are damning it.''
   Automaker officials declined to say how much a subsidy might be
worth to a dealer.
   Around 20 percent of the industry's sales, roughly 1.6 million
cars a year, are to fleet customers, the companies said.
   On other matters, Tonkin:
   _Called on automakers to pay for space in their showrooms like
food and beverage makers pay for shelf space in grocery stores.
   _Said he was forming a task force to meet with manufacturers
hoping to find a way to make customer satisfaction indexes more
uniform. Tonkin said the indexes sometimes discriminate against
dealers and should be standardized for the industry.
   _Simplify warranties to make them more understandable for car
buyers and sellers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
