<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-31 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Weather, Coming of Lent Affect Futures Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The onslaught of colder weather and an expected drop in meat
demand during Lent influenced futures prices for some farm
commodities Tuesday, analysts said.
   Grain and soybean prices were up sharply on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Prices were bolstered by unexpectedly high weekly export
inspection figures and a report from Sparks Commodities, a private
crop analyst, that pegged Argentina's soybean crop lower than U.S.
Agriculture Department estimates, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
in Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``A weather forecast calling for bitter cold temperatures in
wheat growing areas supported the wheat prices,'' said Mickey Luth,
a Chicago analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Wheat settled 3\ cents to 6} cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.40{ a bushel; corn was 3} cents to 7\ cents
higher, with March at $2.74} a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 6} cents
higher, with March at $2.21} a bushel; and soybeans were 4 cents to
12} cents higher, with March at $7.72} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures prices were mostly higher on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cash prices were helpful for both cattle and hog futures, said
Jerry Gidel, general analyst with G.H. Miller, but enthusiasm was
limited by the propect of diminished consumer demand for meat during
Lent, a 40-day religious period which begins Feb. 8.
   ``The cold weather forecast has been a factor in the
marketplace,'' said Gidel in Chicago. ``There should be less farmer
movement of animals to market once the colder temperatures set in.''
   Cattle settled .10 cent to .42 cent higher, with the contract for
delivery in February at 74.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08
cent to .30 cent higher, with March at 84.47 cents a pound; live
hogs were .05 cent to .80 cent higher, with February at 43.35 cents
a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to 1.00 cent
higher, with February at 39.52 cents a pound.
   Precious metal prices were lower for the fourth straight session
on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   ``The further declines were in response to strong dollar gains,
which were accomplished by (Federal Reserve Chairman) Alan
Greenspan's anti-inflationary statements to Congress today,'' said
Jim Steel, an analyst with Refco Inc. in New York.
   Gold settled $3.70 to $4.10 lower, with the contract for delivery
in February at $391.60 a troy ounce; and silver was 4 cents to 4.4
cents lower, with February at $5.79.2 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices fell on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Crude oil settled 16 cents to 26 cents lower, with the contract
for delivery in March at $17.03 a barrel; and heating oil was .31
cent to .64 cent lower, with February at 52.28 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
