<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-31 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Comments Lift Dollar; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged to three-month highs Tuesday
after Federal Reserve Board Chairman said the U.S. trade deficit
would shrink in coming months without a decline in the dollar's
value.
   Gold prices, meanwhile, fell to their lowest level in two years,
continuing the downward trend that began last Friday when they broke
below $400 an ounce.
   Greenspan also said that the Federal Reserve's efforts to boost
interest rates would not lead to a recession, but would extend the
current expansion by keeping inflation under control.
   Currency dealers took the remarks to mean that the U.S. central
bank was unconcerned by the dollar's recent rise and was willing to
keep interest rates tight, something that would make
dollar-denominated investments attractive.
   ``It was Greenspan today,'' said Kathryn Curtin, assistant
treasurer of the National Australia Bank Ltd. in New York.
   Testifying before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress,
Greenspan also reiterated his statement of last week that the
current rate of inflation is too high and said he expects a further
substantial contraction in the U.S. trade deficit.
   Dealers have been focusing on firm U.S. interest rates this year
rather than the budget and trade deficits that preoccupied them last
year.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.60 yen to a closing 129.13. But later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 129.85 yen. In New York the dollar rose to
130.13 yen from 129.30 on Monday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7535 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers than $1.7650 late
Monday. In New York the pound fell to $1.7531 from $1.7625.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
levels, included: 1.8767 West German marks, up from 1.8595; 1.5978
Swiss francs, up from 1.5808; 1.1830 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1813; 6.3743 French francs, up from 6.3235; and 1,371.3 Italian
lire, up from 1,360.5.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
levels, included: 1.8710 West German marks, up from 1.8660; 1.5985
Swiss francs, up from 1.5884; 6.3580 French francs, up from 6.3500;
2.1100 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1085; 1,365.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,365.50; and, 1.1840 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1820.
   The price of gold fell sharply in New York after having been
little changed earlier in the Far East and Europe.
   ``The (precious) metals have just done nothing for so long and
they have to test their lows before they can go higher. ... It's a
matter of water seeking its proper level,'' said Alan Posnick,
senior vice president of MTB Banking Corp. in New York.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose 59 cents a troy ounce to close at a bid
$396.55.
   Gold fell slightly in London to a late bid price of $394.25 a
troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $394.50. In Zurich, gold was
slightly higher, closing at a bid $394.20 compared with $394.00 late
Monday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $391.60 a troy ounce from $395.30 on Monday. Later,
Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was bid at
$390.80 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $394.35 late Monday.
   Silver bullion prices rose slightly on the London market where
the metal was trading at a late bid price of $5.85 a troy ounce,
compared with Monday's $5.83. But on New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.792 an ounce from $5.832 on
Monday.
</TEXT>
