<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     01-31 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices declined Tuesday due to
weather and other factors as investors awaited new statistics on
domestic petroleum supplies.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, fell 26 cents
to close at $17.03 after falling 45 cents on Monday.
   Among refined products, the February contract for unleaded
gasoline lost 1.16 cents to settle at 47.72 cents a gallon, while
domestic heating oil slumped 0.31 cent to a settlement price of
52.28 cents a gallon. The prices of other contract months also
declined.
   Traders said the reopening of the Alaska pipeline after a partial
closing on Monday due to sub-freezing temperatures, contributed to
the drop in heating oil prices. Near-month contract prices had
jumped on Monday as investors anticipated a surge in demand due to
the partial shutdown as well as the blast of cold temperatures that
hit the United States.
   Heating oil and gasoline prices also lost ground as investors
adjusted their positions on the last day of the February contract,
analysts said.
   Jim Fiedler, chief energy broker for E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc., said the decline in crude prices was due partly to
technical corrections following several weeks of steadily rising
prices since November's agreement by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   The accord, which took effect Jan. 1 and extends for six months,
set an oil production quota of 18.5 million barrels a day for the 13
OPEC members.
   At the time the accord was reached, OPEC was producing more than
22 million barrels, far more than the market could absorb. The
excess forced prices to the $12 range, below the $18 benchmark price
set by OPEC.
   Traders said they also anticipated a buildup in energy stocks
when the American Petroleum Institute released its weekly report
after the close of trading on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
