<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Xerox 1stLd-Writethru   01-31 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Xerox, 1st Ld-Writethru,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox Announces Cuts Of 2,000 Jobs; Posts Loss For Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, Xerox stock, to UPDATE with closing price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp., dissatisfied with its earnings, on
Tuesday announced a $275 million streamlining program under which it
will cut 2,000 jobs, trim its electronic typewriter business and
stop selling medical image-making equipment.
   The Stamford, Conn.-based copier giant said a charge to cover
costs of the program was recorded in the fourth quarter of 1988,
resulting in a $77 million loss for the quarter.
   Without the pre-tax charge of $275 million, profit in the quarter
would have risen 8 percent, Xerox said.
   Xerox stock rose 37{ cents a share to $62.37{ in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Xerox lost money last year in electronic typewriters; document
workstations; and medical image-making, which uses an unusual
copying process called xeroradiography, according to David Kearns,
Xerox's chairman and chief executive.
   ``We are not moving as rapidly toward our objectives as we feel
we must,'' Kearns said in a news conference, explaining the
streamlining program.
   The losses were partially offset by a good reception for its new
50 Series of copiers and healthy profits in the financial services
business, which accounts for 30 percent of Xerox revenue, the
company said.
   Xerox said its loss in the fourth quarter contrasted with a
profit of $155 million, or $1.43 a share, a year earlier. Without
the charge, it said, profit would have been $167 million. Revenue
rose 6 percent to $4.4 billion from $4.15 billion a year earlier.
   For all of 1988, Xerox said its earnings fell 33 percent to $388
million, or $3.50 a share, from $578 million, or $5.35 a share, a
year earlier. Without the fourth-quarter charge, profit would have
risen 9 percent to $632 million. Revenue rose 9 percent to $16.4
billion from $15.1 billion.
   The biggest portion of the fourth-quarter charge, $140 million,
comes from writing off excess manufacturing capacity at its
electronic typewriter plant in Fremont, Calif., and disengaging from
the Xerox Medical Systems business, which is based in Monrovia,
Calif.
   Xerox will continue to provide service and supplies to existing
customers of its medical equipment.
   Another $100 million of the charge comes from the cost of
reducing overhead and employment. Kearns said the company could not
yet say how many of the 2,000 job cuts would have to be achieved by
layoffs, vs. retirements or voluntary resignations.
   The jobs that are being eliminated are in staff rather than in
sales or manufacturing, Kearns said. The cutbacks in Fremont and
Monrovia, Calif., will not involve big job cuts because employment
has already been reduced there, Xerox said.
   The company said the market for cheaper and medium-priced
electronic typewriters has shrunk much faster than expected, leaving
the industry with excess capacity.
   Xerox said it hopes to cure the losses in its document
workstation business by gradually dropping its own workstations and
switching its software over to industry-standard workstations made
by Sun Microsystems Inc.
   Separately, Xerox said it was reorganizing its management. It
said Wayland R. Hicks, an executive vice president, will head a new
marketing and customer organization. William C. Lowe, who was hired
from International Business Machines Corp. in December, will head
development and manufacturing and Jay H. Nussbaum will head a new
unit, Integrated Systems Operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Houghton-Mifflin     01-31 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Houghton-Mifflin,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bass Group Discloses 5.6 Percent Stake in Houghton-Mifflin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Houghton Mifflin Co. stock soared
Tuesday after a group led by wealthy Texan Robert M. Bass disclosed
it recently increased its stake in the publisher to 5.6 percent.
   The Bass Group said in disclosing its holdings that its latest
purchase was for investment purposes, and the company pointed out
that Bass had been an investor in Houghton Mifflin for some time.
   Nonetheless, Wall Streeters remembered that it was the Bass
Group's bid last May that led to the takeover of another publishing
giant, Macmillan Inc., at a price about 80 percent higher than the
company's stock had been trading.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Houghton Mifflin shot up
$8.87{ a share to $45.25. At that price, the company's 14 million
shares are valued at about $633 million.
   The Bass disclosure follows two years of sweeping changes in the
publishing business that has seen Macmillan fall to British
publisher Robert Maxwell, Harper &amp; Row Publishers Inc. yield to
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. and Grolier Inc. sell to Hachette SA of
France.
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc., another publishing giant,
underwent a costly recapitalization in 1987 to avoid being acquired
by Maxwell.
   Alan Kassan, who follows publishing companies for Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., said Bass demonstrated his interest in the publishing
business with his initial Macmillan bid and his earlier acquisition
of Bell &amp; Howell Co., an information services and publishing concern
based near Chicago.
   ``I don't know what his intentions are, but he has the interest
and the deep pockets to acquire the whole thing if he so chose,''
Kassan said.
   Bert Boksen, who follows media companies for Raymond James &amp;
Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla., said Houghton Mifflin could
command a price in the mid-$50 a share range should a buyout effort
be made.
   A woman answering the telephone at Bass's offices in Fort Worth,
Texas, said it was company policy not to comment on its business
plans.
   Boston-based Houghton Mifflin is a leading educational publisher
and also publishes general interest books and educational and
word-processing software.
   It ranked fourth in the nation behind Harcourt, Gulf &amp; Western's
Simon &amp; Schuster and Macmillan based on 1987 educational revenue,
according to the trade newsletter Educational Marketer, published by
Knowledge Industry Publications Inc. in White Plains, N.Y.
   Shearson's Kassan said Houghton Mifflin has been a well-run
company with ``a fair earnings performance'' over the past two years.
   Hougton Mifflin earned $24.1 million, or $1.70 a share, on
revenue of $368.3 million in 1988.
   Nonetheless, Kassan said the company is vulnerable to a takeover
because it has a relatively small amount of its stock in the hands
of company insiders and is ``clearly a leader'' in the elementary
school reading market.
   The elementary school market stands to improve over the next few
years, industry analysts believe, as a growing number of children
reach school age.
   In its filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
Bass Group said it purchased 161,200 shares of Houghton Mifflin
stock between Jan. 10 and Jan. 27 at a prices ranging from $34.21 to
$36.80 a share.
   It said the purchase leaves it with 790,200 common shares of
Houghton Mifflin, or 5.6 percent of its 14 million shares.
   In its statement, Houghton Mifflin said, ``We do not see anything
unusual in the Bass Group's filing. Houghton Mifflin has other large
stockholders, most of whom have been investors for a long time.''
   Paul D. Weaver, secretary for the company, declined comment when
asked if the company's board had met to discuss the matter.
   The company adopted as poison-pill takeover defense plan in
December.
   Last May, the Bass Group prpoosed to acquire Macmillan for $64 a
share at a time when the company's stock had been trading at about
$50 a share. Maxwell acquired Macmillan last fall at a price of
$90.25 a share, or about $2.5 billion.
</TEXT>
