<FIRST>r f AM-7-Eleven-Bills     01-31 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-7-Eleven-Bills,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>7-Eleven To Accept Payment Of Utility Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utility customers who don't pay by mail will soon
be able to pay their bills at some 7-Eleven stores.
   National Payments Network of Paramus, N.J., said Southland
Corp.'s 7-Eleven was the first national chain that had agreed to let
the company install computer terminals to handle its electronic
payment system.
   National Payments Network caters mainly to poor and elderly
people who pay their utility bills with cash in person rather than
sending checks by mail, according to Bill Coleman, vice president
for sales and marketing.
   Utility companies in 18 states already accept bills paid through
more than 2,000 locations where the National Payments Network has
outlets. Those are mostly mom 'n' pop stores or small, regional
chains, Coleman said.
   Four 7-Eleven stores in the Los Angeles area have already tested
the National Payments Network system. Other markets will be added as
time goes on, he said.
   Since 7-Eleven stores are franchised, some may choose not to
participate.
   Although many supermarkets and other retail outlets accept
payment of bills, the National Payments Network gets money to
billers faster because it is electronic. That can make a difference
if a utility customer is threatened with cut-off.
   In some areas, 50 to 60 percent of all customers pay their
utility bills in person, National Payments Network said in a news
release.
</TEXT>
