<SECOND>AM-Fairchild-Carlyle, 1st Ld-Writethru,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlyle Group Makes New Offer For Fairchild</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with closing stock price, total
price of acquisition; picks up 3rd graf, Fairchild, attempting ...; ADDS
details of earlier offer in last graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlyle Group, a Washington-based investment
partnership, on Tuesday made a new, higher offer for Fairchild
Industries Inc., the Chantilly, Va.-based defense and space
electronics contractor.
   Carlyle made what it called a friendly offer to purchase all
outstanding shares of Fairchild Industries at $16.30 per share, or
more than $230 million assuming 14.4 million shares are outstanding.
   Fairchild's stock fell 25 cents a share to $14.75 in consolidated
New York Stock Exchange trading.
   The new price per share is the same as Fairchild said Monday it
had agreed to pay to acquire the 25 percent stake held by its
largest shareholder group.
   Fairchild, attempting to stave off a takeover threat by the
Carlyle Group, announced Monday that it intended to buy back $75
million worth of stock and securities held by the big shareholder
group, which is headed by George Soros.
   Carlyle countered with its offer Tuesday. It said that if the big
shareholder group was getting $16.30 a share for its block, the rest
of Fairchild shareholders were also entitled to get that much per
share.
   ``We request that you weigh this proposal in light of your
fiduciary responsibilities to shareholders, not management,''
Carlyle said in a statement.
   Fairchild said Monday it planned to sell the common stock it will
acquire from the Soros group to its employee stock ownership plan.
Fairchild said that step could make an acquisition that is not
approved by the board of directors more difficult.
   A partnership controlled by the Carlyle Group owns 9.99 percent
of Fairchild common shares. Its original offer was $15.50 a share,
which amounted to a little more than $220 million for the common
stock. The total acquisition cost to Carlyle under the original and
new offers would be higher because of the cost of acquiring other
securities or taking on Fairchild debt.
</TEXT>
