<FIRST>u f AM-InsiderTrading-Wang     01-31 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insider Trading-Wang,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Rookie Analyst To Pay $127,000 In Insider Trading Scam; Friend
Accused</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former junior securities analyst convicted of
inside trading in a major fraud scandal will pay back more than
$127,000 in illegal profits under an agreement approved Tuesday by a
federal judge.
   In addition, a college friend of the 24-year-old trader, Stephen
Wang, was accused in U.S. District Court in Manhattan of making
$30,000 in profits from illegal information supplied by Wang in a
separate scheme.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Owen approved a final settlement in
which Wang, without admitting or denying wrongdoing, agreed to pay
$127,585 to satisfy claims arising from his role in what the
government has called one of the biggest inside trading frauds in
history.
   Under the settlement between Wang and the Securities and Exchange
Commission, a court-appointed receiver will oversee and distribute
the money to cover claims by investors who said they lost money
because of Wang.
   The SEC also filed a complaint charging that Jerome B. Cronin,
also 24, of Chicago, allegedly traded in stocks of at least six
companies using tips provided by Wang, who was sentenced last
October to three years in jail.
   In a settlement with the SEC also approved Tuesday, Cronin agreed
to pay back $20,000 in illegal profits. He did not admit or deny
guilt.
   The SEC's civil complaint alleges that Cronin violated anti-fraud
provisions and received non-public information from Wang about
upcoming tender offers and other pending corporate action.
   The alleged illegal transactions occurred via telephone between
Wang in New York and Cronin in Chicago, who knew each other as
undergraduates at the University of Illinois, from July 1986 through
at least September 1987, according to the complaint.
   ``We're saying (Cronin) knew this was inside information,'' SEC
spokesman Chiles Larson said.
   Wang, then a junior analyst with the prestigious investment firm
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., pleaded guilty to conspiring with Taiwanese
businessman Fred C. Lee to profit in the stock market on secrets
about pending corporate takeovers. The SEC said Lee made about $19
million in illicit profits and paid Wang $200,000.
   At the time, Wang also pleaded guilty to a separate, smaller
insider trading scheme with an another party, now identified as
Cronin.
   The SEC complaint states that Cronin made at least $30,000 from
the information and paid Wang $4,000.
   Cronin allegedly traded in the securities of at least six
publicly held companies: Lehigh Press Inc., Utah Power &amp; Light Co.,
Rexnord Inc., Colt Industries Inc., Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc.,
and Burlington Industries Inc.
   The charges against Wang were first disclosed last June.
   At the time, the amount of allegedly illicit profits and the
government's requested penalties, totaling $76 million, made it the
second-largest securities fraud case behind the $100 million in
illicit profits and penalties surrendered by jailed speculator Ivan
Boesky in 1986.
   The Wang case was considered important because much of the
activity came during the height of publicity surrounding Boesky.
   In December, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. agreed to plead guilty
to six felonies and pay a record $650 million in fines in the
largest securities fraud case on record.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BPIdentity     01-31 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BP Identity,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>BP Seeks Stronger Corporate Identity In U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BP America Inc. said Tuesday it is changing the
name of its 7,400 U.S. service stations to ``BP'' by 1991 to better
reflect its status as the largest producer of U.S. crude oil.
   The U.S. subsidiary of the London-based British Petroleum PLC now
operates retail stations in 26 states under Sohio, Boron, Gulf and
BP logos.
   ``I think BP is in many ways the invisible giant of corporate
America,'' said James H. Ross, BP America president and chief
executive officer.
   ``We are the major player in U.S. upstream oil, one of the most
successful and innovative oil companies here and indeed worldwide.
We are far bigger than houshold names in Ohio like TRW, Goodrich and
Sherwin-Williams,'' he said.
   ``Upstream'' refers to the exploration and production side of the
oil business, in contrast with ``downstream'' operations, which
refer to refining and marketing.
   Ross said BP America also has changed the names of its U.S.
exploration, refining and marketing and chemicals businesses to
reflect the BP label.
   BP America operates about 750 service stations in the Northeast
which are identified by the BP logo, with its green shield and two
bright yellow letters. In addition, it has 1,100 Sohio stations in
Ohio, 600 Boron stations in Michigan and western Pennsylvania, and
5,000 Gulf stations in the Southeast. BP America acquired the Gulf
stations from Chevron Corp. in 1985 after Chevron purchased Gulf
Corp. and sold assets to avoid antitrust problems. It also recently
acquired Mobil stations in three West Coast states that will convert
to the BP brand.
   BP America said it plans to redesign some of the service stations
according to a new format.
   Ross said the company ``conducted extensive research, both
nationally and internationally,'' before deciding to unify its
businesses under one name.
   He said use of the name ``BP'' in the United States would provide
the company with a ``consistent identity.''
   BP America, based in Cleveland, moved its headquarters from New
York after the company purchased controlling interest in
Cleveland-based Standard Oil in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
