<DOCNO> AP890131-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     01-31 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribune Co. Reports 67 Percent Jump In 4th Quarter Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribune Co. reported Tuesday its fourth-quarter
profit increased 46 percent, sparked by improved newspaper and
newsprint results and a lower income tax rate.
   Net income for the last three months of 1988 amounted to $62.9
million, or 84 cents a share, compared to $43.2 million, or 56 cents
a share, for the fourth quarter a year earlier, the company, which
publishes the Chicago Tribune, said in a statement.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 8 percent to $625 million from $581
million in 1987.
   For the full year, net income rose 49 percent to $210.4 million,
or $2.78 a share, up from $141.5 million, or $1.80 a share, for 1987.
   Full-year revenue rose 9 percent to $2.33 billion from $2.15
billion a year earlier.
   The 1987 results included pre-tax charges of $21.7 million for
the fourth quarter and $40.1 million for the year relating to
employee severance charges at the New York Daily News, the Tribune
said. Excluding those charges, net income per share increased 18
percent for the fourth quarter and 34 per cent for the year.
   The 1988 improvement reflected record operating profits and a
reduction in the effective tax rate, the company said.
   Operating profit for the company's newspaper business rose 58
percent to $92.4 million as revenue rose 6 percent to $422 million
in the fourth quarter. For the year, the newspaper oprating profit
was $263.7 million, up 37 percent, while revenue rose 7 percent to
$1.6 billion.
   Weakness in the national spot advertising market led to a 3
percent decline in television revenue for its broadcasting and
entertainment group, which operates WGN-TV in Chicago, the company
said. The group's operating profit for the fourth quarter was $16
million, down 4 percent from 1987, as revenue fell 1 percent to $126
million.
   For the year, the broadcasting and entertainment group's
operating profit rose 24 percent to $77.8 million as revenue rose 4
percent to $506 million.
</TEXT>
