<HEAD>Texas Eastern Says Several Firms Showing Interest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf with closing stock price; PICKS UP 11th graf
pvs, `Before Coastal...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp. urged its stockholders in
full-page advertisements in major newspapers Tuesday not to sell
their shares to Coastal Corp., which has mounted a $2.6 billion
takeover bid.
   In addition, several companies that may be interested in making a
competing offer for Texas Eastern have been reviewing the natural
gas company's data.
   Texas Eastern's board of directors on Sunday rejected Coastal's
$42-a-share bid.
   ``Coastal's offer of $42 per share is inadequate. Therefore: Do
not be stampeded into any hasty decision,'' the ads in the Houston
Chronicle, The Houston Post and the Wall Street Journal state.
   Texas Eastern spokesman Fred Wichlep declined to comment on the
number of firms that have reviewed the Texas Eastern data.
   ``All I can tell you is that the data rooms were open on
Saturday, Sunday and Monday, and we have had people in them every
day,'' Wichlep said Monday.
   Texas Eastern, a Houston-based natural gas transmission company,
said last week it planned to contact about 50 companies it believed
may be interested in making a competing offer to the bid by
Houston-based Coastal.
   Wichlep said no special efforts are being used to screen
potential competing bidders. Each company, however, is required to
sign a confidentiality agreement.
   Industry sources have identified British Gas, Elf Aquitaine and
Houston-based Enron Corp., which operates the nation's largest
natural gas transmission system, as three companies that have made
trips to the Texas Eastern data rooms.
   Texas Eastern closed at $48.25, up 25 cents, in New York Stock
Exchange trading Tuesday.
   Before Coastal disclosed its tender offer, Texas Eastern stock
was trading for about $30 a share.
   Coastal President James R. Paul has described Texas Eastern's
search for a competing bidder as an effort to stall Coastal's offer
and a waste of stockholders' money. Coastal's offer is to expire
Feb. 13.
