<DOCNO> AP890131-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OverseasDealers     01-31 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Overseas Dealers,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Halfway Around the World Dealers Came to See What's New</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car dealers from both sides of the world have
some straightforward advice for their U.S. friends _ learn how to
sell used cars.
   More than 100 auto dealers and manufacturers representatives from
16 foreign countries were among thousands of U.S. automobile dealers
who attended the 72nd annual convention of the National Automobile
Dealers Association, which ended Tuesday.
   Visiting dealers from Australia and England, with almost the same
words, said they were struck by how little attention U.S. dealers
paid to selling cars that have some miles on them.
   ``You have no idea how to sell a used car,'' said Bruce White, a
Nissan dealer from Melbourne, Australia. ``I think we can teach the
Americans how to sell them.''
   ``I think we can sell a used car better than you can,'' said
Ashley Winter, a Ford dealer from Newcastle, England.
   In separate interviews, White and Winter said used-car sales make
up half or more of their dealership volumes, and speculated that the
difference may be because U.S. drivers don't treat their cars as
well.
   NADA figures show that used-car sales accounted for 6.3 percent
of all vehicle sales in the United States in 1987, the latest year
for which figures are available.
   Two U.S. auto dealers said the proliferation of used-car auction
houses and used-car businesses not affiliated with a franchised
operation is probably the reason.
   John Bayer of Dudley, Mass., who sells Pontiac, Cadillac and
Oldsmobile cars, said there was discussion at the NADA convention
about preparing a car for resale.
   Bayer and Steve Grindstaff, owner of Grindstaff Chevrolet in
Elizabethton, Tenn., said in interviews that the condition of a
trade-in is a major consideration of whether the car is kept on the
dealer's used-car lot or sold elsewhere.
   Prices also are a big difference in cars sold in the United
States and overseas, the dealers said. Governmental regulations and
duties jack up the prices of cars in Australia sometimes by 100
percent, White said.
   He added the regulations also make some vehicles too expensive
for him and his fellow dealers to handle.
   ``We'd love to have these vans,'' White said after seeing some of
the customized van conversion displays on the NADA show floor. ``But
you can't get them in.''
</TEXT>
