<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NewConstruction     01-31 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Construction,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contracting For New Construction Rebounds 8 Percent In December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction rebounded 8
percent in December, marking a departure from the general
sluggishness of 1988, according to a report Tuesday.
   ``Despite its strong finish, 1988 was a year of generally
softening construction activity, as the value of all newly started
work fell 2 percent short of the 1987 peak,'' George A. Christie,
vice president and chief economist of F.W. Dodge Group, said in a
statement.
   Christie said the 1988 decline ended a five-year period of
continuously expanding construction contracting. He predicted the
market would decline again this year.
   The big factors in the drop were overbuilt commercial properties
and limited public funding, according to F.W. Dodge, a unit of
McGraw-Hill Inc. An additional factor this year is higher interest
rates, Christie said.
   Construction of highways and other public works projects
contributed to an 18 percent increase in the non-building category
in December over November. For the year, the category fell 1 percent
from 1987.
   Residential building rose 7 percent in December but was about
even for the year.
   Contracting for non-residential buildings rose 4 percent in
December but was down 5 percent for the year.
   By region, contracting fell 4 percent in the Northeast, held even
in the North Central region, fell 4 percent in the South and rose 2
percent in the West, F.W. Dodge said.
</TEXT>
