<FIRST>u f AM-BassProfile     01-31 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bass Profile,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robert Bass Busiest Of Wealthy Brothers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Houghton Mifflin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The billionaire Bass brothers are often
described as classic passive investors, but their business ventures
have kept them among the nation's 400 richest people.
   The Bass dynasty traces its roots to the forays of wildcatter Sid
Richardson, who made a series of successful oil strikes in West
Texas. Upon his death in 1959, he willed most of his money to his
partner and nephew, Perry Bass.
   After vastly expanding Richardson's holdings, Perry retired in
the late 1960s and left the family empire to his four sons, who each
inherited $2.8 million. They combined assets to form Bass Brothers
Enterprises, which was managed by eldest son, Sid Bass.
   With bold moves from the oil patch into stocks and real estate,
the brothers added to their collective and individual fortunes.
   Among their most lucrative ventures, the Basses netted an $850
million capital gain after helping to thwart a 1985 takeover fight
for Walt Disney Co. Also that year, the family liquidated Bass
Brothers Enterprises, its primary investment vehicle, and divided
the assets four ways, freeing the brothers to cut some individual
deals.
   Since then, Robert Bass has focused much of his energy on the
information sector. In 1985, he led a group that made a $205 million
investment in Cincinnati-based Taft Broadcasting Co. that was worth
$718 million two years later. He and two other shareholders divided
Taft's assets, with the Bass group getting $157.5 million in cash, a
television station in Columbus, Ohio, and two large cable television
properties.
   In 1988, Robert Bass was instrumental in prying away the Westin
hotel chain from Allegis Corp. for $1.53 billion. In March, he sold
the Plaza Hotel in Manhattan to fellow billionaire Donald J. Trump
for $410 million.
   Last May 17, he reached an agreement to purchase Bell &amp; Howell
Co., a publishing information services company in Skokie, Ill.
   On the same day, a group that he led proposed to buy Macmillan
Inc. The move put the publishing giant in play and it was acquired
last fall by British publisher Robert Maxwell for $2.5 billion and
gave the Bass Group a gain of about $75 million on its holdings
before expenses.
   Most recently, the Bass Group put up $350 million for the bailout
of insolvent American Savings and Loan Association of California, a
subsidiary of Financial Corp. of America.
   The brothers zealously guard their privacy, persistently refusing
interviews and shunning transactions that would require much
financial disclosure.
   They have been described as atypical Texas tycoons with their
conservative style and reserved manner. In Fort Worth, they are
universally revered for their civic investments.
   Sid is director of the generous Sid Richardson Foundation. Ed
often described as the family maverick, has been more interested in
arts and environmental projects. Lee is working with Sid, while
Robert has taken an interest in some political projects.
   ``The big difference in the Basses _ and most people like the
Basses _ is that they're really not looking for any credit for what
they do. They do it because they think it's what they should do and
what's good,'' said Dee Kelly, a Fort Worth lawyer and longtime
family friend.
   Despite their financial muscle, the Basses aren't the
strong-arming type, preferring to work with the management of target
companies, as they did in the Disney situation, Checchi noted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ForeignInvestment-Forecast     01-31 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Investment-Forecast,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Investment in U.S. Setting New Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign investment in the United States, which
soared to a record of $58.1 billion reported in 1987, is set to go
even higher for 1988 according to Richard Apcar, director of
investment analysis at the Commerce Department.
   ``How much the increase will be depends on the data we're still
collecting for the last few months of the year,'' he said in an
interview Tuesday.
   ``It was about $30 billion for the first half of 1988, and I'd
guess about $20 billion for the first half of 1987.''
   Actual investment figures are much larger. For more than half the
deals reported the department could not find any figure at all.
   The biggest takeover in 1988 was the acquisition of Federated
Department Stores, the fifth largest U.S. retailer, by Campeau Corp.
of Toronto, Canada. That was about $6.6 billion.
   In 1987 British Petroleum Co. spent nearly $8 billion for the 45
percent of Standard Oil Co. that it did not already own. That put
the total of British acquisitions for the year at $21.2 billion.
Figures were identified for only 117 of the 249 transactiona.
   As has been the case for the past three years, Japan was the most
active investor with 490 separate deals. Of these, 235 carried
idenifiable prices totalling 13 billion.
   ``While Japan will continue to be the source for most Asian
investments for the foreseeable future, it is interesting to note
that other Asian-Pacific investors, especially from Australia and
New Zealand, have increased their activity here -- the number of
transactions doubled and the value quadrupled in 1987,'' said the
Commerce Department's report.
   It was issued last Friday.
   ``Foreign investment makes an important contribution to the U.S.
economy,'' Michael Boskin, named by President George Bush as his top
economic adviser, said last week.
   ``By helping to build productive plant and equipment in the
United States, foreign investment contributes to current and future
increases in jobs, productivity and growth...
   ``Concerns about foreign ownership are somewhat exaggerated. By
the end of 1987, measured net foreign assets in the United States
amounted to some 3.1 percent of U.S. netwealth on an historical cost
basis.''
   The Commerce Department's report said the trend toward the growth
of foreign investment began in 1983, with the recovery from the
recession of the previous two years. The total number of deals had
peaked at about 1,200 in 1981 and then dropped sharply. In 1987 the
total was 1,328, with values reported for 588 of them. That was an
increase of 26 percent over the year before.
   The report attributed the big rise since 1983 to:
   _The drop in the international price of the dollar after 1985,
which made it cheaper for foreigners to buy in this country
   _Eagerness by many American firms to become more profitable and
avoid takeovers by getting rid of divisions and subsidiaries they no
longer wanted
   _Tthe belief by foreign investors that they must invest in the
world's largest consumer market in order to stay competiive in the
world.
   Boskin said that although the United States has become a debtor
country -- with larger assets owned here by foreigners than
Americans own in other countries -- U.S. direct investment in actual
property and equipment remains greater than foreign direct
investment in the United States. The figures are reversed when
indirect investments such as stocks and bonds are tasken into
account.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
