<FIRST>u f AM-GMBiasSuit     01-31 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM Bias Suit,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM, Bias Plaintiffs Announce Preliminary Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. and lawyers representing
thousands of black employees in Michigan, Ohio and Indiana announced
Tuesday they had tentatively settled a bias suit against the
automaker that could give the plaintiffs payments totaling $3
million.
   The two sides agreed upon a proposed consent decree to end the
case, but GM did not admit it had discriminated against blacks in
promotions and pay raises, company spokeswoman Patricia J. Molloy
said.
   The proposal provides for distribution of $1.6 million to about
2,800 former GM employees, and raises averaging $1,000 a year for
about 1,000 current employees, plaintiffs' attorney Dennis D. James
said.
   James told a news conference the proposed decree also requires
five years of monitoring to ensure that black salaried employees get
their fair share of promotions and pay increases.
   Sheldon Miller, another attorney for the plaintiffs, said the
tentative agreement ``reaffirms the importance of class-action civil
rights litigation, especially in the current unfriendly political
climate towards civil rights in general.''
   The suit, filed in 1983 by four employees, was a class action on
behalf of 10,000 salaried black employees who worked for GM between
1982 and 1986 in Michigan, Indiana and Ohio.
   Those states were chosen for the suit because GM employees there
made a manageable-sized group for the legal action, and because GM
plants and offices in those states account for 75 percent of the
company's salaried employees, James said.
   Members of the class will be notified of the proposed agreement
over the next two weeks and be given a chance to lodge any
objections they may have. U.S. District Judge John Feikens then will
schedule a hearing on whether the decree should be approved, James
said.
   The decree was submitted to Feikens about two weeks ago and
Feikens gave his preliminary approval Tuesday, James said.
   ``This will help blacks to achieve a more equitable position in
upper management and also middle management,'' said the Rev. James
Kennedy, one of the four original plaintiffs.
   Kennedy, now pastor of Mount Carmel Baptist Church in Flint, was
employed at GM's AC sparkplug subsidiary in Flint.
   He told the news conference that after starting in 1956, he
worked his way up from janitor to supervisor of warehousing and
shipping at the AC plant, but found that whites had better paychecks
and higher job expectations.
   Also present were two other original plaintiffs, Larry Dodson,
sales engineer at GM's Allison Transmission subsidiary in
Indianapolis, and Larry Kitchen, an employee of GM's
Chevrolet-Pontiac-GM of Canada group in Detroit, who both reported
similar experiences.
   The fourth plaintiff, Dennis Huguley, formerly on GM's design
staff in Warren, Mich., left GM for a job with Mercedes Benz of
North America in Charlotte, N.C., James said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
