<FIRST>u f AM-GAFTrial     01-31 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Trial,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>2nd GAF Trial Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second trial of GAF Corp. on stock
manipulation charges opened in federal court in Manhattan Tuesday.
   ``This is a case about cheating in the stock market,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney Carl Lowenson Jr. told the jury picked for the second
trial.
   GAF, a major manufacturer of specialty chemicals and building
materials, and its vice chairman, James T. Sherwin, were indicted
last July for allegedly manipulating the stock of Union Carbide
Corp. in 1986. They were accused of improperly trying to inflate the
price of Union Carbide stock to enhance the value of GAF's holdings
in the corporation.
   GAF attorney Arthur Liman countered Tuesday that a government
probe had uncovered ``no smoking gun'' to link the defendants to the
stock manipulations of Boyd Jefferies, onetime head of a Los
Angeles-based trading firm.
   Jefferies, who struck a plea bargain with prosecutors after being
implicated in the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal, testified for
the government at the first trial, which began in December.
   U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe declared a mistrial in that
proceeding Jan. 10 because of an error by Lowenson, who failed to
reveal a report that concluded a key piece of evidence had been
altered.
   The second trial was convened after U.S. Supreme Court Justice
Thurgood Marshall refused to continue a delay requested by the
defense, which claimed a second trial would violate the defendants'
right to avoid double jeopardy.
</TEXT>
