<DOCNO> AP890131-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Centaur-Pennwalt     01-31 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Centaur-Pennwalt,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centaur Demands Special Meeting Of Pennwalt Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centaur Partners, stymied in its $765 million
effort to buy Pennwalt Corp., said Tuesday that holders of more than
34 percent of Pennwalt's stock have called for a shareholders
meeting, at which Centaur hoped to replace the chemical company's
board.
   Centaur said it had delivered to Pennwalt proxies from
shareholders owning approximately 34.6 percent of Pennwalt's
outstanding stock. Under Pennsylvania law, a special meeting must be
called if one is requested by the holders of at least 20 percent of
a company's outstanding voting stock.
   State law requires the company to call the meeting within two
months of the request, Centaur said.
   Pennwalt officials said they were ``in the process of reviewing
the demands to determine whether they have been submitted by the
requisite shareholders and whether they are in a form that would be
effective.''
   At the meeting, Centaur said, Pennwalt shareholders would be
asked to remove the directors, reduce the board from 11 to five
members and eliminate the requirement that directors also be
shareholders.
   In addition, the shareholders would be asked to elect five new
directors proposed by Centaur.
   Candidates nominated by Centaur would likely be more sympathetic
to the partnership's offer.
   Centaur, whoise principals are New York financiers Abbey J.
Butler and Melvyn J. Estrin, launched a $100-a-share bid in
mid-December for the 6.98 million shares of common stock it did not
own. At the time, the group owned about 12.7 percent of Pennwalt's
shares.
   In an effort to thwart the bid, Pennwalt spent $403.8 million to
buy 4.75 million shares, or about 40 percent of those outstanding.
   Pennwalt stock closed Tuesday at $106 a share, up 25 cents in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Pennwalt is fighting the Centaur bid in court, claiming
disclosures made by the group in its tender offer and the
solicitation of proxies from Pennwalt's shareholders were false and
misleading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
