<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GenentechSuit     01-31 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Genentech Suit,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Genentech Won't Appeal British Patent Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Genentech Inc. has decided not
to appeal a British ruling that denied the company exclusive
marketing rights in England to a drug used to fight heart attacks.
   The company said Tuesday ``the doctrines applied in the British
case will have no relevance in U.S. patent cases.''
   Genentech had fought in the British courts against Wellcome PLC
over the British patent for recombinant tissue plasminogen
activator, or TPA. The drug, marketed by Genentech in North America
under the name Activase, is used to dissolve blod clots that cause
heart attacks.
   England's High Court ruled in July against Genentech's unusual
claim to have patented the drug itself.
   In the past, companies have generally been allowed to patent only
the lab process for making genetically-engineered drugs, because the
drugs themselves are found in nature.
   Genentech originally said it would appeal the British ruling.
   TPA has yet to be approved by the federal Food and Drug
Administration for sale in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
