<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   01-31 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stocks Fall in Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei closing, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar maintained its strength against the
Japanese yen Wednesday while share prices plunged, discouraged by
the yen's weakness, dealers said.
   The dollar, which opened at 130.58 yen, up a strong 1.45 yen from
Tuesday's 129.13-yen finish, moved mainly between 130.30-.67 during
the early session. It was changing hands at a slightly lower 130.32
yen shortly after midmorning.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 13.80-point loser Tuesday, shed another 102.44
points, or 0.32 percent, to end the morning session at 31,478.86.
   Currency dealers said the strong dollar opening in Tokyo followed
an overnight surge in New York which was prompted by comments from
U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan who said current
exchange rates were tolerable.
   Testifying before a joint economic committee of Congress,
Greenspan said U.S. industry is competitive enough at the present
dollar rate. He added that the current rate of inflation is too high
and he expects a substantial cut in the U.S. trade deficit.
   Dealers said the absence of central bank intervention also fueled
the dollar's jump.
   On the stock exchange, the market's main economic barometer fell
as investors, discouraged by the dollar's rally, started selling
issues, said an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage firm.
   Some participants remained on the sidelines, he added, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   ``There is no sign of the yen's recovery at the moment, but I
believe investors' purchasing power is still strong,'' the analyst
said.
</TEXT>
