<FIRST>r f BC-IllinoisCentral-ADM     01-31 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Illinois Central-ADM,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archer Daniels Midland Seeks 1 Million New Illinois Central Railroad
Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archer Daniels Midland Co. has told federal
officials it wants to increase its stake in Illinois Central
Transportation Co., the target of a $440 million takeover bid,
authorities said.
   Archer Daniels, the Decatur, Ill.-based grain processor, already
owns about 2 million shares of Illinois Central and is seeking
approval to buy another 1 million shares, officials said Monday.
   On Friday, Prospect Group, which operates in the railroad,
insurance, and consumer products and services businesses, began a
$440 million tender offer for Illinois Central Transportation Co.,
less than a month after the railroad was spun off by Whitman Corp.
   Analysts generally believe Archer Daniels is trying to protect
its own interests through the stock purchases. Archer Daniels's
holdings already amount to 9.8 percent of the railroad, but the
grain processor also is one of Illinois Central's largest shippers.
   Archer Daniels said in a filing Monday with the Securities and
Exchange Commission it has notified the Federal Trade Commission of
its desire to increase its holding of common stock in Illinois
Central to no more than 25 percent.
   Archer Daniels has until Feb. 27 to buy the shares, provided the
government approves the purchase.
   The drought last summer made Archer Daniels more dependent than
usual on Illinois Central's freight lines because barge traffic was
slowed or blocked by low river water levels.
</TEXT>
