<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Allied-Signal     01-31 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Allied-Signal,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allied Signal Reports Drop In Fourth-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied-Signal Inc. said Tuesday its
fourth-quarter earnings dropped 24 percent from a year earlier, when
income was boosted by a one-time tax benefit.
   Allied-Signal said it earned $104 million, or 70 cents per share,
in the last quarter of 1988, down from $136 million, or 88 cents per
share, in the same period of 1987.
   In the year-earlier period, Allied had a gain of $59 million due
to a one-time tax benefit.
   Sales for the fourth quarter rose to nearly $3.01 billion from
$2.95 billion in the final quarter of 1987.
   For all of 1988, the company reported net income of $463 million,
or $3.10 per share. In 1987, the company had net income of $656
million, or $3.90 per share.
   Sales for 1988 totaled $11.91 billion, up from $11.12 billion.
   The 1987 earnings included net gains of $125 million from the
company's sales of its interest in Henley Group and the issuance of
common stock by its former Union Texas Petroleum subsidiary.
   ``Our core businesses remain strong,'' said Edward L. Hennessy,
chairman and chief executive officer of Allied-Signal.
   Allied-Signal is involved in the aerospace, automotive products
and engineered materials industries.
</TEXT>
