<DOCNO> AP890131-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 2322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru   01-31 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new to update, picks up into 2nd graf previous ``Things
are''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks and savings institutions were braced
Tuesday for a possible proposal from the Bush administration to
raise their insurance premiums as a way to rescue the government
fund that insures savings and loan associations.
   A White House official said Tuesday night the prevailing thought
in the administration is that such an approach ``is one of the more
attractive'' solutions.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity said that
increased risk for the insurer should translate into higher premiums
for the institutions.
   White House officials were convened in a meeting late Tuesday by
chief of staff John Sununu in a meeting that focused on what
recommendations to make to Bush on the S&amp;L situation.
   `Things are a little scary to us,'' said Kenneth A. Guenther,
executive vice president of the Independent Bankers Association of
America.
   Guenther said he interpreted comments over the weekend by Sununu
as indicating the administration was backing away from its
controversial suggestion that depositors pay a fee of about 25 cents
on every $100 in their accounts.
   Meanwhile, several members of the Senate Banking Committee called
for a quick infusion of $2 billion into the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp. so that regulators could liquidate more insolvent
S&amp;Ls while Congress debates proposed reforms.
   Sununu, responding to questions in a Sunday television interview,
had defended the deposit fee idea as if he were talking about an
increase in the premium that institutions have been paying since
1934.
   He ``seemed to be moving away from a deposit fee to an increase
in banks' premiums,'' Guenther said in an interview.
   Senior administration officials are saying they will urge
President Bush to propose a premium hike rather than a fee aid by
depositors, according to Tuesday's editions of The New York Times,
which cited unidentified sources, and NBC News.
   Bush intends to present at least an outline of his S&amp;L plan when
he addresses Congress on Feb. 9. So far he has indicated no
preference among the many options.
   ``If I were to make a prediction, my guess is those premiums are
going up,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``Somebody's going to end
up having to pay them. My guess is it will probably be the
institutions, but the depositors will pay them indirectly.
   ``We'll bury this (deposit fee) proposal on the one hand and dig
it up through another hole,'' he said.
   The administration has told members of Congress it likely will
propose selling bonds for about $45 billion. The difficulty comes in
raising the $7 billion to $9 billion needed each year to pay off the
bonds.
   The S&amp;L industry and many members of Congress advocate using tax
money, an alternative the Bush administration is trying to avoid.
   Guenther said an increase in premiums for both banks and S&amp;Ls
would be unfair because about two-thirds of the money generated for
S&amp;Ls would come from banks.
   He estimated that a 25-cent increase in banks' 8.3-cent premium
would push as many as 750 profitable banks into the red. To the
extent that banks and S&amp;Ls pass on the cost to their customers
through lower interest rates on deposits, it would encourage
depositors to put their money in uninsured money market mutual funds
offered by brokerage firms, he said.
   The U.S. League of Savings Institutions, the largest S&amp;L trade
association, has said it cannot pay more toward the FSLIC's problems
and at the same time raise more capital from investors as a buffer
between losses and insured deposits.
   At the congressional hearings, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
noting an estimate that insolvent S&amp;Ls are losing $1 billion a
month, said Congress should give regulators about $2 billion
immediately so they can liquidate some institutions rather than
rescuing them with promissory notes and loss guarantees.
   ``I have to believe that an immediate infusion of about $2
billion for the next six months or so would save us money in the
long run,'' he said.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., agreed, saying, ``It's probably
going to be six, seven, eight months at best'' until Congress acts
on a reform package.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., while not specifically backing
Dodd's proposal, said, ``I think we have to consider acting more
rapidly.''
   The committee chairman, Sen. Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich., is
against spending any money on the problem without tying it to
reforms needed to prevent the problem from reoccurring. But he said
regulators were free to ask Congress for more money.
   William Fulwider, a spokesman for the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board, said the agency would wait until the Bush administration
presented its proposal before deciding whether to ask Congress for
interim financing.
   The bank board has already advocated that Congress allow it to
speed up the sale of the remaining $5 billion in previously
authorized bonds rather than spread the borrowing through 1990, as
now required.
</TEXT>
