<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Drugs     01-31 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Drugs,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Rise in Double Digits at Warner-Lambert, Schering-Plough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Schering-Plough Corp. said Tuesday its fourth-quarter earnings
rose 24 percent and attributed the rise to strong performances in
international sales.
   Another big drug and consumer products company, Warner-Lambert
Co., also cited sales gains in reporting its earnings for the same
period jumped 17 percent.
   Schering-Plough, based in Madison, N.J., said it earned $92.9
million, or 83 cents per share, in the final quarter of 1988, up
from $75.2 million, or 67 cents per share, in the same period a year
earlier.
   Sales for the fourth quarter totaled $739.9 million, a 12 percent
rise over $663.5 million the year before.
   Robert P. Luciano, chairman and chief executive officer, said
international sales turned in an ``exceptional'' performance during
the quarter.
   Warner-Lambert, headquartered in Morris Plains, N.J., said it
earned $77.5 million, or $1.14 per share, in the fourth quarter, up
from $66.3 million, or 95 cents per share, in the same period of
1987.
   Sales increased 11 percent to $997.9 million from $899 million.
   Joseph D. Williams, Warner-Lambert's chairman and chief executive
officer, attributed the performance to strong sales in the United
States and abroad.
   For all of 1988, Schering-Plough reported earnings of $389.8
million, or $3.48 per share, up 23.2 percent from $316.4 million, or
$2.73 per share, during 1987.
   Sales in 1988 were $2.97 billion, a 10 percent rise over the $2.7
billion reported in 1987.
   Warner-Lambert said it earned $340.3 million, or $5 per share,
during 1988, up 15 percent from $295.8 million, or $4.15 per share,
in 1987.
   Sales increased 14 percent to $3.91 billion from $3.44 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
